text: and he is off immediately, opening the face on a length-ball awayswinger. Gets a single to deep point
there is swing and good carry, but it has been called a wide after Kohli leaves it alone. Just does too much
preText:
8.01pm The two umpires finally emerge. Deepak Chahar has the new ball in hand. Let there be swing. One slip in lace. Third is inside the circle

8pm Let the IPL 2024 begin. Virat Kohli and Faf du Plessis to open the innings for RCB. The fielders are ready and in position, but we don't have any umpires

7.50pm Now for the teams.

Royal Challengers Bengaluru F du Plessis*, V Kohli, RM Patidar, GJ Maxwell, C Green, KD Karthik†, Anuj Rawat, KV Sharma, AS Joseph, MJ Dagar, Mohammed Siraj

Impact: Dayal, Akash, Prabhudessai, Swapnil, Vyshak

Chennai Super Kings RD Gaikwad*, R Ravindra, AM Rahane, DJ Mitchell, RA Jadeja, Sameer Rizvi, MS Dhoni†, DL Chahar, M Theekshana, TU Deshpande, Mustafizur Rahman

Impact: Thakur, Dube, Rasheed, Sindhu, Moeen

7.40pm Faf du Plessis has won the toss, and RCB are batting first. "Generally it is always a bat-first wicket," says du Plessis, who knows the ground well as a former CSK player.

Gaikwad says he came to know he would be the captain a week ago. CSK's four overseas players are Rachin Ravindra, Daryl Mitchell, Maheesh Theekshana and Mustafizur Rahamn. He also says Sameer Rizvi is making his debut.

7.35pm Conditions report time. Brian Lara says there are a few cracks, and there is some looseness on the edges of the crack. Lara feels spin is going to play a part. I think they are playing on the centre strip because there is no one boundary that is bigger. Lara still feels you bowl first despite the expectation of spin because you want to protect them from the dew.

7.30pm The toss has been delayed to 7.40pm even though the captains have been out and ready. The start time stays at 8pm.

Deivarayan Mathu has seen Alzarri Joseph mark his run-up. Like Faf du Plessis, Joseph is also a Super Kings man, who unfortunately will play against them in the IPL. Deivarayan points out how du Plessis has liked to play Joseph both for St Lucia Kings and Joburg Super Kings.

7.25pm All eyes on two men who haven't played in a while. Virat Kohli more so because not just RCB fans but also India fans want to see how he responds to the latest demands the India team seems to have made of him in T20 cricket. And MS Dhoni of course, who has again found a way to surprise people after all these years.

7.20pm I am sure you have heard about it, but this is worth checking out again. Ask Star on ESPNcricinfo: Got a question for the Star Sports commentators about this match? Want to ask Navjot Sidhu, Ambati Rayudu or Harbhajan Singh about anything cricket? Go to the ESPNcricinfo homepage on the mobile site, click on the Ask Star button at the bottom of the screen, and send in your questions. They could get answered on TV.

7pm How ya doin'? Thanks Ashish. If I was in the Chennai crowd, I would carry a "Hinthi nahi ata saar" placard. Anyway, this too shall pass. A timely reminder that because of this ceremony, this match will start at 8pm. All other matches will sart at the usual time of 7.30pm. Toss in half an hour.

ShahSafeer: "People are here to see the start of another blockbuster season of IPL while I am here ro see Virat Kohli bat again. It seems like it's been ages since he last batted! "

Our hindi commentary is live as well, while Deiva has kicked off the live blog, too. And with that, please welcome Sidharth Monga in the comms seat.

Ask Star on ESPNcricinfo: Got a question for the Star Sports commentators about this match? Want to ask Navjot Sidhu, Ambati Rayudu or Harbhajan Singh about anything cricket? Go to the ESPNcricinfo homepage on the mobile site, click on the Ask Star button at the bottom of the screen, and send in your questions. They could get answered on TV.

Aaron: "RCB will be looking to groom Himanshu as their designated Leggie this season, would love to see him spin his magic wand in Chepauk!"

6.45pm The opening ceremony is underway. Bollywood actors Akshay Kumar and Tiger Shroff making their way to the stage. Meanwhile, I have just spotted two RCB jerseys amid the sea of yellow! While the celebs do their thing how about some light reading from Alagappan Muthu: ChatIPL - An AI-powered peek at the league that defies logic. There is a also a pretty fascinating interview with Daryl Mitchell from Deivarayan and Alagappan where he opens up on what it was travelling around with his dad, John Mitchell - a world-class rugby coach.

Soumya: "Better to error towards caution. RCB can go with Dagar, Karn and Lormor as 3 spinners apart from Maxi on this pitch. They have the pacers and batting to breach casa Chepauk."

6.30pm If you want to know what's it like at Chepauk right now, Deiva sets it up beautifully from the venue. "He has handed over captaincy to Gaikwad, but he's still Chennai's Thala. The chants of "Dhoni!Dhoni!Dhoni!" and the whistles for him are getting louder and louder. It looks very much like these 14 matches - 16 or 17 if luck is once again on his side - are very much the beginning of the end. At the same time, the crowd is warming up to the new captain Gaikwad. Once, another Gaikwad with Maharashtrian roots, a certain Shivaji Rao, went on to become a household name in Chennai. That's some way away, but for now Gaikwad has the keys to the Chennai kingdom. A huge replica of the IPL trophy now makes its way into the middle. The LED lights are also being tested out ahead of the opening ceremony, which will include performances of AR Rahman and Prabhu Deva."

6.25pm The last time CSK and RCB played the opening game of an IPL season, RCB were rolled over for 70, and it took CSK 17.4 overs to chase the target down. RCB will want to right that wrong. But can they? CSK have three spin options in Maheesh Theekshana, Ravindra Jadeja and part-timer Rachin Ravindra on what could be another slow pitch. In contrast, RCB don't have a world-class spinner in their ranks. Here's Deivarayan Muthu with the match preview.

Pawas: "The first true transitional season of IPL is about to kick off" Really feels that way, isn't? The first time ever in the IPL that none of Virat Kohli, Rohit Sharma or MS Dhoni will be leading a team.

6.10pm We are still close to two hours away from ball one, but Chepauk is already half full and it shouldn't take long for the stadium to be packed to the rafters. And make no mistake, it's going to be a sea of Yellow at the Chepauk. There will be an opening ceremony with all the glitz and glamour in full flow. Once the dust settles, RCB will try and get the better of CSK at a venue where they haven't had a lot of success. In fact, just once in nine attempts - that one coming way back in 2008. Can they change history?

Afeef: "And so begins another season of the IPL. Looking forward to a fantastic season. May or not be Dhoni's last, but we know he will get the loudest cheer everywhere he goes."

5.55pm There is a also a small matter of Virat Kohli returning to competitive cricket after close to two-and-a-half months having missed India's five-game Test series against England. His most recent game was a T20I against Afghanistan in mid-January. How he goes in Chennai will be interesting to see, especially with the T20 World Cup starting right after the IPL.

5.40pm Righto, where do we start. The latest captaincy change is a good place, I reckon. A day before the IPL begins, defending champions CSK have a new captain - Ruturaj Gaikwad. Yep. And as with most things with Dhoni: It happened quietly. A whisper into the ether. Just like it did in 2014. And then in 2020. The end of an era. MS Dhoni's last act as captain was lifting the IPL trophy. His most lasting act, subverting expectation. Here's Alagappan Muthu on how as a season begins, an era ends, but life goes on for Dhoni.

5.30pm IPL S17 E01. Ten months on since that crazy final in Ahmedabad which started on a Sunday and ended on a Tuesday, we are back it again. Ten venues. Ten teams. New captains. Comebacks. Fanwars. The carnival returns. Hello and welcome to the ball-by-ball commentary of match No. 1 of IPL 2024 - MS Dhoni Ruturaj Gaikwad-led CSK vs Faf du Plessis-led RCB. I am Ashish Pant nice and early and will soon be joined by Sidharth Monga with all that unfolds in Chennai. Join in, it's going to be a fun ride.

preText:
10.15pm Out come the two CSK openers, Rachin Ravindra and Ruturaj Gaikwad. Gaikwad taking strike. Yash Dayal is the impact sub for RCB, who has come in for Dinesh Karthik. Anuj Rawat has the gloves. Siraj has the ball. Over the wicket with a slip in place

10.10pm Thanks, Sidharth. Righto, this should be a good chase. A lot will depend on how CSK start. There will be a new opening pair this season with Devon Conway not around. RCB will be eying early strikes through Mohammed Siraj and Alzarri Joseph.

That's that! CSK's winning run against RCB at Fort Chepauk continues. There is a review, but more in desperation, I think. Aims for the yorker that hits Dube's pad and goes to the fine leg fence. Ball tracker confirms the ball pitched outside leg. Ruturaj Gaikwad has made a winning start to his captaincy tenure.
postText:
IPL 2024 gets off to a rousing start with CSK getting the better of RCB at Chepauk yet again. If you missed any of the action, Deiva's report will be in soon. That's it from us tonight. Thanks everyone for tuning in. It's a double-header tomorrow and we will be live nice and early to bring all the action. Till then, this is me Ashish signing off on behalf of Sidharth, Thilak and Chandan. Ciao!

Mustafizur Rahman is the player of the match for his 4 for 29.

CSK captain, Ruturaj Gaikwad: Total control right from the start. 2-3 overs here and there but once the spinners came on, we were in control. 10-15 runs lesser would have been great but they came back well. [Turning point?] To get Maxwell and even Faf out, the quick wickets were the turning point. Helps to control the next five-six overs. That was the main point. [Captaincy debut] I have always enjoyed it. Haven't felt the additional pressure, right from the state side. Not even a single time I felt pressurized by anything. Obviously had Mahi bhai with me. [On the chase] Everyone is a stroke-player in our side, even Jinx. There is role clarity in the batting unit. Helps a lot. Lots of positives, but two-three things to work on. The batting, everyone chipped in. If we had a few batters from the top-order batting through, the chase would have been easier.

Presentation time.

Some stat nuggets from Sampath:

- This is the 8th consecutive win for CSK vs RCB at Chepauk, the longest winning streak for any team against an opponent at a venue in IPL. Next best streak is for MI, who have won their last seven matches vs KKR at Wankhede.

- Ravindra Jadeja unbeaten in a successful IPL chase for the 27th time, joint-most by any batter, alongside MS Dhoni.

Amey: "Credit to Jadeja for playing only 2 dot balls and keeping the scoreboard moving, especially when Dube was struggling."

Afeef: "RCB needed a better plan than just bowling short balls. Alzarri could've been used better, I feel."

Rachin Ravindra: Pretty complete performance by us. We held our nerves. Batting with Jinx [Rahane] and Rutu, very calm heads. Lucky we had 4-5 days of good training. I find it easier going from red ball to white ball because I think the positions are the same, [Form] It's been good. The wickets were a bit different in training but I backed myself in the game. The experience of the amazing crowd was great. Helps a lot.

Faf du Plessis: You have to get ahead in the first six overs. Chennai squeeze you with their spinners. We lost too many wickets in the first six overs. We were 15-20 runs short on a pitch that wasn't as bad as we played in the first ten overs We were always a little bit behind trying to get ahead of the game. They were always ahead of the game. [Short ball plan] Dube wasn't comfortable with the short ball, we were trying to get a few wickets in the middle overs. But didn't happen. [Batting first] If you look at the stats, it is very in favour of batting first. It looked a bit on the drier side. The spinners, in the second innings, the ball started to grip a bit. We backed our seamers against Dube. But batting first was the right decision. [On DK and Rawat] Really good for Dinesh setting up the season for someone who hasn't really played a lot of cricket in the last year. Really important knock for himself. Rawat showed some really promise even last year. He showed composure.

11.55pmAnd the wait continues. That is eight wins on the bounce for CSK against RCB at Chepauk. And a clinical win it was to kick-off IPL 2024. It was Rachin Ravindra, on IPL debut, who gave the chase a flying start with a 15-ball 37. Rahane also did his bit scoring a quick 27. RCB did come back into the game with a few quick wickets as they adopted the short ball plan. But I felt they over-did it. Dube was clearly struggling initially, but once he survived, run-scoring was easy. Jadeja did his bit in rotating the strike, and eventually CSK got home with eight balls to spare. While RCB's middle order collapsed, CSK had all their batters contributing. And that was the difference between the two teams.

preText:
3.30pm A slip and a short third for Warner. Here we go

3.28pm David Warner and Mitchell Marsh walk out to open for DC. Looks like Sam Curran will take the new ball.

3.20pm TIL: Former India legspinner Sairaj Bahutule was the friend of the son of ghazal singers Jagjit Singh and Chitra Singh. Vivek Singh lost his life in a car accident, and Bahutule was in the car when it happened. It was such a tragic incident for the family who were never the same again.

Bahutule survived but sustained multiple fractures. He is now a coach at NCA, and his experience of coming back from that trauma has helped Rishabh Pant in his recovery. That, and more in Nagraj Gollapudi's piece tracking this Pant comeback. It is so life-affirming that Pant has made it back, and that he has done so not by targeting the comeback but by enjoying small little things on the way back.

3.10pm

Delhi Capitals MR Marsh, DA Warner, SD Hope, RR Pant*†, T Stubbs, AR Patel, Sumit Kumar, Kuldeep Yadav, RK Bhui, KK Ahmed, I Sharma

Punjab Kings S Dhawan*, JM Bairstow, LS Livingstone, JM Sharma†, SM Curran, HV Patel, Harpreet Brar, Shashank Singh, K Rabada, RD Chahar, Arshdeep Singh

So Anrich Nortje is still not fit. What a blow it has been for DC.

3.02pm Home captain Shikhar Dhawan has won the toss, and PBKS will field first. The main reason for this is because they are not quite sure what to expect from the new ground. Livingstone, Bairstow, Curran and Rabada are their overseas players.

"It is a really emotional time for me," Pant says. "I just want to enjoy every moment on the filed. Looking forward to my first match back. Really excited for the season."

Warner, Marsh, Hope and Stubbs are DC's overseas players. DC would have batted forst anyway. Hope is a surprise choice there.

3pm Thanks Ekanth. hello y'all. Looks like good batting conditions. The new ground in Mullanpur looks beautiful, but there is no cover from the sun in the stands.

I see Risbhabh Pant walk out with a mic for the toss. What a life-affirming sight. I am not one for body language analysis, but whoever I see greeting Pant looks like they are just in awe of the comeback he has made to professional cricket after that dreadful accident

Pitch report: The straight boundary is 75 metres and the square ones are in the mid-60s. Fine boundaries, at 60 metres, are shorter. I couldn't catch the ends in the graphic. Matthew Hayden says there's a lot of mystique around new venues. Cricketers don't like change. Says the pitch is rock-hard and it's a black-soil track, not a lot of grass, which means there won't be much turn for the spinners and seamers won't be excited. There's a lot of breeze coming in, the longer boundaries will be difficult to hit. It's probably a 8.5 or 9-run per over pitch.

Toss coming up soon, Sidharth Monga will be in to take you through it.

Afeef: "So happy to see Pant back on a cricket field. Hope he does something special today."

Punjab Kings Season Preview Wasim Jaffer answers whether they have enough in-form overseas players

2:50pm Nagraj, who's in India and will be on the road through IPL 2024, has been exploring. He takes you through the story behind feature-rich Maharaja Yadavindra Singh Stadium here. It's a venue where fast bowlers have had their tails up in the Syed Mushtaq Ali Trophy, India's domestic T20 comp. With the two-bouncer rule coming in this season, it'll be fun to see how bowlers use it, especially after how RCB went full-on with the tactic against CSK last night. Dale Steyn and Harshal Patel have talked about it too.

Mustafa Moudi : "While all focus this season is on Dhoni, I feel this could be the final season for the man who holds most Orange Caps in IPL History - David Warner as he has been announcing hos retirement one after the other. Hoping for a rocking finish to his IPL Career!!"

Junaid Anwar: "Mansur Ali Khan pataudi too had a car accident at 20 which left his one eye permanently damaged,he came back to play and became captain as well,so much similarity to pant."

Capitals' season Preview Jaffer says they rely heavily on Warner

2:40pm Sairaj Bahutule, who had suffered a serious accident himself, chatted with Nagraj Gollapudi about Pant. Ricky Ponting too talked about the 'amazing story'. Check it out. Pant, himself talked about his comeback and the rollercoaster of emotions around it. You can find that here. He's getting on his gloves to do some drills now btw, Sourav Ganguly, on one knee, is underarming balls from closeby. Pant's focusing on getting down and lossening up. Will be interesting to see how he keeps today. Warner is out for some throwdowns too.

Match Preview Pant's return eclipses all else as Kings vs Capitals launches IPL's 36th venue

2:30pm Rishabh Pant makes his return to top-level professional cricket after recovering from a life-threatening accident in late 2022. It's hugely significant as he takes back the reins of Delhi Capitals in their season opener against Punjab Kings. For Kings, this is a new start at a new home, in Mullanpur. It's a sunny day, there's a dance ceremony going on. There's a big logo across the centre of the ground and the dancers are out wearing traditional clothing, songs are on rotation, there's some swords and acrobatics too. There's a smattering of people in the stands, that might build up as we move forward.

postText:
From Shiva Jayaraman: ESPNcricinfo's Forecaster had DC's chances of winning at 38.9% at the start of the 20th over. The ended their innings with 56.7% win probability

Tarun: "Amazing knock from Porel, how big was that first six?" 99 metres

Abhishek Porel has played a lovely cameo right at the end to give DC a score to bowl at, but they will still feel they are below par. They went nowhere in their middle overs, losing wickets regularly, but Porel has given them a fighting chance. Porel says he knew he could be needed because the wickets were falling. So he was ready to bat should he be needed. He says he wanted to react to the ball and not pre-meditate. He says this is now a good score, and backs his side's bowling. Will it be enough, though? Find out with Ekanth in a bit

Stat from Sampath: Fourth instance of Harshal Patel conceding 25 or more runs in an over in the IPL, joint-most by any bowler alongside Shivam Mavi.

text: Short and wide, slapped in front of point. 138ks and Dhawan eased into the cut, stayed on top of the bounce and his front leg was hovering up as he got it into the ground. Not perfectly timed but well enough
preText: 5:28pm Pant has a chat in the huddle before leading DC out. Dhawan and Bairstow are the openers. It's still bright out but the shadows are lengthening. Porel is in good spirit as you'd expect. Khaleel has the ball, will he find swing? Slip in.

text: Length outside off, patted with an open face to point.

Gets a bit too straight, more because of the angle, Dhawan helps it along. Three-quarter length, lucky for Khaleel it went to fine leg
Skilful from YJB. Guided wide of gully. Length ball angling away through fourth, he waited and opened the face last second, got it fine enough too. All Khaleel can do is smile

Driven through cover. Bairstow is on the front dog, walks into the top-of-bounce drive. He got width and Khaleel's errors have cost Capitals a 17-run opening over. It's the most for Punjab Kings, if I heard Murali Karthik right
Grass-sizzling slap through point. Went just to the left of Axar, who didn't pick it up. Pant not happy with the effort. Was a wide length ball to which Dhawan charged and belted with a cross bat
Pretty much the same. Dhawan takes a step down and knows he doesn't have to play at that

text: Gets it too wide outside off. Fuller side of length, shaped away a bit but started too wide

He missed the ball and couldn't hold onto his balance. He stretched his front foot back. Third umpire's checking if there's bat involved. Ultra-Edge coming up, no bat involved. Replays confirm he's just in Good keeping from Pant, who was blinded, pushed the ball into the stumps rather quickly but Jitesh's desperate swivel saved him.
preText: Sumit on. Is he the back-up for Ishant's potentially lost overs?

text: WIde on a length, steered to deep point

Short and wide, slapped through the gap at cover. "Like serving candy to a baby" says Daren Ganga. 107ks, sat up just above waist height.
Full ball is pushed to long-on

Flicks it from middle and off to midwicket

He missed it and was mid-jump and out of the crease. Meanwhile, Pant lunged low, stretched his upper body as far forward as he could and pushed the ball into the stumps. That oughta reaffirm thoughts around his keeping

text: Wide and shortish, 122ks, cut hard to deep point

text: Into the pitch, outside off. Liam tries flat-batting but top edges it over the bowler
preText: Can Marsh make amends after a poor last over?

text: Pick-up hook over the short boundary at deep fine leg! Shortish ball, around head-height but it's not pacy. Curran got his head to the offside to get well inside the line and help it along
Curran is sliding along the crease to put Marsh off his line. Got one on a back of length this time, fourth stump but he'd opened up enough to get room for the cut through backward point

preText: Around

Livingstone didn't have to much as he was readily inside the line, lifted it with precision. Both players exchange a smile
preText: 16 off 13, boundary or more will push it firmly in Kings' favour. Marsh goes over the wicket

Ball popped off the glove for Pant to take a dolly. Khaleel and Pant share a glance of understanding, this seems to be a plan coming off

shortText: Ahmed to Harpreet Brar, no run

preText: Harpreet in. Khaleel on a hat-trick!

text: David Warner has dropped it at long-on! That's probably the unlikeliest event today as he has been a livewire in the field. He ran in and tried to cup the ball but it popped out. Was a shortish ball outside off, bounce too high and Harpreet clothed the pull
preText: 8 off 7. Effective free hit.

shortText: Sumit Kumar to Livingstone, no run

postText: Sandy: ""SUPERRRR-OVERRRR"?" Unlikely but who knows

text: Another wide. Short one bounces well above head height
Wide and shortish, let go. Easy wide picked up
preText: Run a ball needed, Livingstone on strike. Wicket will be huge. But with Ishant's absence, Sumit will have to bowl the final over

text: Clean as a whistle, slugged over cow corner and Punjab Kings start their journey in Mullanpur with a win. Was a wide ball on a length. 119ks, Livingstone lunged and had ample time as the ball sat up to be clobbered across the line
postText:
Pant's return game was fun. He didn't get a big score but looked happy and healthy, which has been the theme leading up to now. Hope that continues and that Ishant's fine. Updates will be in about that soon and you'll be able to check it out here. If Kings manage to get most from their resources, they'll have a good season. For now, the second game's started. KKR are struggling against SRH. Do follow that, and take care.

Sujit: "So Porel's innings ensures that Delhi don't take a big NRR hit. But they really need to spruce their bowling. I mean Khaleel and Marsh as front line bowlers is an invitation to the opposition to indulge themselves."

Sam Curran, POTM: Really pleased, didn't know how the ground would play. Amazing way to start. Nothing better than starting with a win at home. [Chat when Axar, Kuldeep were bowling] Those two are world-class bowlers and play a lot of cricket for India, thought we could take it deep with them being a bowler down. We were in a good position, and then to be with my great mate Liam, was pretty special. [Surviving the dropped chance] At that stage, you gotta take those risks, thankfully luck was on my side there. I knew after surviving it, one of us had to take it to the end Thought the wicket got better under lights, was a good pitch. Ground was big but the ball was travelling well, not much spin and ball was coming on nicely from the pacers. [Did you ask Dhawan for more overs] We got some great options, nice additions too, maybe it'll be different in Bangalore. Most importantly, we won.

Shikhar Dhawan, Kings captain: Feels great, happy to be on the ground. I've been preparing for this tournament, this is the first time I'm playing at this high a level since the last IPL. I was a bit nervous as well but yeah, came through. No chat in the innings break after the 25-run over because I was preparing to bat. Also, bowlers will be going through their own emotions. So I would rather give them space and chat after things calm down. I felt we leaked a few extra runs, of course extra nerves are there in the first match. It's normal. Felt the wicket got better under lights, we got a good start and Sam played an amazing innings. Livingstone finished it nicely. [Decision to bowl first] I didn't know the records here, it's a new ground. So didn't focus on it too much, we practiced during day and at night. Thought we'd let the other team use their brains first and then we'll assess it. It worked for us, so we're happy and content.

Machakaari : "DC didn't win the crucial moments. But for Kuldeep and Axar,Their bowling looks seriously weak. Fielding below par to say the least" I still can't get over Warner dropping a catch.

Rishabh Pant, DC captain: Ishant's injury was clearly evident because we were anyway one player short because we lagged with the batting a bit. Abhishek came in and chipped in with a few runs which were crucial. We were short on extra bowling. We actually pulled it back in the end [but couldn't complete the job], part and parcel of the game. [Batting] Personally I was pretty nervous but you have to go through this when you enter the field. This isn't the first time being nervous, but happy about that [return overall]. I think we had a par score but because we were one bowler short, because of an injury, can't do much about it. Wicket played as we expected to play, can't make excuses. We will learn from it but having one bowler short is never good. End of the day, well played to them [Kings] I guess. Porel's finish helped us finish on a high. It was an amazing innings, congrats to him. I think it's just his third or fourth game but the kind of impact he made was huge. Really looking forward [to seeing him] this season.

7:19pm It was a seesaw battle but Kings were often in front. For Capitals, Ishant twisting an ankle in the field was a big blow. Especially since it was in the sixth over. The bowlers, Marsh and Khaleel in particular, not coming good cost them. Curran, pushed up to No. 4, was spectacular. Bairstow and Dhawan gave Kings a decent start but fell quickly, so Curran held the innings together amid Kuldeep looking threatening as ever. Axar was trying his best to play a holding role. Sumit, who had to be brought in, was expensive. Curran and Livingstone used the short boundary to their advantage, especially when it was behind them and the bowlers went short. Capitals pulled it back a bit late in the innings, Khaleel got Curran but it wasn't enough with Livingstone and his clean hitting taking the hosts home, in their new home.

Afeef: "Last season Livingstone played one of his best T20 knocks against DC but PBKS failed to get over the line. I'm glad he could finish off this chase against DC today."

text: shortish and wide of off stump, Salt thrashes a thick outside edge down to deep third
preText:
Anyway, enough of such high jinks. The KKR openers are on their way out - and it's Sunil Narine pushed up alongside Phil Salt to start off! Looks like Bhuvneshwar Kumar with the new ball for SRH. Salt is taking strike. Slip in place

Hello, IPL peeps. I like orange, I like purple, but which one's best...? Only one way to find out. FIGHT!

7.23pm We are only ten minutes away from the action, and here comes Alan wearing a mix of orange and purple. Whom is he rooting for tonight? Only he can answer.

Ask Star on ESPNcricinfo: Got a question for the Star Sports commentators about this match? Want to ask Navjot Sidhu, Ambati Rayudu or Irfan Pathan about anything cricket? Go to the ESPNcricinfo homepage on the mobile site, click on the Ask Star button at the bottom of the screen, and send in your questions. They could get answered on TV.

"SRH might have the best overseas contingent by far. Head, Hasaranga and Phillips are great players, and it's a shame we're capped at four!" --- Life is only that much bit fair, Rishy

Ashish: "No GP!! Won't watch this match without him"

Kolkata Knight Riders: 1 Venkatesh Iyer, 2 Phil Salt (wk), 3 Shreyas Iyer (capt), 4 Rinku Singh, 5 Nitish Rana, 6 Sunil Narine, 7 Andre Russell, 8 Ramandeep Singh, 9 Mitchell Starc, 10 Harshit Rana, 11 Varun Chakravarthy. The impact-sub options are Suyash, Pandey, Arora, Raghuvanshi and Gurbaz.

Sunrisers Hyderabad: 1 Mayank Agarwal, 2 Rahul Tripathi, 3 Aiden Markram, 4 Heinrich Klaasen (wk), 5 Abdul Samad, 6 Shahbaz Ahmed, 7 Marco Jansen, 8 Pat Cummins (capt), 9 Bhuvneshwar Kumar, 10 Mayank Markande, 11 T Natarajan. The impact-sub options are Reddy, Washington, Malik, Phillips and Abhishek.

7pm It is windy at Eden, as we get set for the toss. SRH win the toss and bowl first. Pat Cummins says T20 "is pretty quick", and so he'll have to think on his feet when it comes to captaincy in this format. His other three overseas players are Markram, Klassen and Jansen. Meanwhile, home captain Shreyas Iyer is greeted by a roar, and says his back "feels fantastic". He refers to the team sheet, and says his overseas quartet is Salt, Narine, Russell and Starc.

6.45pm Steven Smith - yes, him! - who is one of the experts at ESPNcricinfo for this IPL, gets his prediction meter ticking. He forecasts Starc's wicket tally, IPL 2024's MVP and much more. And if you're wondering what made Smith guess that number for Starc, here's Sid Monga's analysis on the constant and universal appeal of Starc.

There are some subplots which will be taking shape at Eden Gardens tonight, with Shreyas Iyer's return, and Cummins vs Starc being two of them, as Hemant Brar's preview reminds us. As for the two most expensive buys in IPL history, Cummins, who is Starc's captain at Australia, says it will be "weird seeing him in the other dugout".

6.30pm They come very rapidly in the IPL - like sharp, rising waves in the sea. Only last night we were in Chennai, the southern part of the country; and even before the action in Mullanpur, the northern corner, is wrapped, we are all but readying ourselves for a game in Kolkata in the east. This is Himanshu saying hello ahead of the third game this season, with Alan, who is busy munching lunch, set to join me soon.

preText: "Phil is rubbing salt into KKR wounds - needs to get a move on! (Sorry, could not resist)" You're right, SD. He needs to season this innings with a few more boundaries

text: back of a length outside off, Salt slaps a cut in front of square and pushes hard for two

shortText: Shahbaz Ahmed to Ramandeep Singh, no run
text: tossed up wide of the stumps, 87kph and Ramandeep toe-ends an attempted slog down the ground

shortText: Shahbaz Ahmed to Ramandeep Singh, (no ball) SIX
text: launched over cover, six more! Ramandeep is on one here. Makes some room and lofts this, easy as you like, into the boundary boards
preText:
Shahbaz Ahmed on to bowl

"Graham Gooch like stance for Phil Salt. A huge backlift !!! Is Salt also from the same county as the great Gooch." He is not from the mighty Essex, Sowmya. Born in Wales, raised in Barbados, currently plays for Lancashire
postText: And Shahbaz has overstepped, too

shortText: Shahbaz Ahmed to Ramandeep Singh, 1 run
text: quicker and straighter, nurdled to leg for one
postText: Gourav: "the win probability for KKR is in 80's now, but looking at the surface I feel SRH is still ahead in the game." Forecaster currently thinks they are on for 209, which would be a good effort

shortText: Shahbaz Ahmed to Salt, no run
text: floated up and Salt picks out cover on the drive
clipped down the ground

shortText: Shahbaz Ahmed to Ramandeep Singh, 1 run
text: worked for a single into the leg side, bringing up the 50 stand
smeared through the off side, Salt picks up four more. Steps away to a flat delivery wide of off and beats extra cover inside the ring with a meaty swipe

wkt_text: Ramandeep Singh c Markande b Cummins 35 (20m 17b 1x4 4x6) SR: 205.88
text: chipped to cover, Cummins strikes! Hit high on the bat as he looked to drive on the up, well held by Markande diving across to his right. Ramandeep won't be taking this deep. The KKR recovery takes a hit
preText: Cummins brings himself back on
postText: In walks the finisher, Rinku Singh

text: lofted over mid-off, four first ball! Steps into a full delivery from Cummins and just dismisses it from his sight
short of a length, 140kph into the body. Rinku rocks back and angles the ball to deep third
short ball swivelled away on the pull through square leg
back of a length into the body and Rinku nudges it to the infielder
full on leg stump, 141kph and flicked wide of fine leg for a couple
preText: "I think the forecaster is taking into account one Rinku and another Dre Russ." Darn tootin' it is, Darshan

text: looped up and driven, the bowler swoops to his left to collect
preText: Markande is back for Shahbaz

text: hammered through the covers, fifty for Salt! Steps away and clobbers a legbreak through the infield. Salute to the home fans, a fine start for the England man on KKR debut
dragged down and swung away leg side
very full and loopy wide of off, 80kph and driven down to long-off
postText: "It's like KKR doesn't actually want dreRuss to bat at all!!!" I dunno, Joynul. The top order have done their best to get him in early...

wkt_text: PD Salt c Jansen b Markande 54 (68m 40b 3x4 3x6) SR: 135.00
text: Salt swings to leg, but holes out to Jansen in the deep! Salt has shaken his last after giving the KKR fans a taste. Stepped away as Markande pushed one down the leg side, didn't quite get hold of his shot - but it still needed good work from Jansen running around to his right and diving full length for the catch
postText: Here is Dre Russ at No. 8

text: tossed up and he shows it a diligent straight bat in defence
postText: "Tame end to a salty innings!" But how long will it linger on the palate, SD?

text: short of a length, steered for one
nasty delivery, 139kph and rising sharply off a length. Russell ducks and loses sight of it, splicing the ball into the off side as he reaches out in front
full length, 143kph, heaved away through square leg for one
round the wicket, back of a length outside off and jabbed down to deep third
short but with pace off, 115kph and spinning through past Russell's belligerent swipe across the line
full, straight, 141kph and carved out to deep point
postText:
This is from my colleague Sampath... Highest scores on debut for KKR in IPL:

Brendon McCullum - 158* vs RCB, 2008

Manish Pandey - 64 vs MI, 2014

Owais Shah - 58* vs DC, 2010

Jacques Kallis - 54 vs CSK, 2011

Phil Salt - 54 vs SRH, 2024

text: boom! Slog-swept into the crowd! Vintage Dre Russ, keeps his head down and eyes on the ball, before clonking it over deep midwicket. 91-metre six
preText: Markande to Russell

text: tossed up towards the tramlines, called wide but SRH review it. And the replay shows it was inside the tramlines, so the call is overturned
pushed through on the stumps, defended
connects again! Another one sails over deep midwicket! Plants the front foot and swings with a vengeance across the line, goes fully 102 metres!
Dre Russssssssss! Markande is getting a mauling. Tossed up wide of off and he launches on to the front foot to pump him over long-on

slogged down the ground, taken! Markram is claiming the catch running in from long-off. What does the smart replay say? Very grainy image for Bruce Oxenford to work with, but he reckons there was ball on the ground before the fingers got around it. Cheers from the home crowd, Russell will continue
postText: Time for another strategic timeout. Go top up the biscuit barrel

text: back of a length on fourth stump, Rinku runs it behind point
preText: Four overs to go, can KKR get to 190-200? Bhuvneshwar is back on

text: Russell in a rush, battered over midwicket! Back of a length and hauled high into the crowd one again. Just Dre Russ things
short and smeared through square leg, 128kph length delivery and slugged for four as he backs away
pitched up, 135kph and this is walloped down to long-off for one. Bhuvi will take that
full on the pads, Rinku picks up two into the gap at deep square leg
preText: Here's Rakesh: "I think the KKR need to think out of the box and use DreRuss as a floater and NOT always keep him for the last. I would like to see DreRuss at 3-4-or 5 depending upon the situation. He fires, you win, he fails, you have back up with 2-3 batsmen to follow."

text: speared through backward point, Rinku gets in on the fun. Low full toss at 141kph and he opens the face to pick up four
short of a length and Russell mistimes an attempted muscle down the ground. Single to long-off
preText: Natarajan for the 18th

text: back of a length, fifth stump and guided calmly to short third by Rinku
belted into the crowd! Russell is a mood tonight. Half-volley on the pads and he doesn't miss out
preText: "Russ on song reminds me so much of Viv, bowlers simply cannot do much against such rampaging batsmen!!" I'm sure he won't mind the comparison, Sriram Ramakris
postText: That's the 50 stand, from just 24 balls

text: full down the leg side, another wide from Natarajan
slower-ball bouncer, gets too bouncy as Russell leans back and attempts to ramp
Natarjan digs the ball into the pitch and gets Russell off strike
short and sliding down leg as Rinku bails out
Rinku finishes with four more down the ground! In the slot again and lofted back towards long-off
goes wide blockhole, Russell swings himself into an extravagant drive. Just one to the cover sweeper
low full toss, helped away through midwicket! Looked to have got away with it but the strength of the man gets it to the rope between two boundary riders
preText: Two overs left, Bhuvi will bowl one of them
postText: And Bhuvi has overstepped, free hit coming!

text: gets the yorker to land, 136kph angling across. Rinku digs it out for one
short ball, swatted off the nose! Dre Russ brings up fifty with his sixth six. Vintage stuff from the veteran West Indies allrounder. Bit top-edgey but it flies all the way over fine leg
preText: PokeMan: "DreRuss at 8 Allows KKR to go gung-ho from start. Today it didn't come off, but I like the strategy."

text: low full toss, heaved away to wide long-off, they'll charge back for two
Russell steps away, Bhuvi goes for the wide line... too wide
tonked over cover, six more! Goes for the wide yorker by misses his length but a few feet. Russell holds the pose on one knee as he slaughters another one into the boards
short and smashed! Jumps into a flat-batted mow through cover and that's the KKR 200 up! Dre Russ punches the back of his bat, he is cooking in the Garden tonight
postText: For all their vaunted bowling, SRH have leaked 77 from the last four overs

wkt_text: RK Singh c Markram b Natarajan 23 (35m 15b 3x4 0x6) SR: 153.33
text: top-edged in the slog, taken at long-on! Rinku knows he has to go (or get Russell on strike). He opts for the former and holes out to Markram a few yards in off the rope
preText: Natarajan to close out

text: low full toss, swatted behind point, Starc gets up and running in purple with a boundary
preText: Mitch Starc, the $3million man

text: shortish and helped away into the leg side
preText: "This is just brutal," yelps Andrew, echoing the thoughts of many
postText: What else has Dre Russ got in his locker tonight?

text: on a length, and angling across to finish on off. Tapped to cover-point's left
preText:
Starc has the new ball, with every delivery of his to cost INR 6 lakh. Agarwal on strike.

Alex: "Any score above 180, let alone 209, is nearly impossible for SRH. They are relatively weak in the batting department." --- They have now added a batter to make full use of the rules, so who knows?!

Here comes the Impact Sub for SRH: Abhishek Sharma replaces Natarajan.

9.30pm So the last five overs for KKR yielded 85. With that Russell Muscle, it's only fortunate for those concerned that none of the balls landed in the Hooghly river nearby. SRH will need to repeat those heroics if they are to hunt down a mammoth 209, although they will hope there is some dew to help them.

text: ahh, the length was there to be lofted, but Agarwal missed. Starc went on the fuller side of a good length, pitching it around fourth stump while getting to move away. Agarwal looked to launch it, but missed
short of a length on leg, and dabbed just close to the leg stump. Agarwal takes off, but is sent back by Abhishek

ahh, some very late movement in the air after the ball pitches, and that costs KKR five wides. Starc bowled short and just outside leg, as Agarwal looked to pull but the ball went over his bat. Then the ball moved away to finish outside off even as Slat leaped on the leg side
backs away, and Starc follows. Bowls an inswinging yorker finishing on leg, with Mayank heaving but getting it off the bottom of the bat to square leg's right
driven through the covers! He hangs deep in the crease, and drills this fullish ball which finishes wide of off. Beats cover-point to his left
taps this fullish ball on middle and off, which straightens away towards off. Single to deep third

shortText: Harshit Rana to Agarwal, no run
text: fullish ball angling in, and pitching on sixth stump. The ball ends closer to off, and is pushed to mid-on off the inside half of the bat
preText: Harshit from the other end

text: lofted over mid-off! The bat turns in his hands, but that was still timed well. He bent his back knee at this full delivery a bit wide of off, and sent it sailing

shortText: Harshit Rana to Agarwal, no run
text: loud and animated for lbw... and it is given out after probably 29 seconds! However, Agarwal reviews. There is no inside edge, as the ball shapes back in to his front pad, while beating the inside edge. My first impression, though, is that this one is heading down the leg side. Yup, replays confirm that this length ball, which pitched on fourth stump and shaped back in, would have ended outside leg, as Agarwal looked to flick but missed
preText: Slip vanishes

text: ahh, almost chopped on! He looked to slash with an angled bat, with the ball being on a length just outside off. He got a bottom edge, with the ball dribbling away past the stumps and to the leg side

shortText: Harshit Rana to Abhishek Sharma, no run
text: bowls on a length around off, and it straightens away. Nudged to midwicket
preText: Abhishek facing his first ball. Harshit from around.

shortText: Harshit Rana to Abhishek Sharma, no run
text: this is shorter in length, and on a wide-ish line outside off. He looks to slap, but is beaten by the extra bounce
on a fullish length while angling across and finishing on middle and off. Dabbed late to deep third
preText: Sujatha: "From being a Test regular for India to being out of contention, Mayank has lots to set straight!"

text: dropped by Salt! That rubs - forgive the pun - Salt into the wounds, as the ball races away for four. Salt finished on front of first slip in trying to grab it high, but the ball popped away off his gloves. Starc bowled full and wide of off, as Abhishek went driving away from his body but got an outside edge

shortText: Starc to Abhishek Sharma, no run
text: full length again, but this is much straighter. Clipped to mid-on

shortText: Starc to Abhishek Sharma, no run
text: now some extra bounce for Starc. On a length in the channel outside off, as he looks to punch without any foot movement but is beaten
change of pace, as he bowls full on off at 120kph only. Pushed to mid-on for a quick single
ahh, thumped with the pace! He presents the full face of the bat at this fullish ball swinging in and finishing on leg, driving it to mid-on's right to send the ball motoring away

shortText: Harshit Rana to Abhishek Sharma, 1 run
text: on a length, and slightly wide of off. He pokes it away from his body to deep third
postText: "Forgive the pun? More like encourage" --- So Sweet of you, Eddy

shortText: Harshit Rana to Agarwal, no run
text: ohh, he shaped to sway away at that but then ducked a bit. Harshit bowled on a length around sixth stump, with Mayank perhaps first assuming that the ball was coming his way

just short of deep backward square leg running and diving forward! Ramandeep was the man there, as Agarwal walked down the pitch at this length ball wide of off, and swiped that across the line. Great effort from Ramandeep, though

superb shot! This gives me a hint as to how Kohli's straight loft off Haris would have looked had he gone over backward point. On a length just outside off from Harshit, and Agarwal simply lofted with the open face of the bat

shortText: Harshit Rana to Agarwal, no run
text: on the shorter side of a length in the corridor, and tapped to the keeper's right

pulled over mid-on, and the ball teases the fielder all the way back. Not entirely timed well - that came off the top half of the bat, as Harshit bowled a slower ball - but it was on a length and a bit wide of off, as Agarwal pulled at it

shortText: Varun to Abhishek Sharma, no run
text: ahh, appeal for stumping first ball! The square-leg umpire refers it up. Abhishek dragged his back leg forward but pushed it back before the bails were whipped. Varun went fullish while taking it across, as the ball finished outside off, and beating his attempted loft
preText: Varun into the attack

text: the man at point dives across to his right, but can't get a hand. Abhishek skipped down the pitch and went lofting, but got this full ball around off from the outside half of the bat
over wide long-on! He slog sweeps this length ball finishing around middle and off, with his back leg folding to facillitate the shot
goes fullish on the stumps, as Abhishek skips down again and pushes to mid-on
preText: From around now

text: full and flat around off, and driven to long-off
preText:
Back from over to Agarwal

Krishna: "That Mayank six is the most beautiful shot of the match!" --- Could be the best of the season, I'd think

text: but it doesn't make any difference! Again went across the line, with this full delivery ending around fifth stump after turning away. Slogged impactfully!
preText: Back over for Abhishek too

text: backs away, and just clears mid-on! The fielder had turned around and started running forward, with the ball dropping over his head. Short of a length from Harshit, as Agarwal swung back down the pitch

shortText: Harshit Rana to Agarwal, no run
text: ahh, this time he follows Agarwal, and bowls a good-length ball which shapes back in from off and finishes outside leg. Agarwal is cramped for room, and ends up gloving to the keeper's right in an attempt to guide it

wkt_text: MA Agarwal c Singh b Harshit Rana 32 (27m 21b 4x4 1x6) SR: 152.38

Agarwal pulls but off the higher side of the bat. The longer side of the boundary comes into play, as Rinku takes it low
ahh, on the helmet first ball! Hits the grille, as he looks to sway away at this short-of-a-length ball rising on to middle and leg. The ball rolls away towards deep third even as it took the grille
preText: Tripathi at No. 3
postText: The physio arrives for the routine concussion check, and so we have a break in play. But all is well, and we resume.

shortText: Harshit Rana to Abhishek Sharma, no run

shortText: Harshit Rana to Abhishek Sharma, FOUR
text: swatted over point! He jumped down a bit while also making a bit of room, as Harshit bowled short and a bit wide outside off. There was no one out on the boundary, and Abhishek capitalised
postText:
"I was initially confused when Tripathi came out to bat for SRH. He is still a KKR guy in my mind!!" --- The times change more quickly when it comes to IPL cricket, Shrikant!

The first time-out

text: full and dipping on his pads. Paddle swept to short fine leg

text: fullish ball, and flatter on middle and leg. Turns away a bit, and is defended down

shortText: Narine to Abhishek Sharma, no run
text: shorter side of a length, and on sixth stump. Slashed to point, where the fielder tumbles to his left to stop that
ahh, this turns in towards leg off a short of a length on middle and off. Swiped to deep square
on a length on leg, and sliding down. Swept to short fine again
uff, this turns in off a fullish length on sixth stump. He went to glide that, but was beaten
hacked just wide of deep third! On a short of a length just outside off, as Abhishek slashes at it even as he didn't have all the room to work with
preText: Time for Russell Muscle with the ball
postText: Ganesh: "The attitude of Rana towards Agarwal was not of a good sportsmanship, I believe" --- The young man will learn with time

Russell dug one a short at Abhishek, with the ball climbing nicely towards the batter's throat on middle and leg. He went for the pull, but top-edged it, with the extra pace getting the ball to zip through off the pitch
pulled to deep midwicket! Another short ball from Russell, but this on fifth stump, and Markram rides the bounce to pull comfortably
preText: Markram

text: flashed to deep point, as the ball is on a short of a length in the channel outside off
well bowled! Short delivery just outside off, as Tripathi shaped to pull but then swayed out of the way, with the line being quite tight

this dips on a fullish length on middle, and hints to turn in. Clipped to deep midwicket
preText: Here comes KKR's Impact Sub: Suyash replaces Ramandeep
postText: Raj83: "Can the palindrome Markram do a palindrome here?" --- We shift from the Salt puns to the Markram palindrome...

text: fullish on middle and off, and turning away. Pushed to long-on
on a length just outside off, and turning. Pulled to deep backward square's left, and the pinch two

short of a length outside off, and slapped to deep point
short of a length just outside off, and punched to long-on with the turn into him
fullish ball dipping just outside off, and turning away. Swung to long-on
preText: Suyash into the attack

text: slog swept over long-on! He goes down on his back knee, and clubs this full ball finishing outside off after turning away
this is full again, but wider outside off. He has to drag this sweep from wide outside to play to long-on
short of a length just outside off, and slapped to deep extra cover! The ball is crashed to beat deep point to his right, as he bags four more
this is the one turning in, as it is full and just outside off. He drives but gets it off the inside half of the bat to deep square

dropped by Suyash! And the ball goes on to hit the umpire just below his left knee! The umpire is in pain, as Tripathi absolutely smashed this length ball just outside off. Suyash tried to take it with both hands to his right, but the ball burst out after tickling them
half an appeal for lbw by Salt, but not given. On a fullish length on middle, and hitting his front as he looked to flick but missed
preText:
There's a bit of delay, as the umpire gets some treatment after being pinged by that hit from Tripathi. We resume after a few minutes, as Narine continues.

"I was blessed with a baby boy and girl last month. Named them Shreyas and Smriti, respectively. Smriti won WIPL earlier this month. Will Shreyas follow suit?" --- Congratulations Aravindh, and my only guess is that you had twins! Maybe Shreyas will indeed follow Smriti!

text: this is faster and on a length on middle again. Nudged towards mid-on this time
collapses his back knee to try and sweep, but gets this length ball outside off from the bottom of the bat towards square leg
fullish ball just outside off, and hinting to turn in. Punched to long-off

on a fullish length just outside off, and turning in. Pulled to long-on

slog sweeps this length delivery on middle and off to fine leg

text: skips down, and punches this shortish ball around off to extra cover

on a length on middle, and turning in. Hits his pad outside leg, as he looked to flick but missed

Time-out

shortText: Suyash Sharma to Klaasen, no run
text: uff, sharp turn from a length on off, and ending outside leg, as he looked to slash after making room, but missed

wkt_text: Abdul Samad c VR Iyer b Russell 15 (20m 11b 1x4 1x6) SR: 136.36
text: straight to deep midwicket! The fielder was placed right on the edge of the rope, and that arrived at a comfortable height, in front of his stomach. shortText: Harshit Rana to Cummins, no run
text: superb final over! KKR can now breathe. He bowls another slower ball, and foxes Cummins too. On a length in the channel outside off, and there is some extra bounce too, as Cummins swings his bat and is beaten. KKR win by 4 runs
preText: Cummins
postText:
A game which could have gone anywhere. In what was typical modern hitting, Russell hammered 64* off 25 balls, and Klaasen hit back with 63 from 29. KKR were 51 for 4 at one stage, before going on to post 208; SRH required 60 in the last three overs, but fell just four short. Exceptional T20 batting from both sides! And with this thriller, we wrap the double-header Saturday up. Join us for another two games tomorrow, as this is Himanshu signing off on behalf of Raghav and Alan. Good night!

Andre Russell is the Player of the Match: "Sometimes I realise how I'm striking the ball... I just try to react to whatever comes my way. Over the last year or two, bowlers have been exceptionally good to me. I'm still figuring out how to score. I realise everyone is coming to me with a plan. I've been a permanent fixture in the XI [since making it there]. What I did tonight is just to say 'keep supporting'. I am happy to contribute with this jersey on. Harshit's body language was on point in the last over; he wanted the ball. If he was shying away from it, it could have gone their way. With the first ball gone for six, he still got the job done."

Shreyas Iyer, KKR captain: "Right from the 17th over I had butterflies in the stomach! To be honest, I thought anything can happen in the last over. Harshit was a bit nervous when he was coming to bowl [the last over]. I told him, 'Even if we lose, it's fine'. I tried to calm him down as much as possible. Narine and Russell have got such experience. Elated to see how Russell performed with bat and ball. Sunny executed well. It is a luxury to have them in the team. Whenever you start with a win, it gives you motivation. There are areas we need to improve on as a team - fielding is one of them!"

Time for the presentations

Afeef: "This game boiled down to Russell vs Klaasen, the two most destructive batsmen from both the squads today"

Ramandeep Singh: "I was really enjoying my time in the middle. Trying to play with intent. All thanks to Gauti paaji and Abhishek Nayar sir. I was striking pretty well in domestic cricket. The way these guys have backed me is tremendous. I really want to play like that (like Russell!). Maybe one day I will play like that! The plan was that Klaasen was really hitting the pace ball. So the message was to take pace off. I really loved the atmosphere at the ground."

Pat Cummins, SRH captain: "Close game in the end. Wonderful game of cricket; unfortunately didn't go our way. Dre Russ did what he does best. You do your planning, and you try to execute your plans. But he's a pretty tough guy to bowl to. Tough job in cricket to bowl to someone like him. It's one of those ones which goes one way or the other. Who would have thought we would have got that close? Unfortunately, a bit too much. Lots to be encouraged by. A couple of points to work on also."

Joel Mick: "There's something that even Cummins can't do!"

Karthik: "Jailbreak :)"

11.25pm The heart rates rose and fell in the final over, which started with SRH requiring 13. The first ball went for six, and thereafter, it was all KKR, as Harshit got Shahbaz, who was playing second fiddle, and Klaasen, who threatened to do the impossible. Before the last over began, Klaasen and Shahbaz had pumped 63 off the three overs just before that. It seemed like KKR were running out of ideas, but just then, Harshit came out with his magical slower balls to deny a rampaging Klaasen, who continues his dream run in this part of the world. Hang around for the presentations.

KL Rahul says they'd have batted first, thinks pitch won't change much. Happy to be back on the field. Injuries have become my best friend in the last two years, but I'm trying to do my best when I get my chances. Pretty much the same team combination as last year. QDK, Stoinis, Pooran and Naveen will be the overseas players. Shamar will hopefully get a go later on.

Sanju Samson says it's a good wicket to bat on, okay to do both, but they have different combinations they want to try out. Coming back to Jaipur sends a positive vibe. Lot of youngsters in the team have become superstars in the last ten months, it's great. Almost the same team, Parag will come in at No. 4. Three foreign players - Powell might come in as impact sub.

3pm The pink flags are flying and the captains, KL Rahul and Sanju Samson, are out. Heads is KL's call, it's tails. Samson wins it, RR will bat first

Pitch report: Matthew Hayden says it's a brown surface with cracks, which means it's very dry. It's why spin has played a big role here from the start in 2008. So a big powerplay is key for batting teams before consolidating in the middle overs.Ground dimensions: Longer boundaries - in the late 70-metre range - down the ground from on end. Square boundaries are 62 and 70 metres either side. Smaller ones - 56 and 64 metres - are at the other end.

What's the best batting position for KL Rahul? Tom Moody answers

2:40pm The stadium is making Jaipur look quite literally like the pink city. The seats are flush pink, the sun is out. Avesh and Mohsin Khan were chatting during their warm-ups. Krunal Pandya, on his birthday, had a hit. Samson's having a word with his team-mates in a huddle. KL Rahul was out too, there will be eyes on him as he returns after an injury, he'd missed the second half of the last season too. The skipper is addressing the LSG huddle and just handed Devdutt Padikkal a cap.

CricDude: "RR seemed to have a good auction, but on a closer look, the balance issues are still there, coz of lack of allrounders. If RR go for Jos, Rovman, Hetty and Boult, opposition teams can take on the two Indian pacers. Best thing for RR is to play both Boult and Burger. My XII would be Jos, Yashasvi, Sanju, Riyan, Jurel, Hetty, Shubham, Ashwin, Avesh, Boult, Burger, Chahal."

Match Preview: Will Rahul continue to open as LSG begin season against Royals?

LSG, conversely to RR, have too many allrounders. What they need is a firing middle order. And that's what Abhimanyu Bose explores in the preview. Whether they pick Shamar Joseph and how he goes will be interesting not just from an IPL perspective but also from that of West Indies as they'd like to see how he turns up in T20s, where he has limited experience, while managing his workload for Tests.

2:30pm Cricket's not played on paper but viewing it in theory can be fascinating. Look at the two teams participating today - Rajasthan Royals arguably have the best XI but it's meant that they weren't particularly benefited by the Impact Player rule. Matt Roller documented it last year during their game vs RCB. Rovman Powell, Nandre Burger, and Tom Kohler-Cadmore are their big buys but they're all overseas players.

postText:
The first game of the double-header Sunday is wrapped up, as RR beat LSG by 20 runs. But the action shifts to Ahmedabad, where Pandya's GT host Pandya's MI. That is it from us from Jaipur this evening, as this is Himanshu signing off on behalf of Raghav, Thilak and Ekanth! Good night!

Sanju Samson is the Player of the Match for his 82*: "It's always great fun to spend time in the middle. This time I have been a different role, with a slightly different combination. Sanga has given me suggestions... I have been playing IPL for ten years, so there's experience coming in. Good start, but let's see how it goes. It's all about understanding your strengths and weakness. I just react to the ball. That helps me maintain the shape. I think I should give the trophy to Sandeep Sharma. I wouldn't have been standing here [but for him]... I thought of calling him, but then thought it would be a bit too much! Everyone chipped in well. We just had to stick to our plans."

Time for the presentations

"Looks like Ashwin gave a coach's talk" --- He loves it, KumarS!

R Ashwin: "It was a wicket of two halves. When we batted first, it stuck in the pitch. Sometimes it is tough... After the eight-over mark, we felt the wicket was a good one. In our view, we were ten short. It was a good pitch; it tends to get better here. I went for 12 off the first ball I bowled! I bowl in different stages of the game. The body is ageing. Requires different mindset. I came from a Test series. I went for 15 in the first over - that was inside the powerplay. The moment that phase of the game is done, I try to shell it away. The next three overs of mine went for 20, and I got a wicket... Most importantly, [it is about] preparing for every single batter in the opposition. The game is built by perception. Sandeep has been an unsung hero. He stepped up for Prasidh last year. He is a character; it's about the fight they have. A bowler for a fight is way more valuable than a bowler with a skill. There are two bouncers to be used, and that's the only fillip the bowlers have got in this competition. Boulty's very aggressive up front, and so is Nandre."

KL Rahul, LSG captain: "I don't think the target was a lot; it was just ten over-par. We bowled well in patches. Not making too much out of it. Just made a few mistakes. Mohsin was our powerplay bowler in the first season, but he wasn't fully fit last season. Good to see him back. Naveen has been crucial for us since he has come in. Powerplay is crucial for every team, and I don't think any team has cracked it yet. We'll made from the small mistakes we made. When we are three [down] for nothing, and we give ourselves a chance of chasing 194 speaks of our line-up... We need to find ways to win games of cricket. We'll try to build from here, and see where we can get stronger. Langer's brought a lot of calmness to the group. I stole his line when I said we need to find ways to win games of cricket. We enjoy having him around. All of us have watched him coach Australia to a T20 World Cup and an Ashes victory. When you get runs, you always feel good. But it's important for us to end up on the winning side. That gives more satisfaction. Missing a season was really painful."

7.23pm LSG needed another 49 from the last 24 balls, with Rahul and Pooran well set and ready to smash. That is when Sandeep Sharma struck, and pushed LSG back against the wall. His first over had gone for only five, and he started the death overs with Rahul's wicket. Rahul took his time to score 58, and eventually, it was too much to do for even Pooran, who was much brighter with 64* in 41 balls. RR seemed to have lost their way after they had LSG at 11 for 3 and then 60 for 4, but Sandeep, who finished with 1 for 22 in three overs, was spot on when required. Hang around for the presentations.

text: good length ball, wide, and going further away. Slaps a cut for a boundary first ball!
preText:
Hardik Pandya against his former team.

Many of you are asking who is Spencer Johnson. Andrew McGlashan did a profile of the fast bowler recently.

Mumbai Indians: Ishan Kishan, Rohit Sharma, Naman Dhir, Tilak Varma, Hardik Pandya, Tim David, Shams Mulani, Gerald Coetzee, Piyush Chala, Jasprit Bumrah, Luke Wood
Subs: Dewald Brevis, Romario Shepherd, Vishnu Vinod, Nehal Wadhera, Mohammad Nabi

Gujarat Titans: Wriddhiman Saha, Shubman Gill, Sai Sudharsan, Vijay Shankar, David Miller, Rahul Tewatia, Azmatullah Omarzai, Rashid Khan, Umesh Yadav, Sai Kishore, Spencer Johnson
Subs: BR Sharath, Mohit Sharma, Manav Suthar, Abhinav Manohar, Noor Ahmad

7pm, toss: Alright, Hardik and Gill are together in the middle. Mumbai Indians' Hardik Pandya wins the toss and chooses to bowl. "Looks like a good track, might have dew later. (Back to where it all started) Feels good to be back. Obviously my birthplace is Gujarat and I got a lot of success in Gujarat so grateful to this state. But my cricketing growth has been in Mumbai. (Prep) Been two weeks since we started the camp. Boys are eager to go out and perform." Mumbai are playing with three overseas players for now. Tim David, Gerald Coetzee and left-arm seamer Luke Wood.

Shubman Gill, TItans captain: "Excited to captain at a venue where I have many fond memories. The crowd has been one of our strengths. I have been here for a week and have played a couple of practice sessions. Three players making debut for GT: Umesh bhai, Spencer Johnson and Omarzai."

Ask Star on ESPNcricinfo: Got a question for the Star Sports commentators about this match? Want to ask Navjot Sidhu, Harbhajan Singh or Irfan Pathan about anything cricket? Go to the ESPNcricinfo homepage on the mobile site, click on the Ask Star button at the bottom of the screen, and send in your questions. They could get answered on TV.

6.57pm Just few minutes to the start, hello everyone once again. Brian Lara on the broadcast says there are some cracks on this surface but it wouldn't stop this surface from being a high-scoring one.

strong>6.55pm More news from Shashank about Gujarat's potential team combination: "Looks like Spencer Johnson will start. He's also marking his run up. Rashid, Miller, of course. Could be a toss-up for the fourth spot." With that, let me hand it over to Sreshth, who will keep you entertained for the first innings.

6.50pm Here's Shashank from the ground: "Ground about 60% full at the moment. Massive wave of MI blue outside the ground while I was coming in. Was 38 degrees a while ago, gotten a lot cooler. But there's hot air blowing on your face. They call it aandhi? There was a small cultural programme an hour ago to welcome the teams. They've made way for the players.

"Nehra, Sachin, Rohit had a long chat in the middle. Nehra playfully pulled out Hardik's measuring tape as he was marking his run up. There's a lot of laughter and banter between Hardik and his opponents, who until recently, were his teammates."

6.47pm As we wait for the toss, you can keep an eye on the proceedings from Jaipur, where KL Rahul and Nicholas Pooran have set up a potential thriller against Rajasthan Royals.

6.40pm If you need more of a scene-setter, there's no better read than our preview, authored by Shashank Kishore, who is also our man at the ground today! He has also written about Ahmedabad being Hardik's home away from home, and Gill's big batting challenge. You can also follow Al Muthu's live report, where you will get a more detailed coverage, with more stats and insights.

6.30pm Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of today's blockbuster clash between Gujarat Titans and Mumbai Indians - or as I am going to refer to it this season (at least), the 'Hardik Pandya derby'. For the uninitiated, Hardik Pandya's career was launched by Mumbai Indians, following which he has gone on to earn a superstar status. Then, released by Mumbai Indians, he joined Gujarat Titans as their captain for the franchise's first year. He led them to the title in their maiden season and to the final again last year. Now he has returned to Mumbai Indians in an all-cash trade, and has replaced Rohit Sharma as their captain.

The last time Rohit Sharma played for Mumbai Indians as a non-captain, they had never won the IPL. Now they jointly hold the record for most title wins. How will Rohit fare this year, freed up from his responsibilities? How will Hardik go, leading the team where he started his career?

The focus will be on them, but also on Shubman Gill, who has his first season as captain? His franchise may only be two years old, but have gotten used to success already so expectations will be high. I am Abhimanyu Bose, and I'll be joined soon by Sreshth Shah as we bring you all the action from the Narendra Modi Stadium in Ahmedabad.

ESPNcricinfo's forecaster suggests this is a 50-50 game. Remember, Mumbai don't have Suryakumar Yadav and a newbie in Naman Dhir instead. It'll also be interesting to see who Titans' impact player is. See you on the other side, where Abhimanyu Bose will lead you through the chase.

9.15pm Titans bat through 20 overs without ever changing gears, finishing on 168. Credit for that, though, must go to Jasprit Bumrah, who didn't open the bowling but split his four overs into two beautiful spells to finish with 3-14 in four overs. He conceded just the lone boundary and bowled 14 dots.

Bumrah was ably supported by Gerald Coetzee, who was the seventh bowler introduced but ended up bowling his full quota to finish with 2-27. Hardik, Luke Wood and Chawla were a tad expensive, but Mumbai would take that in Ahmedabad, known to be batting friendly.

Back to the Titans, and they'll be disappointed that they couldn't change gears through the innings. Both Saha and Gill started positively, but once they fell, nobody else could really keep the tempo up. Sai Sudharsan with 45 did try to offer some resistance, but with his strike-rate of 115, you could say the bowlers enjoyed that more.

Sai Sudharsan: Wicket is a bit tricky, and there was turn on the wicket. I think this is a good target. I enjoyed my match-up with Bumrah. Dew is also a little less today so spinners might have some say.

Abhishek: "MI conceded at least 15 more because of strange on field bowling changes, but still easy to chase it down"

Rishy: "As uncomfortable the truth is, Sai is not what Titans need. His lack of acceleration hurt badly today and other than the one inning in the playoffs last year he's been pretty average and dare I say overrated"

text: Straight to Rashid Khan at deep midwicket! Short ball angled across him does the trick. Piyush connected with the pull but couldn't get any elevation on it. Rashid catches it just above head height running back and Umesh Yadav is on a hat-trick!
