preText: Jasprit Bumrah comes out to bat. Meanwhile, our statman Sampath says MI's win probability was 92.73% at end of 12th over, the ball before Rohit Sharma got out!

text: Top edge falls short of long leg, but it doesn't matter. Gujarat Titans have won! A tightly fought match and a close, close win for Gujarat Titans, defending 169!
postText:
11.45pm There were some great performances from Mumbai Indians. Jasprit Bumrah, back and fit and firing for MI, bowled a brilliant spell, finishing with three for 14. Rohit Sharma and Dewald Brevis got to the forties. But it's a complete team effort from Gujarat Titans that eventually comes out trumps. It was another closely-fought contest with the home team coming out on top, which has been the trend for all five games this season. That will be all from us. On behalf of Sreshth, Thilak and everyone else at ESPNcricinfo, it's Abhimanyu signing off.

11.3pm Stay tuned for the presentation ceremony.

Gujarat Titans captain Shubman Gill: "I think the way the boys held their nerves, and the way we bowled in the death overs, especially with the dew coming in, I thought it was special. With the dew, how the spinners bowled, they made sure we stayed in the game. It was all about putting on the pressure [on the batters]. [Mohit] has been a revelation for us since he joined us last year and hopefully he can continue his form. We just wanted them to feel under pressure. The plan was to keep building the pressure and wait for them to make a mistake. [On their total] I thought 170 was a good score but we definitely left 10-15 runs out there. Even with them, they were scoring above par but with the old ball and the pitch being slow, it's difficult to hit."

Player of the match, Sai Sudharsan: "Even in the first innings it was a little bit difficult. Dew helped them go after the bowlers but I think we pulled off a great game today. I'm not taking it as pressure, I'm just taking it as an opportunity to express myself and help my team win. After a few balls I felt it's not that kind of a wicket where you go after the ball every over. So i felt building the game was more important. I was actually a bit shocked for getting the player of the match because there were many great contributions [from the bowlers]. [On bowling plans] Taking the pace off was the plan. Even I found it difficult."

Hardik Pandya: "Obviously we back ourselves to chase those 42 runs [in the last five overs] but it was one of those days where we see the score quite less in those last five overs, we lost a bit of momentum there. It feels good to be back because this is one stadium where you can enjoy and feel the atmosphere quite lively and obviously the crowd was full and they got a good game as well. [On Tilak turning down the single to David] I think Tilak felt that was a better idea at that point of time. I completely back him. Not an issue, 13 games to go."

Debutant Spencer Johnson: "Absolutely incredible [experience]. Full house here. To get the win is very special. [On the 19th over] I think to stay calm. I had Ash [Nehra] telling me you're going to win the game. To have the backing from him and everyone else, even after going for runs in my first over, it's pretty cool. For me what works well is bowling hard lengths and keeping calm and not panicking and sticking to doing what I do well. This is easily the biggest crowd I've played in front of. I've always wanted to play cricket in india and here I am. I hope we can keep winning. Shubman is unbelievable. He sat next to me on the bus trip. He was calming me. We talked through the game. As a young captain, he's unbelievable."

Roopang : "Difference between two team is Nehraji"

Rajesh: "While everybody plays cricket, Nehra plays football. Always outside the line, passing tips ball by ball! Have not seen other coaching staff do this. Kudos!"

Ahmed: "The whole GT bowling unit is POTM in my opinion!" Indeed! it was a fantastic team effort to choke Mumbai Indians the moment they slowed down a little. Saw an opportunity and grabbed it.

11.25pm What a brilliant comeback from the Titans after Mumbai Indians looked like they were cruising to victory! Sai Kishore bowled beautifully, Rashid Khan was wicketless but economical. But Mohit Sharma with a two-wicket over changed things around before Spencer Johnson responded to an expensive first over in the IPL with two big wickets in the 19th over. The stage was set for Hardik Pandya to take his new team to victory over his old and he started the final over with a six and a four but the experienced Umesh Yadav came out on top eventually. Shubman Gill starts off his first captaincy assignment with a win over his old captain!

Afeef: "Got to commend the GT bowlers and new captain Gill for how they choked MI."

text: Full outside off, Dhawan gives it a gentle push wide of mid-off and Maxwell lets it slip through and the ball gets away for the first four of the match
preText:
Siraj from over the wicket. One slip in place

7.27pm The umpires walk out with the match ball. Mohammed Siraj has locked and loaded and is ready to fire. Shikhar Dhawan walks out with Bairstow. Here we go!

Irfan: "What is the point of including overseas players in subs when you are already playing 4 overseas players in the starting XI?" Well, it allows them to come on as substitute fielders.

You all have a lot of questions for me, but if you want to have some answered by the commentators on Star Sports' Hindi coverage, head over to ESPNcricinfo's mobile site and click on the AskStar button and fire away your queries. There is a good chance you'll have them answered as the innings goes on!

Amith: "I think Faf gave out the batting first sheet at the toss... If they're fielding first, why wouldn't they start with Karn Sharma in the team and bring in DK for the chase?" Yes, it's an odd one! But maybe they are happy to get some overs out of Maxwell and Green, with an extra batter there for the chase. But yeah, not the same XI as Faf said at the toss.

7pm RCB win the toss and bowl. Faf du Plessis says they lost clusters of wickets in the last game and they need to improve on that. They are unchanged from the last game. Shikhar Dhawan says he is looking forward to batting first. Punjab Kings are also unchanged.

RCB XI: Faf du Plessis (capt), Virat Kohli, Rajat Patidar, Glenn Maxwell, Cameron Green, Dinesh Karthik, Anuj Rawat (wk), Alzarri Joseph, Mayank Dagar, Mohammed Siraj, Yash Dayal

Punjab Kings: Shikhar Dhawan (capt), Johnny Bairstow, Prabhsmran Singh, Sam Curran, Jitesh Sharma (wk), Liam Livingstone, Shashank Singh, Harpreet Brar, Harshal Patel, Kagiso Rabada, Rahul Chahar

Subs: Arshdeep Singh, Rilee Rossouw, Tanay Thyagarajan, Harpreet Bhatia, Vidwath Kaverappa

Subs: Suyash Prabhudessai, Mahipal Lomror, Karn Sharma, Vijaykumar Vyshak, Swapnil Singh

6.55pm Simon Katich at the pitch report says it's a rock hard pitch with a bit of grass and should be a high-scoring ground. There are some artificial cracks and it could be a bit two-paced, he says.

Prakyam S: "Looking fwd to see Harshal patel against RCB."

Joy: "All matches have been won by home teams so far in this edition, going by the trend, RCB must have there first win of the season."

Jeyaram: "Bring in Will Jacks in place of Alzarri Joseph and go all guns blazing is the way to go for RCB. They need to get 25 runs above the par score if they have to win." Jacks is an exciting prospect for sure, but for now, I think they will continue with Joseph.

6.37pm RCB's numbers at home are not impressive. This season question marks persist over their death-overs skills and their spin options - and the Chinnaswamy will not allow slips on either front. Here's what Hemant has to say on why Bengaluru brings few home comforts for RCB.

Can Kohli shine in front of the home crowd? Will Arshdeep be key? Got questions about #RCBvsPBKS for Sidhu and Irfan? Go to the ESPNcricinfo homepage on the mobile site, click the Ask Star button at the bottom of the screen, and send in your questions. They could get answered on TV.

Afeef: "Looking forward to watch Liam Livingstone clear the Chinnaswamy roof." The stage is all set for it!

6.30pm Royal Challengers Bangalore Bengaluru are back at the Chinnaswamy after losing their first game of the season in Chennai. The home crowd, who got to celebrate some success recently in the Women's Premier League, will be expected to be vociferous, cheering on their favourites in Virat Kohli, Glenn Maxwell, Mohammed Siraj and co. RCB will be up against Punjab Kings, who clinched victory in their first game of the season and will look to make it two in two. Can they silence the home crowd or will RCB open their tally today? Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of today's IPL clash in Bengaluru. I am Abhimanyu and I'll be joined by Ekanth as we bring you all the action from the Chinnaswamy.

In big news that broke earlier in the day, we have the full schedule for IPL 2024. It's confirmed that the final will be played on May 26 in Chennai. Coming back to today's game, all you need to know about it, you can find in Hemant Brar's preview. Hemant is also at the ground today and he will keep providing valuable insights here and in our live report. The live report, manned by Ashish Pant today, is also your destination for a more detailed coverage of the game with stats, analysis and more.

A quick reminder that you can follow the game live on our site in Hindi as well.

postText:
9.15pm A good finish provided by Shashank Singh, but RCB will likely feel the happier side after this innings. They bowled well, and Punjab Kings never really looked like they got going. There was a critical partnership between Sam Curran and Jitesh Sharma and then Shashank provided the spark at the end. Yash Dayal was excellent, so was Siraj. Alzarri was good but conceded runs at the end. But overall, RCB will be happy with how the bowlers went. The score may not be what you are used to at the Chinnaswamy, but as Curran said, there's something in the wicket for the bowlers, so the chase may not be as straightforward for RCB. Join Ekanth in a bit to see how Kohli and Co. go!

Sam Curran: "I think it's probably slightly under-par but there's a bit in it for the bowlers. I think simple stuff. There's a bit in the wicket. With the new ball they bowled well and there's something for the spinners as well. We are going to go out there with a plan to defend 176."

text: Full down leg, Rawat collects and has a shy at the stumps but misses by a lot as Shashank hurried across for the single. Called wide as well. But it's reviewed, only in vain. The wide call remains

9:26pm Faf and Kohli have been ready for a couple of minutes. Simon Katich says Kings are 20-25 unders, which I is what I think too. But if Kings get the big three cheaply, maybe even contain Kohli, they could be in with a good chance. They get into a huddle as the openers walk out.

text: YJB has dropped it at first slip! Just above head height, tried to take it with both hands but it burst through the palms. He was standing still but leapt last second. Got done for pace, was standing in front of the keeper too. Early life for Kohli. Was a wide length ball, going away with the angle - close to the tramline, the cover drive on-the-up was attempted.
Kohli walks down to cut off the length, drives it on the up, beats cover to the left. Was a length ball but turned into a fullish one.
Down leg and it's helped fine. Three-quarter length just over the pad, glanced with ease.

Guided wide of slip! Length around fifth, he waited and used the pace and angle. Bairstow dives in vain, not in reach this time. That went right off the sticker too
Length on leg, beats the full-faced defence that was attempted
Length outside off, opens the face and taps it towards point

text: Appeal for caught behind, there's a small chat about whether the was catch. Looked like the umpire raised his finger but it is actually sent upstairs. Jitesh dove to the right and took it low, ball went straight in the gloves. Was a wide 137ks length ball that was around the offside tramline. Green tried heaving it square on the offside but even his reach wasn't enough
Length around off, defended in front
Crisp and pure, through cover it races for four. Full around fifth, Patidar eases it with a check. Went off the absolute middle
Length around off, defends with an angled bat. Perhaps too much as it lands just behind and bounces over the stumps
Leathered but Patidar's hit on the non-striker's end. Kohli stayed leg side of the length ball and prioritised power. On the up but he's been happy to take that on today

Midwicket almost pulls off a stunning one-hander. It was Chahar salmon-diving to the left, got hands on it but could only parry it towards mid-on. It turned into a tight run, no direct hit. Was a length ball around off that Kohli tried clobbering across the line. Bat face turned and it went around knee-height. Distance was the issue
Rabada saves three at short third by diving to the left. Was a length ball around off, defended late
Full on the pads, 132ks, swings in and beats the attempted whip across the line
Rabada saves three more, this time with a dive to the right. Was a length ball outside off that was steered off the back foot
Cut to cover off the back foot

text: Bumper sits up and DK hooks it over the fine-leg boundary! Slower one, 126ks, landed short, angled in to go over leg stump. Sat up for DK to get inside the line and launch it. Short fine leg was in, just a 59-metre hit. Brings the equation down to 11 off 7
postText: Mustafa Moudi : "DK yet again playing a DK - Dangerous Knock !!"

text: DK scoops the game back in RCB's favour. Whataguy! This was premeditated but to perfection. He was going square-on and the ball was into the pitch, angling outside off, he got behind it and launched it behind again. Short fine leg was in again, he outplayed a pacer. Again!
preText: AJ: "Can RCB be declared the winner because they have scored more runs by the 19th over " Arshdeep has 10 to defend.

text: Drilled down the ground, DK's reviving himself and takes RCB to a win in their first home game. Arshdeep went full and just outside off, Karthik got across and blasted it flat over the bowler. Too straight for long-on. Crowd are ecstatic
postText:
That was fun. There were unforced errors, teams not capitalising after getting close to taking home the advantage. Kohli's intent™️ chat won't be too loud given how he exploded at the start. But both teams got a lot of things right tactically and skill-wise, which made it a great game for the neutrals too. Hope that trend continues as the tournament progresses and that you follow it along with us, here on Cricinfo.

Harit Gautam: ""We had to pay the price for dropping Kohli" hope the selectors don't have to repeat Dhawan's words after the World Cup "

Kozhakks: "Loved the post match presentation from Kohli! The camaraderie between Harsha and Kohli was evident in that. "

[Dancing down and hitting over cover to pacers] I had to, bowlers know I play the cover drive pretty well. So they won't allow me to hit gaps. Guys like KG and Arshdeep, if they are hitting length, you have to create momentum, once you're closer to the ball you negate the bounce. You have to come up with a game plan and try to keep improving. I know my name is often used to just promote the T20 game across the world these days but still got it I guess. [Last two months] We were not in the country. We were at a place where people weren't recognizing us. Just to feel normal for two months was a surreal experience. Of course, things become totally different with two kids from a family perspective. Just being together, the connection with the older kid too is amazing. I couldn't have been more grateful to God for the opportunity that I got to spend time with the family. I was telling the guys that the voices got that much louder as it wasn't the case for the last two months. It was amazing to be another person on the road. I don't play for caps, it's just another opportunity. (2/2)

Virat Kohli, POTM: [To the crowd] Don't get overexcited, it's just two games. I know what this (orange cap) means. [Love story with the crowd] It's been going on for years. People talk a lot about playing the sport. At the end of the day you don't talk about the achievements, stats or numbers but the memories. It's what Rahul Dravid says. The friendship, love, appreciation, backing has been amazing and is what you'll miss and never forget. In T20, I'm opening, I try to give the team a blazing start. But when wickets start falling, you have to understand the conditions as well. The wicket wasn't as placid as normal here. It was a bit two-paced. Had to play correct cricketing shots, couldn't hit balls across the line. Tried a few, felt like I needed big hits at the other end, which didn't happen as Maxi and Anuj got out quickly. Disappointed not having finished it off. It was a slot ball that I sliced straight to deep point. Not a bad bad though playing after two months and getting into the tournament. (1/2)

Faf du Plessis, RCB captain: [Was he cool] Only on the outside, not as much on the inside. Gotta make sure you get over the line early in the tournament. Great to see the composure at the end. Don't think game was gone after Kohli went, because of the Impact Player and Mahipal in. In previous years we used to feel 12 runs in the last overs would be tough but now even 15s seem gettable in the last two. Really pleased for DK getting his game going. It sets us up for the rest of the tournament. Games get won at lost at the No. 7 and 8 position with the Impact subs, so he's key. Our plan at the auction was to find the DNA of the team. It's tough on this unique ground. The pitch was a bit different. Kohli's is still the same person, has had a nice break. It helps keep fresh in the back end of the career.

Dinesh Karthik Getting there [past the rust] I wasn't completely in control but it started to feel good. We needed the partnership with Lomror, he took the pressure off me with that six. It was critical, he batted well. Harshal is a wily customer. If you miss the dipping slower ball, you're done, so I had to time the scoop well. Lomror looked calm, didn't tell him anything at first. Told him to put that behind after he hit that six, then keep his head still and the rest will follow through. He's been batting well in the nets too.

Shikhar Dhawan, Punjab Kings captain: Good game, we brought it back. Think we were 10-15 less. Should have encashed in the first six overs. We had to pay the price for dropping Kohli. We lost momentum there, it was crucial. It looked a good wicket but wasn't true. It was stopping, bit of double-bounce and turned. 70% it was coming good. I was happy with my runs but think could've played faster in the first six. We lost two wickets which put pressure too. That total we thought was par. Match went till last over, at the end we could have bowled better. Harpreet is bowling really well, that too to left-handers on a small ground. He soaked in pressure and got breakthroughs. His celebration, the Kabaddi thing, is big in Punjab. People connect with the thigh-five, happy to see him doing it

11:14pm It was a twist-y turn-y chase. Kings were in it despite the unforced error. But Kohli gave RCB liftoff and DK landed the plane safely. All games this season have been won by the home team. RCB's record hasn't been great but that wasn't an issue tonight. The biggest event seemed to have taken place at the start of the chase, when Bairstow dropped Kohli. It unleashed one of the best players, and indeed flayers, in cricket. Him charging pacers and clubbing them through extra is what we've imagined doing as kids. The overseas stars failed. Promoting Green to No. 3 and Patidar over Maxwell didn't work. Harpreet was sensational, Rabada was good too. The constant wickets almost derailed the chase, especially Kohli fell due to some smart field placement. But DK came in with ice in the veins, got Lomror for support and the duo cleared the game with great skill and calmness.

Raab: "As a Bangladeshi, just had PTSD watching DK bat like this. If you know, you know. "

text: Wide and full. The angle takes it too far. DK leans and shapes to play but knows he doesn't have to. Gets the wide and the stumps' lights are doing their own dance

shortText: Azmatullah Omarzai to Gaikwad, no run
text: Good length ball to start off just outside off. Gaikwad shimmies down and pushes to backward point
preText:
7.29pm All set then. Out come the two umpires, followed by the two CSK openers, Rachin Ravindra and Ruturaj Gaikwad. The GT team stride out too, led by Shubman Gill. Gaikwad will take strike. Azmatullah Omarzai to take the new ball. He got some swing in the first game. He is over the wicket with one slip in place.

Amarnath: "What if they bring in Theekshana or Santner instead of Pathirana in the 2nd innings..Just to take the opposition off guard." Santner. Theekshana isn't in the subs list.

7.20pm That is a bold call from CSK to go with just one genuine spin option at Chepauk. Santner might still come in as a sub, though Gaikwad said that Pathirana will be included. Titans have a balanced side, and will bank on their batters to chase down anything. Will we see Rachin Ravindra getting a bowl here? And on the subject of Rachin, here's Deiva about an unlikely Wellington reunion in Chennai.

Elsewhere, India chase their FIFA World Cup dream in a qualification match against Afghanistan in what happens to be Sunil Chhetri's 150th match. Follow it live, here.

Here's Daryl Mitchell: Excited to see the first game here in front of a full crowd at home. (CSK fanbase) Its amazing. Coming from a little country at the bottom of the earth, this is really special. (Gujarat Titans' challenge) They've been at the pointy end of the last two tournaments, they know how to win. For us it is to control what we can, do the little things well. (New captain) He's obviously a good man. He's a world-class batter at the top of the order. He is cool and calm like MS. (Chennai conditions, typical?) The characteristics of the pitch are similar to what we've seen at CSK.

Aditya: "Woah! The new generation of captaincy coming into effect! You normally don't see Dhoni making bold changes like these but Gaikwad is ready to take it on. Loving it!"

Sai: "Great prediction, Joy!"

Tariq : "Omerzai will be interesting to watch with bat and same as Rashid"

Playing XIs

Chennai Super Kings:: 1 Ruturaj Gaikwad (capt), 2 Rachin Ravindra, 3 Ajinkya Rahane, 4 Daryl Mitchell, 5 Shivam Dube, 6 Ravindra Jadeja, 7 Sameer Rizvi, 8 MS Dhoni (wk), 9 Deepak Chahar, 10 Tushar Deshpande, 11 Mustafizur Rahman

Subs: Matheesha Pathirana, Shardul Thakur, Shaik Rasheed, Nishant Sindhu, Mitchell Santner

Gujarat Titans: 1 Wriddhiman Saha (wk), 2 Shubman Gill (capt), 3 Azmatullah Omarzai, 4 David Miller, 5 Vijay Shankar, 6 Rahul Tewatia, 7 Rashid Khan, 8 R Sai Kishore, 9 Umesh Yadav, 10 Mohit Sharma, 11 Spencer Johnson

Subs: Sai Sudharsan, BR Sharath, Abhinav Manohar, Manav Suthar, Noor Ahmad

7pm Toss: Gujarat Titans have won the toss and will bowl first. Titans are going in unchanged, but CSK have one change. They have Pathirana coming in for Theekshana.

Gill: That [first] match was very physically and mentally exhausting. Quick turnaround, but we are are used to it. It was a tremendous feeling to be able to be down in the game and then come back. It showed the character of our team. We are going with the same team.

Huge applause for Gaikwad: We were looking to bowl first. Wicket is similar to what we had in the first game. Batting first here is not much difference. I would say, slightly rusty start but we came back well. And once we came back we did not allow them to be back. Everyone showed good intent. In place of Theeskahana, we have our Malinga, Pathirana.

Pitch report from Anjum Chopra and Mathew Hayden: Lovely to be back. Really good wicket. There was quite a lot of bounce in the first game. There is a lot of grass on the surface. Very unusual for Chepauk to have grass. The way Chahar bowled in the first game, it was carrying really nicely through. There are patches where it is a little uneven with the grass surface. Very much inside the first four or five overs to do the damage and then the spin comes into its own and it gets tough. That is where CSK come to their own. It is a bat first wicket.

6.55pm Another interesting subplot in this game is the Chennai boys vs Chennai Super Kings. Titans have as many as five Tamil Nadu players in their side - Sai Sudharsan, Sai Kishore, Vijay Shankar, Shahrukh Khan and Sandeep Warrier. Among the quintet, Sudharsan, Kishore and Vijay are set to slot into Titans' XI or XII (accounting for the Impact Player). Sudharsan, Kishore and Vijay all have been part of CSK or Junior Super Kings, their grassroots programme. And back in the day, Shahrukh used to be a ball boy at Chepauk for IPL matches. In contrast, CSK don't have a single local player in their main squad.

CricDude: "GT needs to relook at their middle order. Except Tewatia, all others take time to settle. They need to bring in Abhinav Manohar who can keep the run rate up."

6.50pm New captains Gill and Gaikwad have already grabbed the headlines with their captaincy. After Titans snatched victory from Mumbai debutant Spencer Johnson talked up Gill's leadership, saying the captain sat alongside him on the bus to help calm his nerves in the lead-up to the game. As for Gaikwad, he rifled through fielding changes in his first game as IPL captain, and one such change, which involved extra-cover moving to sweeper cover, brought CSK their first wicket. The two new captains will once again be in the spotlight. Here's Deivarayan Muthu with the preview.

Joy: "If Pathirana is good to go, I would bring him in for Theekshana. If the pitch proves to be assisting spinners a bit, there will be the option of using Rachin."

6.40pm Remember the last time CSK and Titans came face-to-face? It was the final of IPL 2023 which began on a Sunday and ended on a Tuesday. In between there was a clash which ebbed and flowed like you won't believe. And in the end, with CSK requiring 10 off 2, Ravindra Jadeja struck a six and a four to help CSK secure a fifth IPL final. If the two teams can recreate even half of the drama from that game, we're in for some fun.

6.30pm Hello and welcome to match number 7 of IPL 2024 as Chennai Super Kings get all set to host Gujarat Titans. Both teams made a winning start to their season. While CSK got the better of RCB in a high-octane clash on the opening day of the tournament, Titans scored a sensational come-from-behind win against Mumbai Indians on home territory. Six games so far this season, six wins for home teams. Can Titans buck the trend and breach Fortress Chepauk or will CSK continue their winning run at home? I am Ashish Pant, and will soon be joined by Sreshth Shah as we try and answer all your questions from what should be a pulsating clash.

9.21pm: Right, so CSK finish on 206 for 6. It's not a normal Chepauk surface, absolute belter today. But you have to think that CSK are above par. The impetus was provided by Rachin, who came out all guns blazing smashing a 20-ball 46, hacking six fours and three sixes. Once he fell, it was Gaikwad and Rahane who took the innings forward before Shivam Dube took over. He hammered two fours and five sixes, taking down Sai Kishore and Rashid. Sameer Rizvi, in his first IPL stint, then crashed Rashid for a six first ball to take CSK past 200. Can Titans chase this down? Join Sreshth in a bit to find out.

postText:
Q: What do you think of having two bouncers in an over? And does it benefit bowlers who like to go pace-on or those who prefer variations like cutters?

Pathan: I love this rule, there's something for bowlers. There are so many rules only for batters. Now the rules are coming in with something for the bowlers. Especially in T20 cricket, guys who use variations can get a lot of benefits. Pace-on bowlers, the bouncers can take outside edges, etc. So it will hugely benefit bowlers with variations.

Another question answered by Irfan Pathan

Q: Which Indian fast bowler will have a breakout season? (Harshit Rana, Yash Thakur, Yash Dayal, Akash Madhwal)

Pathan: Very excited for Mohsin Khan, provided he plays all the games. I think Yash Dayal was very impressive especially on that pitch, swinging the ball the way he did. In the first few overs, he put his senior partner Siraj behind him. As I always believe, left is right. So any gun left-armer.. I want to see with Yash Dayal, how he does when he is under the pump. After wat has happened last year, there will always be question marks. So it is important for him to have a couple of games under pressure.

preText:
Question for Irfan Pathan: All young batters have seen a dip in their strike rate the season they have been named captain. Why is this trend there and will we see the same with Gill and Gaikwad?

Answer: With Gill especially, we don't associate a big strike rate with him. Last year he had a fantastic strike rate. But before that season his strike rate in T20s was 127. So he has always been a guy who takes his time, thinks about batting long. So I don't think that's the case with him. Ruturaj Gaikwad is the kind of player who looks for a big strike rate, score quick runs. Today, Rachin was taking an aggressive approach. But I think Ruturaj was also waiting for Rashid Khan, who has played very well. So I don't think it will affect these guys.

Maphaka to open the bowling. Here we go.

7.30pm Mayank Agarwal and Travis Head walk out. The Mumbai players are in a huddle.

Northpaw : "So excited to see Maphaka in action! A future superstar. But we have to remember the lad's not even 18 yet... Whatever happens, invaluable experience will be gained by him. All the power to you, Kwena and good luck! "

Watch Tom Moody, Mitch McClenaghan and Wasim Jaffer on our T20 Time Out live.

hari: "mark my words, Maphaka is going to be lethal, especially with the bouncers..."

How many times have Indian sports fans seen their best player let down by their team? Those days may be in the past for Indian cricket, but for Sunil Chhetri and Indian football, it's still the main tale.

7.20pm ESPNcricinfo has learned that Luke Wood has a minor knee issue, and is expected to be fit for their next game on Monday.

Praveen: "Rahul Tripathi doesn't even make the squad?" --- Yeah, guess when you have Head, Agarwal and Abhishek, it's difficult to fit in Tripathi.

7.15pm Maphaka has had an excellent U-19 World Cup earlier this year. In case you want to know more about him, go here.

NM: "You have listed Cummins as (capt) but not for Pandya. Fanning the flames? " - Ha, nothing like that. Just an oversight. If you see, didn't put wk against Kishan's name either!

Here are the XIs:

Sunrisers Hyderabad: 1 Travis Head, 2 Mayank Agarwal, 3 Abhishek Sharma, 4 Aiden Markram, 5 Heinrich Klaasen (wk), 6 Abdul Samad, 7 Shahbaz Ahmed, 8 Pat Cummins (capt), 9 Bhuvneshwar Kumar, 10 Mayank Markande, 11 Jaydev Unadkat
Impact Players: Nitish Kumar Reddy, Glenn Phillips, Umran Malik, Washington Sundar, Upendra Yadav

Mumbai Indians: 1 Ishan Kishan (Wk), 2 Rohit Sharma, 3 Naman Dhir, 4 Tilak Varma, 5 Hardik Pandya (capt), 6 Tim David, 7. Shams Mulani, 8 Gerald Coetzee, 9 Piyush Chawla, 10 Jasprit Bumrah, 11 Kwena Maphaka
Impact Players: Dewald Brevis, Romario Shepherd, Mohammed Nabi, Nehal Wadhera, Vishnu Vinod

7pm Mumbai Indians have won the toss and they will field first. "We as a group want to make sure we do right things all the time," their captain Hardik Pandya says. Luke Wood misses out with a niggle. Kwena Maphaka makes his IPL debut. Sunrisers have made two changes. Travis Head comes in for Marco Jansen. T Natarajan has got a niggle, so Unadkat comes in.

Here are the XIs:

6.50pm Brian Lara says during the pitch report that he would prefer batting first on this surface, which has no grass at all. He says the best time to bat will be the first five to ten overs as the ball will start gripping later on and cutters is the way to go for seamers. The square boundaries are 63 metres and 66 metres. Down the ground it is 76 metres.

madyeti: "All games so far have been won by the home team. Hopefully SRH keeps this up."

6.40pm Sachin Tendulkar just presented Rohit Sharma with a special 200 jersey. This is Rohit's 200th IPL game for Mumbai Indians.

DT: "Any updates about Surya Kumar Yadav?" --- He is still at the NCA, recovering from ankle surgery. And Wanindu Hasaranga continues to be unavailable for SRH.

6.35pm One thing to look forward in today's game is the battle between Heinrich Klaasen, arguably the best T20 batter right now, and Jasprit Bumrah, the ace seamer. They are likely to come face-to-face at the death. Abhimanyu captures that, and more, in his preview. Irfan Pathan, Tom Moody, Mitchell McClenaghan also discuss how Mumbai can counter the Klaasen threat here.

6.30pm Hello and welcome to match 8 of IPL 2024. It's Sunrisers Hyderabad vs Mumbai Indians in Hyderabad. Both teams lost their opening game - Mumbai lost to Gujarat Titans and SRH to KKR - and will be keen to open their account. I am Hemant Brar and will soon be joined by Abhimanyu Bose as we bring you all the action.

9.33pm Well, what a rush that was! Can we expect more of the same from Rohit, Kishan and co in the chase? Will be nothing short of a miracle if Mumbai Indians do make a game out of this. Stay tuned!

We do have a new highest score in the league in IPL 2024. But what else has been new this season? Think you've been the league's biggest fan? Test your knowledge with this quiz by my colleague and passionate quizzer Sreshth Shah.

preText: Shiva: "Last 3 overs.. 18 runs! That's the Game for SRH"

text: Length ball outside off, Hardik can only slap it down the ground to long-off. The pace-off strategy has been working wonders for SRH
preText: Jisan : "15 th over sealed the game, millionaire man delivered" He did indeed! Although, the game is still alive

text: Unadkat bowls a legcutter back of a leng outside off. David had moved his bat out of the way but attempted to swat it away very late. Can't get it past the keeper
Full and wide again, David can only get it off the toe end to deep midwicket
Full and wide, David throws his bat at it but misses. Called wide, but SRH review. The umpire's decision is upheld
Slower bouncer outside off, Hardik pulls it and it goes high in the air but falls short of deep midwicket
Just short of long-on. Yorker-length on off, Hardik jams his bat down and it goes in the air flat, but falls just short of Markram
preText: Jabba: "Bumrah and Cummins are different mustard. The difference today is Cummins took a couple of wickets"

text: Back of a length outside off, pulled away to deep midwicket for a couple
Low full toss and David doesn't miss out! Flicks it away over deep square leg for his first six today
Bouncer outside off, David goes for the pull but gets a top edge over the keeper and four. Lucky runs for MI, but they won't complain
Swatted away over extra cover! Bhuvi digs it into the pitch outside off, David plays it almost like a tennis forehand shot. Goes all the way
Bhuvneshwar closes out the over with a yorker on off that David can just dig out towards mid-off
Full and wide, David extends is arms to reach it and slaps it down along the ground. Long-on and long-off didn't stand a chance
preText: So, this match officially has the highest number of runs in an IPL game!

text: Nails the yorker just outside off, David can only dig it out to extra cover

What a fielding effort! Bouncer outside off and Hardik slaps it wide of long-on. Mayank races across to his right and grabs it head height and throws it back in before falling over backwards. He also seems to have hurt himself. The check shows Mayank got rid of the ball before his feet touched the ground. Excellent, excellent fielding
postText: Mayank is good to continue after a concussion check

text: Nails it and send it into the second tier! Length ball angled into David and he swings it away majestically
Length ball, but way wide of off. Umpire has his arms up
Slower short ball just outside off, David dabs it to backward point

wkt_text: HH Pandya c †Klaasen b Unadkat 24 (40m 20b 1x4 1x6) SR: 120.00
text: And Hardik Pandya has to go! Unadkat is all laughs. SRH know they now all but have it in the bag. Cutter dug into the pitch, seaming away. Hardik goes for a pull but can only top edge it. Easy peasy lemon squeezy for Heinrich Klaasen
postText: Romario Shephard comes out as the impact substitute for Mumbai Indians. He replaces Maphaka

text: Cummins starts off short outside off, David swings it away on the bounce to deep midwicket. That was at 120kph
Slower bouncer from Cummins and Shepherd can only help it out to deep square leg
Short outside off, David manages to pull it away to deep backward square off an inside edge
preText: The 37 sixes today is the int-most in a T20 match ever, Sampath chimes in.

text: Slower bouncer outside off, he goes to pull but is beaten on height
Cummins sticks to the short ball plan. Digs it in short outside off, David skies it but it lands safe around midwicket
Short again, pulled out to deep square leg
On a length outside off, punched wide of long-off for just a single
preText: So Sunrisers Hyderabad have mathematically won this one, unless they bowl a bucketload of no balls. Mayank Markande will close it out for them
postText: Hardik: "Seems ironic coming from me.. but Hardik is to be vlamed for his mediocre strike rate in the outcome of this game..." Hey, brave of you to shoulder the blame!

text: Length ball outside off, Shepherd frees his arm and deposits over long-on. Most sixes in a T20 game!
Legbreak tossed up outside off, Shepherd can't connect
Full outside off, Shepherd moves across the stumps and smacks it down the ground for a boundary
On a length outside off, punched out through cover point for another boundary
Wide on a length, Jaiswal middles it first up. Punches it with the swing, away from the body, to point.
preText:
7:29pm Nanda Kishore and Nitin Menon are the umpires walking out. Capitals' players follow them. Jaiswal and Buttler to open for RR of course. Khaleel has the ball. Slip in, wide gully/short third too.

7:23pm The skies are completely dark, the aerial shots show just how prominently pink the stands are. Might not be a sellout but the attendance seems healthy. The pitch has patches of mint-chutney green. Straight boundaries from one side are smaller and the other bigger. Square ones, as mentioned in the report, are 67 metres each.

Matthew: "Boult listed at 8? Going up in the world, he's normally 10 or 11, even in T20s! " Yeah, they are banking on their mainstays. They have gone with three overseas players, which means Burger or Powell can come in depending on how they go. But the point holds

Hari: "Even with impact player, RR only has 6 batters? they badly need a batting allrounder for worst case situations..." It was a concern last year but they're happy to adapt based on how things are going in the first innings, like in the last game.

Vivaan: "@Ekanth Fraser McGurk cannot be subbed in because DC area already starting with 4 overseas players :p" Oh yeah, sorry. Thanks for correcting

Yoel: "Will we finally see Fraser-McGurk play? " He's likely to be subbed in. Hopefully, DC don't have an injury again

Tarun: "What happened to Prithivi? Is he injured? " No, tactical call.

For key insights along the game, check out Sidharth Monga's Live Blog

RR Impact Subs list: Rovman Powell, Nandre Burger, Tanush Kotian, Shubham Dubey, Kuldeep Sen

Rajasthan Royals: 1 Jos Buttler, 2 Yashasvi Jaiswal, 3 Sanju Samson (capt, wk), 4 Riyan Parag, 5 Shimron Hetmyer, 6 Dhruv Jurel, 7 R Ashwin, 8 Trent Boult, 9 Avesh Khan, 10 Sandeep Sharma, 11 Yuzvendra Chahal

DC Impact Subs list: Abhishek Porel, Jake Fraser-McGurk, Pravin Dubey, Kumar Kushgara, Rasikh Dar

Delhi Capitals: 1 David Warner, 2 Mitchell Marsh, 3 Ricky Bhui, 4 Rishabh Pant (capt, wk), 5 Tristan Stubbs, 6 Axar Patel, 7 Sumit Kumar, 8 Kuldeep Yadav, 9 Anrich Nortje, 10 Khaleel Ahmed, 11 Mukesh Kumar

Sanju Samson: We also would've bowled because of the dew that is expected. Both pitches look similar, this has an even covering of grass. The teams here are very competitive. We have good players and will play good sides. Playing the same team

Rishabh Pant: Wicket is fine but we want to use it when conditions are dry. Feels good to play 100 games for the same franchise but not thinking about it too much. Most of the concerns will be injury-based. We could've got the last game if Ishant's injury wasn't there. Gotta control what we can. Ishant hasn't recovered and Shai Hope has a bad back, Mukesh Kumar and Anrich Nortje come in.

7pm Murali Karthik is out for the toss with the captains - Sanju Samson and Rishab Pant. Pant calls heads, he's right. Delhi Capitals will bowl

With five minutes to go to the toss, Rishabh Pant gets a jersey with 100 written behind. This will Pant's his 100th IPL game. Delhi Capitals, Daredevils previously, is the only team he's represented in the tournament.

Mohit Arya: "I feel if today Samson scores a fifty this could be breakthrough season for him 600 season, well we all hope so!"

Vince: "Is a rock hard pitch high or low scoring?" I think (and hope) high.

Pitch report: Equidistant square of the wicket with 67 metres. 76 metres down the ground. Simon Katich says RR have done their homework after a poor home showing last season. Pitch 5 was used twice, they made 237 and got bundled for 60. They'll hope to change that trend. It's a rock-hard pitch. When the cracks are pressed, there is a bit of movement which indicates there could be low bounce with the new ball, which was the case in the first game too. Going into the pitch with cutters, going high with the bouncers - something Sandeep did well - is expected to work. Both teams have had issues chasing. RR did well batting first last game, so they might prefer that.

Mukesh Kumar going full throttle, says Shashank, from the ground. Likely to come in for one of Ishant or Khaleel Ahmed

Nandre Burger interview with Shashank Kishore: 'I didn't want to be a cricketer, it was a free way to study'

6:40pm Kumar Sangakkara is currently addressing RR's players in the huddle. Samson smiles before they break jauntily. Theirs is a five-head 5D chess group that's looking to recreate home dominance which was lost in the last season. Jaiswal's still blazing, Parag's hit the ground running and will get a good run at No. 4, Jurel's coming on a high too. Buttler needs to hit form and Samson needs to find a way to carry his form deep into the season. Chahal and Ashwin are their big-name spinners. Sandeep is can be a specialist wherever you want him to be. Their Impact Sub selections are smart too. Expect them to be formidable.

Match Preview: Shaky Capitals look to raise their game at high-flying Royals' den

Mustafa Moudi: "Its really strange that DC didnt pick Prithvi Shaw in their opening match. Yes, he has a terrible season last year but that doesnt make him a Poor Batsman. They should back him as we all know how destructive he can be whenever he gets going. They must learn from RR who backed Jaiswal, when he was failing initially and rest is history. Similar thing is happening with Parag too !!"

6:30pm It's pink city, it's home-team advantage, it's run fests. The trends at the 17th edition of the IPL have been strong and Rajasthan Royals will hope to continue it against Delhi Capitals. Rishabh Pant's comeback last week was amazing, more for his return than his performance. His keeping was solid and his range-hitting - including some competition with Jake Fraser-McGurk in the lead-up to this game, has been good. Ishant Sharma, who got injured while fielding last game, is available. Anrich Nortje is expected to play, Prithvi Shaw might be out. Capitals need their middle order to fire.

text: Doesn't time the flat-bat flap but it clears mid-off, Stubbs ran back but it landed a few metres after sailing past him. Was a shortish 135ks ball outside off that Jaiswal tried to muscle while on the move, ball got big on him.
preText:
Seems to be a delay, might be sightscreen-related.

Vinod Rajpal: "Hello Eknath, will the law of average work tonight...can away team win the match ?" The toss has gone their way, so it is likely

text: Tad back of length at the body, tucked to midwicket
Pitched up on the pads, inside edge off the gentle flick goes onto pad and deflects towards fine leg
postText: Sowmya : "If anything, teams need to hold on to their catches. We all saw what happened after Head was dropped last night."

text: Fullish outside off, 137ks, Buttler's upper body leans to reach for the drive to the right of mid-off
Jaiswal miscues again, Khaleel's had the better of him this over. Went real full and angling into the pad this time, Jaiswal tried whipping it through midwicket and inside edged it.
postText: More than the swing, pace and bounce seemed stark in the first over in my eyes

text: Chopped wide of leg stump. Wide and full, Buttler reached out to drive on the up through cover. Too much to do while hitting on the up and aiming square, luckily he gets a single to fine leg
preText: Mukesh on.

text: Trots down and drives wide of mid-off. This is what Kohli did in Bengaluru, get down to length balls and punch it on the up. this one was from top-of-pad height.
preText: Around the wicket

shortText: Mukesh Kumar to Jaiswal, no run
text: Fullish on the pads, might've got a thin edge on the flick onto pad

shortText: Mukesh Kumar to Jaiswal, no run
text: Mukesh beats him on the cover drive this time. Wide on a three-quarter length, 136ks, a bit of shape away in the air. Jaiswal going for the full-blooded drive again
postText: Harsha: "Is Jaiswal having 2 sets of pads on each other? Or is his pad chipped out?" Might be the latter

wkt_text: YBK Jaiswal  b Mukesh Kumar 5 (11m 7b 1x4 0x6) SR: 71.42
text: Is that one stump out the ground or two? Looks like off stump was flattened and middle rattled. The flying bails was shiver-inducing. Seam-bowling special. 141ks on a length, angling in from around the wicket, decked in to cramp Jaiswal for room on the flick, ball ricocheted off the bat onto the stumps.

shortText: Mukesh Kumar to Samson, no run
text: Length ball angling back in, Samson tries to play it straight. Might've been another inside edge
preText: Ump asks Samson to get ready quickly, which he does. Slip in, over the wicket
postText: Chuvi: "One has always felt Mukesh is the seam bowling clone of Shami. Way to go but that was the first impression one got"

text: Ooh, Buttler still happy to have a big crack. Wide and full, angling away, he tries to slay it through cover and misses
preText: Slip and wide-ish gully in

text: Buttler fending away from the body, thickish edge doesn't carry to gully. Lands low to his left and pops back. Was a wide length ball which Buttler played late and tentatively
postText: Karthik: "Yashasvi didn't look comfortable at all today "

text: Three-quarter length on fourth, defended cautiously off the back foot, towards mid-on
Length outside off, wide-ish and let go again
Angle takes it too wide, Samson has no need to play that length ball
postText: "If the ball rises a bit higher than expected, the difference between Jaiswal and Travis Head is imminent, "Dr Rajeev Tyagi observes. "Head sends it behind the stump, Jaiswal tries to pull. Huge difference in the outcome! "

text: Khaleel continues being disciplined. Length, angling in towards top of off at 141ks, defended to the left of the bowler.
preText: Around
postText: Simon Katich makes a good point about how the extra air speed from DC's bowlers is making a difference unlike the last game here

text: Length on leg, clipped to midwicket
Tentative wipe but it gets four to third. Back of length around sixth, may have shaped away a bit. Samson managed to play it with soft hands and got it wide of the diving gully fielder
preText: Shubha : "Mukesh bowls that utterly uncomfortable length at a fair pace. Irrespective of the format, that is bound to buy you wickets" Here he is again. Slip and wide gully in

text: Proper bumper, proper pull! Not that bad a ball, 144ks, landed very short and rose to around neck-height. Samson was inside the crease and slapped it up and over. The surprise ball doesn't work
Lovely square punch. Samson stood leg side of the length ball on off, he was just waiting for it to arrive and then opened the face to guide it in the gap in front of point
preText: Field has been changed. Deep third and square leg are out

text: Worked off the back foot, Nortje runs to the diagonal left from mid-on and stops three. 135ks on a back of length, angling in at the body, that was really well timed, again
preText: Short 45 moves to cover point
postText: Vinod Rajpal: "Please stop discussing on Mukesh Kumar, he is now leaking runs !"

shortText: Mukesh Kumar to Buttler, no run
text: Buttler's trying to go big but can't. DC's plan to him seems to be keeping it wide, away from his arc and reach. This three-quarter length ball did both, he tried flaying it square and missed it
Good reactions from both players. Buttler charged down to cut the angle but Mukesh probbaly saw him and went length on leg, Buttler was inside the line and managed to glance it to fine leg
postText: The Goan: "Probably controversial take, but in my opinion RR has the best top 3 in the IPL. Thoughts?" I'll go CSK irrespective of who's in cos that's how that team seems to work. On a serious note, it is a good take. RCB's isn't too bad either

text: Length outside off, tapped to point
Beaten on the stand-and-deliver square-drive. Hard length around fifth
preText: Northe i. Slip is wide and far

text: Chipped uppishly, clears the bowler and lands safely. Mid-on runs to the left and stops it. Length ball around the stumps, Samson stood outside leg and check-punched it
Wide on a length, around sixth stump, Buttler bends his back across and clips it to mid-on. Away from the body but unlike the attempted drives, he made contact here
postText: Ahmed: "Butler needs a good score. It's time. He is too good of a player to be so muted for long time!!"

text: Sharp bumper, pacy but it's too high. No, not a wide. Was outside off and let go
Length around fifth, Samson tries to run it down to third with a fully open bat face. Misses. Sniffin-leather stuff
postText: Siddhesh: "Nah CSK has the best top 7 or 8 or even 9. Unmatched in terms of batting depth especially with the impact player rule. RR definitely has a very good top 3 though. "

text: Good yorker, Buttler squeezes it out well. It was angling to off, Buttler went low and got a thick outside edge as he tried to jam it, ball goes to deep third

wkt_text: SV Samson c †Pant b Ahmed 15 (19m 14b 3x4 0x6) SR: 107.14
text: Guided to the keeper! Khaleel's around-the-wicket-angle works. He's cramped Samson for room, who tried to back away and chop the 141ks into-the-pitch ball through point. Ends up nicking it to Pant. Khaleel's jubilant, DC's new-ball bowlers have made it their powerplay.
Short-arm whip to mid-on first up. Whiplash in followthrough too, full and at the body
preText: Back over the wicket

text: Bouncer beats the pull!. Parag tries to take it on with a powerful hit, too quick
postText: Neel : "How's the pitch, again?" It's offered good pace and bounce. DC have used their angles really well too

text: Pitched up outside off, driven to cover
preText: Around. Square leg goes back, informs Shashank

text: Funky don't work either. Parag shuffles across early and tries to paddle the length ball over short fine, he misses and the ball misses off stump.
postText: Sunitha : "So Buttler has to anchor for the time being "

text: Very short. Too much, definite wide this time. Pacy at 142ks but it kept elevating, Parag started shaping to play it but decided to leave
postText: Sheernali SG: "Looks like Delhi is set to break the norm of this IPL so far - to beat the home team"

text: Ah, the flat-trajectory familiarity. Shortish and on leg, 96ks, worked towards midwicket
preText: Axar comes in, from around

text: Fullish around off, tentative push. Goes off the outer-half of the bat to mid-off. 98ks, looked like Parag initially wanted to work it to mid-on
Tucked towards midwicket, Buttler wanted two - even went halfway down. Stubbs came in and threw it on the bounce to the non-striker's end, the batter was hurried and put a full-length dive
Hit to deep square leg. Might've been a thickish inside edge
postText: Deep: "Nice spell upfront from Khaleel. Like Jaydev Unadkat, Shivam Dube, and Barinder Sran - I feel like Khaleel's first stint with international cricket came when his game hadn't fully developed. He certainly looks better now with his lines."

text: Length dart on leg, tries to nudge it square. Misses. 100ks
Fullish around off, Buttler tries punching towards mid-off. Gets it off the inside-half of the bat and to the bowler. 99ks
postText:
Raj: "This feels like a test match after yesterday "

TRock: "Good to see bowlers in the game today. "

text: Full around off, just 83ks, Parag leans across and gets real low to punch it to long-off
preText: Kuldeep on now

wkt_text: JC Buttler lbw b Kuldeep Yadav 11 (43m 16b 0x4 0x6) SR: 68.75
text: Beaten on the reverse, lbw appeal turned down. Kuldeep took the matter, and literally Rishabh's hands, into his own and signalled the T. Where did this pitch though? Buttler tried playing it on the up, got beaten and ball hit just under the knee-roll, outer-half of the pad. It has pitched in line and Kuldeep might as well have Hawk-Eye tech embedded in him cos the ball is projected to land in line and go on to smash leg peg. It landed around a back of length too, which makes his conviction look even better. Buttler tried to break out of his struggle but perishes in the attempt

shortText: Kuldeep Yadav to Ashwin, no run
text: Length around off, tries clipping it to midwicket. Uppish leading edge takes it to cover
preText: Ashwin up at No. 5

text: Length on off, backs away and punches it to deep point
postText: Neel looks at the positives : "The perfect situation for RR middle order to shine .. early days eh?"

shortText: Kuldeep Yadav to Parag, no run
text: Full around off, pushed to the left of cover. 103ks
Length at the stumps, 95ks, worked to deep midwicket
Darted on a back of length on leg, punched off the back foot to long-on
Clips it off the pads to midwicket
postText: Bhargav : "Butler and RR seem sleep walking " ouch

text: Fullish around fourth, punched to deep point
Maybe like Matthew Hayden said on air, Ashwin might have been in to tackle spin. They are trying to milk them too. This is clipped off the pads to midwicket
postText: Shashank from a little while back - From 'Buttler, Buttler', Warner has got the crowd behind him at the long-off boundary chanting his name. All he had to do was shake a leg, do that signature 'Pushpa' dance move that once became a rage. And they're all cheering for him now.

text: Too short and Parag ends the 31-ball boundary drought. It was 103ks, angled in at the pads, helped away with the pull from waist-height and got it to the long-leg fence
Tries to clip the shortish ball with the closed face. Misses. Timeout
postText:
The Goan: "And just like that, my take that RR has the best top 3 has been smashed out of the park. Just like the RR top 3. "

JustForMyInfo: "Can Umpire agree to such forced signals? " Actually a fair question. Guess Pant was okay with it. Would've been completely different drama if he wasn't. Not sure what the rules are either

text: Full on the pads, clipped to long-on
preText: DC well ahead right now. Will RR continue to consolidate, when will they try to go big and who will their impact player be? Kuldeep to continue

text: Length on middle, good dip, 83ks. Bowled from close to the crease, driven to deep cover off the back foot
Full around off, 88ks, pushed to long-off

Similar length, just down leg, 98ks. Ashwin tries to go across and clip it. Ump thinks it's missed everything. Thought Pant reviewed the wide but Virender Sharma sad it's a stumping appeal if I heard that right. No edge, Ashwin's feet were well in the crease, he was getting off-balance but managed to keep the tip-toe in the crease. The caught behind was checked
Length on leg, clipped to square leg. 97ks

Dances down and mows it over wide long-on! He carried the momentum and swung freely, got it 84 metres far. It was on a length around off, he stayed a bit leg side and had a rotational swipe. Ashwin big-dogs Kuldeep on this occasion to bring up the first six of the innings. This could turn into an interesting battle though
Full on leg, clipped to long-on
Ash Anna big-dogging Nortje now! Into the pitch, top-of-off, doesn't matter! Ashwin stands still and lumps it over the leg side. Pulled to perfection from deep in the crease
preText: Powell isn't padded up in the dugout for now. Nortje returns

text: He can't double down though, had a funky attempt did Ashwin. Went across and tried to paddle it over fine leg. The length ball hit him and deflected towards third
postText: Sravan: "Ashwin done his part with Bat !!" A bit early but he sure has started well

text: Fullish on leg, clipped to the leg side
Shorter, pulled harder! 142ks and was shorter than the first ball but it rose just under rib-height. Ashwin, in the crease, was unfazed
postText: Nayeem: "Is Ash batting on the Hyderabad pitch? "

text: Full at the stumps, goes legside of the ball and tries to drive hard through the line. Plinks it to long-on
Parag can't connect with the pull. Not dissimilar to the fourth ball in terms of length. But line was tighter, around fourth stump and the pace sharper at 146ks.
postText: Hari : "@Ekanth We can confirm that Ash anna has done enough now."

text: Chopped towards backward point
preText: Axar replaces Kuldeep, although I'd have liked Kuldeep for one more

text: Tries to pull the shortish flat dart on top of the pads. Goes square, misses completely. 110ks
postText: Ripon: "Can anyone tell me, why Rajasthan Royals have only three foreign players in their squad?" To bring in an overseas player as an impact sub if needed. They're keeping the option open

text: Length outside off, chopped off the underedge to point
Uppish drive, no check, lands safely and rolls to long-off. Length outside off, Parag tried hitting on top of the bounce, may have come in slower than he expected
postText: Amiya: "With Heti, Jurel and a possible Powell to come I still believe RR can get to a winning total of 160 here ."

text: Guided to the off side
Arm ball on a length, leg-stump line, worked to long-on.
postText: Axar's raced through that over in no time, given batters nothing to work with either

text: Length at the stumps, 84ks, clipped to deep-forward square leg
Flat-bat swipe is miscued, falls safely and goes to long-on
preText: Ashwin-Kuldeep contest resumes
postText: Anjan: ""Axar's raced through that over in no time, given batters nothing to work with either" and no comments to publish either!"

text: Wow that's a heck of a pull! The swivel from deep in the crease made it look even more powerful. 94 metres far it goes. Wasn't all that short, was going around fourth, Parag limboed back and lumped it over midwicket

shortText: Kuldeep Yadav to Parag, no run
text: Length around fifth, 87ks, punched towards cover
Darted down leg, 89ks, fullish and Parag tried shovel-sweeping it fine. Misses. Pant half-stops it
preText: Pant takes some time out of the game, has a word with Kuldeep

text: Kuldeep varying line and length now. Goes wide on a length, 82ks, Parag reaches out and slaps it to long-off

shortText: Kuldeep Yadav to Parag, no run
text: Gorgeous ball to beat bat. Went the other way. Length ball landed on off, 83ks, and went away. Parag went for the straight drive but got tentative last second. Well well, Pant's reviewd for a caught behind. It's really close but nothing detected on Ultra-Edge. Review ost.
postText: Neel: "Let them get what they can, RR Challenge will be keeping Warner and Rishabh quiet. Tough Challenge "

text: Back of length, middle and leg, 103ks, pulled to deep midwicket
preText: Around

text: Length on middle and off, Parag tries to flick through midwicket but the 99ks ball takes the leading edge and goes to point

wkt_text: R Ashwin c Stubbs b Patel 29 (24m 19b 0x4 3x6) SR: 152.63
text: Ashwin tries to clear deep midwicket but can't. 95ks length ball angling in, he saw it in his half and tried went for a stand-up slog sweep. Got a decent chunk but not enough to clear Stubbs, who took it and swivelled back, the step was within the cushion. Ashwin's given RR's innings some impetus though
Length on leg, clipped around the corner
postText: Anjan: "Think its time for Ash anna to retire from batting and let the sloggers come in now" This had come in a little while back.

text: Arm ball on a length, off stump, punched to long-on. 101ks
Fullish on leg, 101ks, worked off the back foot to deep midwicket. RR take the timeout
postText:
Trishul: "Once again RR choose not to bring their best hitter (Hetmyer) out early and then don't give him time to get in " It's a 50-50 call. I think Jurel's okay and maybe RR see him as a finisher who goes off right away. But yours isn't a bad call

Sujatha : "In other words Axar is Jaddu 2.0 "

text: Bat-pad or not? Pant and Khaleel have a long-ish chat, the bowler asked to go with one second to go but Pant isn't convinced. Good call in the end as there was an inside edge on the attempted off-drive before it hit pad. Replay comes in an over later, it was ball hitting pad first but impact would've been umpire's call
preText: Khaleel has a leg-side heavy field. All the deep fielders are out there. Just deep point on the offside. Around the wicket

text: Tucked-up proper. Into the pitch, angling in, Jurel was caught hurried, shaped to play the pull but was halfway into the shot when ball hit bat and went to the leg side
Helped over the fine-leg boundary. RR have played from-the-crease shots really well when the bowlers have gone short even slightly short, which was the case this time.
Low fully on fifth, attempted yorker at 140ks, Parag is up to it. Takes a small stride forward, lunges low and opens the blade to direct it through the backward-point gap

Slashed over extra cover. Picked the bones off the 126ks slower ball, too full though. Easy step hit for the batter, might've picked it off the hand, got it off the bottom-third of the bat. Ponting not too happy, probably with the fielder not getting close enough
Whisked away to the offside

postText:
Sudarshanan will be in for the chase. Let me see if I can get a couple comments in

Sampath's stat: Before this IPL, Riyan Parag was one of the two batters with 1000-plus T20 runs at No.4 with a strike rate of 150-plus and 40-plus average. Suryakumar Yadav being the other. However, Parag batted only twice at that No.4 position in his 54-match IPL career till 2023.

Sai: "RR were literally 58/3 in 10 overs, so this is a remarkable recovery ft. Ash, Parag and Hettie!!!"

Anshul: "Parag has finally started to live up to the hype around him"

Riyan Parag: [Last over] It's a result of a lot of practice behind the scenes. It's not the bowler but the ball he's bowling and I practised against a lot of those balls and could execute the shots tonight. I have my options ready both sides of the wicket, that's what I've been working on lately. I back myself, I know I have the power to dig out yorkers and hit sixes off short balls. Sometimes it works out, sometimes it doesn't. [Being 26 at run a ball] Sanga and Sanju bhaiyya came in and told me to do it deep, knew I'd go big at the end if I did. For someone coming in, it's not easy but not as much for someone set. It's been tough, I am a bit emotional right now. But it's been a lot of work. Backed myself, practiced a lot, seeing the fruits of it now.

9:24pm 58 off Parag's last 19 balls, says Simon Katich. It was ridiculous hitting. Whether the bowling was on point or not, it was sensational. You don't just hit both sides of the wicket with that good a connection repeatedly. There were things that happened before but who cares? I mean, if living in the moment was this fun, self-help people wouldn't have had to use it so much. Anyway, it's a great score. Parag started well, carried the innings together. Ashwin played a handy cameo. Capitals' new-ball bowlers were great. Axar tried holding them down. Kuldeep was good but was taken down. I'm just typing words on autopilot.

postText:
And so, the streak of home teams winning matches continues in IPL 2024. Nine in a row, and it is the longest such streak at any point in the IPL, says Sampath. That's all we have for you all tonight. Do join us for another cracker - RCB take on KKR in Bengaluru - tomorrow. Till then, take care, ciao!

11:41pm Time for the presentation

Sanju Samson, Royals captain: "The way we started, the first ten overs, we were like Rovman, be ready you might have to bat! The IPL is changing and we all have to be flexible. Earlier it was about 11 players, now it is about all 15 players. Me and Sanga had a lot of chat between 15th and 17th over before deciding the Impact Player. It's all about gauging in which zone they are. You have to look at that and take your decision. I saw Sandy was calm and Avesh was also looking good, so i went with that. Riyan Parag has been a big name in the last few years. Wherever I go, people ask me about him. There is something very special he can give to Indian cricket."

Riyan Parag, Player of the Match: "Emotions are settled, mum's here as well. She's seen the struggles, this feels special. I know what my ability is and I never let that change - irrespective of whether I perform or not. A lot to do with the domestic season, where I scored a lot of runs. Someone in the top four has to take it deep. First match, Sanju bhaiya did it, today I did it. I had to work very hard. I was on bed in the last three days. I could manage it today."

11:25pm High fives all around in the Royals camp. Ninth successive win by a home team this season. The bowling changes from Samson were spot on. Never let the batters settle and some excellent death bowling saw them eke out a 12-run win. This was after a Riyan Parag special enthralled one and all in Jaipur. That was clean-hitting of a different class, capitalising on his superb form. Axar was thrifty with the ball for Capitals, but barring Warner, none of the batters could get going.

Rishabh Pant, Capitals captain: "Definitely disappointed. The best thing to do from here to learn from it. The bowlers did well through the 15-16 overs. But the batters did well at the death, hopefully we do better in the next game. The platform that Warner-Marsh gave was very nice. We had to save wickets. We had to consolidate but at the end we had a lot to cover up. [On not bowling Nortje to Parag earlier] There is always one or the other option, but we wanted to finish Nortje in the death overs. Sometimes you are going to go for runs. Didn't go well for us today."

Avesh Khan, Royals bowler: "[On the death-over yorkers] My plan is always clear. One side was longer, so my plan was to bowl wide yorkers. I was giving myself five seconds and only thought about executing them. My focus is always on the execution and back my yorkers. Enjoying myself here because we have Sandeep, Boult, Burger, all of whom have different skills. Samson gives me freedom to execute and only steps in if he sees I am struggling. I try to improve myself everytime. In T20s I try to reinvent myself. I never think about selection and only practice what I want to bowl."

text: Outside edge? Kohli plays it with soft hands though! The Chinnaswamy roars as he gets going with four. He almost guides it well past short third, who slides but is nowhere close to the ball
preText:
Kohli takes strike against Mitchell Starc running from over the wicket. One slip in, and a short third

7:28pm Virat Kohli and Faf du Plessis walk out to the middle after the KKR fielders

Rev: "RCB missing a trick here? By not playing lomror while batting first?" I felt so too, yes

7:15pm Alzarri Joseph: "It's a pretty good wicket. It's important to stay consistent with the hard lengths. It's a good cricket wicket. You can go the distance if you are not consistent. I have been enjoying the pre-season games here. [Rinku and Russell] We know what we want to do but I won't be saying what exactly."

Venkatesh Iyer: "It's always good to come to Chinnaswamy. RCB are playing, we want to be the first team to take back two points from away games. The game was as good as highlights, some sensational hitting. The batters identified the pitch was a belter. It's the batters' job to identify what a good score on a given track is and bat accordingly. If you know it's a flat track, you have to go out there and carry on the moment. It is important to assess the conditions and it is a skillful format for batters as well. [On Maxwell] We would love it if he misses out one more game. They have got some amazing batters, we sit and assess the opposition players and where to bowl and where not to bowl."

Akhil: "Kind of homecoming for Starc as long long ago the only team he played for in IPL is RCB."

Mohit: ""Wait, what?? Why is Nitish rana not in the team? any word about him?"" No clue, Iyer was not asked much about the changes, and he seemed to be struggling to figure out the changes at toss

Adi: "@Mohit Rana appeared to have hurt his finger while attempting a catch last game. He didnt come back to the field after that"

7pm KKR win the toss and opt to bowl

"Had a chat with the curator and she was intellectual about how the wicket will behave," Iyer says. "The preparation has been good, we have to carry forward the momentum. Important to be in the present and get a good start. My role is to play the anchor role and play through and through. Good to have lethal bowling line-up as captain. They were phenomenal last game. Need to capitalise on the start. One change: Anukul Roy comes in."

"We would have liked to chase," du Plessis says. "Important early season to get over the line in close games. Helps the confidence as well. All the great cricketers have got the ability to adapt, and then see what your options are. Love the support here. Unchanged."

RCB: F du Plessis (capt), V Kohli, RM Patidar, GJ Maxwell, C Green, KD Karthik, Anuj Rawat (wk), AS Joseph, MJ Dagar, Mohammed Siraj, Yash Dayal

KKR: PD Salt (wk), VR Iyer, SS Iyer (capt), RK Singh, SP Narine, AD Russell, Ramandeep Singh, MA Starc, AS Roy, Harshit Rana, CV Varun

Sravan: "Early Prediction : RCB is the first team loose at home in this IPL. Rinku Singh is the PoM"

SandyKam: "Apt name for this RCB vs KKR is 'Clash of Titans'. Oh, and RR vs RCB can be called 'Battle Royale'."

6:55pm Angkrish Raghuvanshi gets his KKR cap.

Pitch report: It is the centre wicket - 61m square boundaries, says Ian Bishop. "Last game, we saw a number of wickets going pace-off a lot. It may be something that happen today too." Sunil Gavaskar looks at the good length spot on the surface and says that it is a bit loose there. "It will come apart a bit and will help the ball turn. Pace-off will work, but those are on a shorter length. Spinners should get more purchase."

6:50pm Mitchell Starc is in his first IPL since 2015. And so tonight's about Starc vs Kohli. Ahead of the contest, we had Steven Smith talk to us about Starc's mindset while bowling to Kohli. Watch what he had to say. Smith believes that Kohli knows what's coming his way and will be prepared for it.

Junaid Anwar: "Is this the El classico of the IPl,definitely worth the hype given the history of talents and the shenanigans from both sides." Are we all on for shifting that title to the RCB-KKR contest? Junaid, i don't think the suggestion will please MI-CSK fans.

Zayan: "If RCB bat first, bring in will jacks and sub him in the second innings and bring in Alzarri Joseoph. If RCB field, sub Joseph in the second innings and bring in Jacks. Only way for RCB to win against KKR's batting firepower." Can't do it if RCB name four overseas in the XI

6:40pm Andre Russell has announced himself in quite the style this season. His unbeaten 64 off just 25 balls - vintage stuff from Dre Russ - massively helped KKR to edge out Sunrisers in their opening contest. Not to mention his two wickets with the ball. What's very impressive is the work that went behind in him finding his mojo back, especially against spin. He has worked a lot on hitting spin with some help from his KKR team-mate Sunil Narine. Hemant Brar has more on how a small stride helped Russell take a giant leap.

Meanwhile, it is a landmark game for Narine as well. He becomes just the fourth man - third from West Indies - to play 500 T20s. Sampath Bandarupalli with some stats highlights of the mystery-spinner.

Mustafa Moudi : "As if KKR vs RCB battles were already not exciting that we have 2 additional reasons to watch this - Virat Kohli Vs Gautam Gambhir and Rinku Singh vs Yash Dayal. Super excited for this clash !!"

6:30pm Hello hello hello! A warm welcome to ESPNcricinfo's ball-by-ball coverage of perhaps one of the spicy contests in the IPL - Royal Challengers Bengaluru feat. Virat Kohli versus Kolkata Knight Riders with Gautam Gambhir as mentor. Home teams have won all nine contests in IPL 2024 so far, and both RCB and KKR are coming here off wins. RCB already have a loss to their name though, will KKR also follow suit? Do stick around for all the updates from Bengaluru as I, S Sudarshanan, will be your eyes and ears for the first innings, with Sreshth Shah for company.

postText:
9:04pm Kohli stays unbeaten after opening the batting - the 16th time it has happened in the IPL - to finish on 83, but have RCB have got enough? He started off in top gear but even as he continued to motor along, the others around him struggled. Only Green and Maxwell managed to find the boundaries regularly, and then of course, Karthik at the end. But has Kohli's innings put RCB in a good position or are KKR in it?

Cameron Green after handing Kohli the Orange Cap: "Pretty happy with the total. Bit more freedom in the last couple of innings. Good to get in early today. There's certain bowlers in their team I haven't faced before but [Kohli] has, so that helped. They used the change of pace, hitting it in the wicket. Hopefully dew does not come in."

KKR will fancy their chances with a long batting line-up. Will they break the home-team winning streak? Join Sreshth to find out

Sudhir: "Honest opinion (and I know I'm right) - RCB missed a key play by not sending in D Karthik earlier, ahead of Patidar and Rawat. They are 30-40 short of a part total, I think." Might not be that big a difference, but yes, I think DK should have come in earlier given how little of the innings was left

Pratheek Jain: "Batting through the entire innings and still scoring less than half the runs - not sure if VK would be happy with himself today."

postText: Bharat Arun, KKR bowling coach: "[KKR bowlers] did a magnificent job. They took pace off, which was much needed on the track. They did a great job of restricting RCB. Pace off was the most effective, and fast bowlers did that. If you bowl fast on this track, it becomes easy for fast bowlers. 180 was a par score, if we had a good start, which we have, we should be able to chase it. (Spinners) Anukul Roy did a magnificent job. He bowled straight at the stumps and that paid dividends. (Starc) Experienced bowler, knows what to do."
