text: game set and match! Six over square leg and KKR win by seven wickets! Half-tracker on off and Shreyas goes deep in his crease before playing a whippy shot off his waist. Does it have the distance to clear deep midwicket? Oh yes, it does!
postText:
Big win for KKR tonight and they are now 2-0 in this IPL 2024 season. It is also the first win for an away team, so plenty of other sides will be pleased with how this result panned out. See you tomorrow for more IPL cricket. Till then, on behalf of everyone at ESPNcricinfo, bye bye!

Jai Kedia: "I want to credit y'all over at Cricinfo for the excellent "MVP" tool you've built. It's very difficult to convert traditional cricket stats into match impact in T20s but you have done a sensational job. Harshit Rana today is an example. On the surface his stats don't impress but he played a crucial role in KKR's win."

11.05pm On his 500th appearance in T20s, it is Sunil Narine who is the Player of the Match for his overs and batting blitz. Here he is: "(500th T20 match) It is a nice milestone. Hopefully there are 500 more to come. Great to perform like this. Relief also to get it after a while. (Batting success today) Just self belief and support staff giving encouragement. Little bit of hard work and it is helping. (Bowling, how he pulled things back) Powerplay is always the hardest over to bowl so you have to forget that. When you come back later, you have to capitalise and pull things back. (KKR camp) It helps when you win. Self belief and confidence is coming from the support staff."

10.57pm We'll have the presentation shortly. And here's the winning captain Shreyas Iyer: "(rest between games) Absolutely. Coming here, we were in good shape between games. Coming here and hitting few balls made us feel comfortable. (Bowling innings) Russell showed slower ones are good here and the way he executed them were easy to see. From there on, rest of the bowlers picked up on that and made that their plans. Communication was brilliant. (Narine as opener) See Narine when he comes in, he has one job that is to clear the outfield and get maximum runs. Today was a phenomenal example. We were contemplating today whether to open with him or not, but this was great. (Nature of surface between innings) From one end, it was pretty good to bat on. From the other end, it was two-paced. It was bouncing extra. That was the communication we were having and passing it on to the batter coming next. (Break between now and next game in Visakhapatnam) We are spending a day here tomorrow and then going to Vizag. Have to see the nature of the pitch there. (Only one playoffs last four seasons - what expectations?) Not expecting much. Season has just started and we have just two wins so far. We need to embrace this and enjoy each others' successes."

Humaid Salman : "Only off-pace bowlers can succeed at Chinnaswamy. Fizz would have been a good buy but RCB never learn from mistakes. Bowlers like Starc also goes for runs here.I would definitely retain Vyshak before Siraj"

Venkatesh Iyer, who hit a fifty: "Let's see how my back is. Will know after a scan. The ball was coming on really well in the evening. Credit goes to Sunil Narine whose runs took the pressure off us. We just had to finish formalities. (Venkatesh's mindset) With a platform like that, you have to maximise. With a left-hand spinner bowling, I walked in in front of Angkrish, so I knew I had to take 'em on. Also my fiance was here today so it was a special day. (Facing Vyshak) Pace-off in totality was tough but if fast bowlers bowled pace-on, it was easy to take them to the cleaners. Happened with us in our bowling innings too."

Bruce Wayne: "Any one who played more than 6 deliveries in this match had a higher SR than Kohli - and that is the reason RCB lost - not ground or dimensions or pitch. If Rizwan or KL Rahul or Steve Smith or Williamson etc played this innings - that would be the only conversation point."

Hari: "Gambhir comes in - asks Narine to open, picked Salt and plays him over Gurbaz (who was benched by DC last season), doesn't care to sub Varun, injects aggression to bowling department (especially Harshit). Championship mindset!"

10.48pm Losing captain du Plessis: It was two-paced in the first innings but the pitch became better in the chase. It was not easy batting in the first innings, and you could see that with Virat also struggling a little. (Looking back) We could've tried one or two things, but the way Salt-Narine batted, they pretty much took the game away. They were excellent and broke the game in the first six overs. (Did you miss spin options?) We've tried Maxwell and fingerspinners are effective here but today there wasn't much spin. And with them having a left-right combination, spinners can find it tricky. We needed a wristspinner who could turn it both ways. (Vyshak) Very good. He hasn't had a lot of opportunity. We thought of getting legspinner Karn as an Impact Sub but brought him in for his cutters. We saw Dre Russ bowled 80% of his balls as cutters, so knew that would work. Good mix-ups from Vyshak, in terms of skillset.

10.45pm And an away team finally wins a game in IPL 2024. This game turned out to be a non-contest with KKR cruising to victory with 3.1 overs remaining. Every batter who turned up in purple and gold had a field day out today on a batting-friendly surface, and this par target was razed down easily.

KKR fans would once again love to see Narine get among the runs, who nearly got a fifty in his 500th T20 appearance. Salt, the two Iyers and an unbeaten Rinku ensured all their boxes were ticked as a batting side.

For RCB, only Vyshak's spell was promising. Otherwise, they all went for runs, even the spearheads Siraj and Alzarri Joseph. The only question that remains is whether they lost the match with the ball or with the bat when they scored only 182. We'll know more about what they think when we hear from Faf du Plessis.

shortText: Curran to de Kock, no run
text: Starts off with a good length ball just outside off, QDK looks to block and gets an inside edge onto his pads
preText:
Dhawan leads his team out and they get in a huddle as the umpires walk out. Rahul and QDK stride out. Sam Curran has the new ball in hand. Over the wicket to Quinton de Kock. One slip in place.

Praveen: "So if LSG were fielding first then KL would not have been in the eleven for the first innings ? Is that what this is about ? Thank you for explaining" Bingo!

7.25pm It's almost time for the match to start off. M Siddharth is in for his first appearance of the season and Mayank Yadav is making is debut for LSG. And as a reminder, KL Rahul will only play as a batter today, with Nicholas Pooran leading LSG. How will the LSG batters go against Rabada, Arshdeep, Brar and company?

Satish : "If overseas player can't substitute another overseas player, then what is reason behind the teams for keeping them in impact sub list" They can come on as sub fielders. Also, if a team has started with three overseas players, they can still come on as an Impact Player.

Pradeep: "Strange that LSG chose KL to be impact player, they could have chosen Padikkal!" It's been done keeping Rahul's workload in mind.

Gajesh: "What kind of workload management KL is under? He kept wickets earlier even though QDK was there and now he is playing as impact sub. Is there something I'm missing?" Maybe him keeping in the first game aggravated something. With fitness issues, you never know when something flares up.

Bini Sivan: "Impact player in Playing XI??" So effectively, Rahul will only bat, and go off for whoever comes in as the Impact Sub, and hence Pooran is the captain.

Jasdev: "Can teams swap an overseas player for another overseas player? This way, effectively utilizing 5 overseas players in a match!" Nope, the only way an overseas player comes on as an Impact Player is if the team starts with just three of them.

7pm It's toss time, and it looks like Nicholas Pooran is out there for LSG! We'll know soon enough what is up with KL Rahul. Yup, Pooran out there with Dhawan. LSG win the toss and bat. "KL Rahul is playing as an impact player," Pooran says. They are easing him in as he is returning from an injury. Says they want to put up a good total and defend it. Dhawan says Punjab Kings would have bowled first anyway because of the dew they saw last night. Wants his bowlers to get their lines more tight and also for batters to not lose back-to-back wickets. Punjab Kings are unchanged.

LSG XI: Quinton de Kock (wk), Devdutt Padikkal, KL Rahul, Marcus Stoinis, Nicholas Pooran (capt), Ayush Badoni, Krunal Pandya, Ravi Bishnoi, Mohsin Khan, Mayank Yadav, M Siddharth

Subs: Ashton Turner, Naveen-ul-Haq, Amit Mishra, Deepak Hooda, K Gowtham

Punjab Kings XI: Shikhar Dhawan (capt), Jonny Bairstow, Sam Curran, Liam Livingstone, Jitesh Sharma (wk), Shashank Singh, Harpreet Brar, Harshal Patel, Kagiso Rabada, Rahul Chahar, Arshdeep Singh

Subs: Prabhsimran Singh, Rilee Roussouw, Tanay Thagarajan, Vidwath Kaverappa, Harpreet Bhatia

6.55pm Here is Brian Lara with the pitch report from the ground: The pitch has a little more grass, it's a little thicker. Something in it for the fast bowlers. It's a red soil pitch. No visible cracks, a level surface so should be a good contest between bat and ball. Lara reckons the pitch will hold for the 40 overs, so he thinks the team winning the toss should chase.

6.50pm While you'll get all the ball-by-ball action right here, for a more detailed coverage with stat nuggets and more analysis as the game goes by, don't forget to keep checking in on Sid Monga's live report.

6.47pm It looks like Delhi based right-arm medium-fast bowler Mayank Yadav has received his first cap for Lucknow Super Giants.

Ami: "Where can I find information regarding which teams will play each other twice, and which teams will face each other only once?" You'll find it all on our fixtures page.

Junaid Anwar: "Both these team remain away from media glare,fanfare,hype and all that normally associated with an IPL team,that also has an advantage as it allows players to remain free of pressures thereby playing to their full potential." Well, KL Rahul's strike rate will not escape scrutiny from media or fans, I can tell you that!

6.40pm Have any questions about today's match for the Star Sports Hindi commentators? Do you want to ask Sanjay Manjrekar, Mohammad Kaif or Harbhajan Singh anything cricket? Go to the ESPNcricinfo mobile site, click on the AskStar button and fire away your questions and you may just have your doubts answered on TV!

Also, don't forget that you can follow our commentary in Hindi as well!

Mustafa Moudi : "When before LSG is hosting their first match today, the home side winning streak got broken. So no assurance for LSG to win this. Feeling little sad for them !!" Yup, that streak got broken so that KKR could maintain their streak at the Chinnaswamy last night!

Bong Boy Ashish: "Lucknow is definately going to win their first match of the season. Ravi Bishnoi leads the IPL wicket-taking charts at the Ekana stadium. He is going to be the key player today." He had a quiet first game of the season, but back at his home ground, he will be hoping to make more of an impact.

Afeef: "I wish Rossouw could play but there's no place in the playing XI. That being said, I want Livingstone to come good in this tournament. He's been having a rough time for the past few months in terms of consistency."

6.30pm With ten games already done, IPL 2024 is well and truly underway. Today, for Match No. 11, we have Lucknow Super Giants, led by KL Rahul, up against his former team, Punjab Kings. LSG need to get off the mark, and will hope that home advantage will help them do just that. Kings, meanwhile, started the season with a win, but then lost in Bengaluru, so they will want to get momentum back on their side. The last time the two teams met was a high-scoring affair, but if the pitches at the Ekana stadium last season are anything to go by, today should be a much trickier affair for the batters. Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of today's game. I'm Abhimanyu and, along with Ekanth, we'll be bringing you all the action from Lucknow.

If you want to do some homework on the match, look no further than Vishal Dikshit's match preview. Meanwhile, in some team news, LSG have signed Matt Henry as a replacement for David Willey, although the New Zealand quick is not going to be available for today's game.

Meanwhile in Indian football, the league is witnessing it's closest ever season with 11/12 teams left with something to play for. Four teams are still battling to win the league shield, while seven teams are in the race for the remaining two playoff spots. The scenarios are ever so complicated, but here's our handy guide.

And that will be our first time out of the day.

postText:
9.20pm Right then. A half-century from Quinton de Kock and some rapid 40s from today's captain Nicholas Pooran and Krunal Pandya have helped LSG set Punjab Kings a target of 200. Sam Curran was excellent with the ball, taking three wickets, while Arshdeep took two. Rabada and Chahar chipped in as well, while Brar was economical despite not getting on the wickets column. Join Ekanth soon to see how the chase will pan out.

Krunal Pandya: I've always prepared that way that I'll be flexible as a batter. I just want to go out and contribute to the team, regardless of what position I bat. I like to prepare well. I take it like an exam where if you study well, your paper will go good. I treat cricket the same way. [On the total] Pretty happy. One side is bigger, one side is shorter. If we bowl smartly we can defend this. The surface has been changed and it's much better than last year."

text: Length outside off, chopped to backward point
preText:
M Siddharth to bowl. Here's a bit about him from Deivarayan Muthu icymi: Siddharth is a left-arm fingerspinner, who was born in Jakarta (Indonesia) where his father Manimaran played a bit of club cricket. The family moved to Chennai to help Siddarth become a professional cricketer. Siddharth is a bit of a super-specialist in the TNPL: he bowls with the new ball and swings it. In the most recent TNPL, he spun Shahrukh Khan's Lyca Kovai Kings to the title. In IPL 2023, he was a net bowler for Chennai Super Kings and in the past, he has also had a stint with India as a net bowler. Siddharth has spent much of his career in the shadows of R Sai Kishore, TN's premier spinner and captain. This is his chance to emerge from the shadows of Sai.

9:34pm Hello and welcome back. Dew could be an issue in the chase but will Kings not have Livingstone? This game could get dicey. Dhawan said after the last game he wanted to cash in better in the powerplay. Bairstow will need some runs too.

preText: Okay, wait's done. Here's Mayank Yadav. From Deiva earlier: Mayank is a fast bowler from Delhi, who hit 150kph in the recent Syed Mushtaq Ali Trophy. Gautam Gambhir had snapped him up when he was with LSG, but Mayank suffered an injury in IPL 2023, with HP quick Arpit Guleria replacing him in the side. After Mayank had recovered from that injury, he was fast-tracked into the North Zone side for the 50-overs Deodhar Trophy where he knocked out Rahul Tripathi's middle stump with a rapid delivery. He was recently in action in the DY Patil tournament in Mumbai too.

text: Dhawan uses the pace again. Gets it on top of the bounce and guides it wide of short third. Not that bad a ball, channel line, decent length but the batter
postText: Phani: "Early views, Mayank seems more organised than what Umran Malik has been.Would like to see gim bowl yorkers, slower ones, wide outside offa etc stuff though.Encouraging early signs though."

shortText: Ravi Bishnoi to Prabhsimran Singh, 1 run
text: Driven to deep cover
Stays leg side and whacks a sweep to deep midwicket

shortText: Ravi Bishnoi to Prabhsimran Singh, FOUR
text: Cannoned down the ground. 103ks, length on fifth, Prabhsimran had a free swing. Step-hit too, which is what the batters want in T20s

shortText: Ravi Bishnoi to Prabhsimran Singh, 1 run
text: Clips the length ball to midwicket
Length on off, pushed to coer with the fully open bat face

shortText: Ravi Bishnoi to Prabhsimran Singh, SIX
text: Don't think he middled the slog sweep but it cleared long-on anyway. 104ks but overpitched. Just outside off, Prabhsimran got on one knee and got it off the bottom-quarter of the bat but it sailed 78 metres far.
postText: The new batter manages to pull things back after a couple of quiet overs.

text: Goes across and real far back, helps the hard-length ball to deep fine leg

Mohsin is tangled up on the deep-backward-point boundary falls over the toblerone! 149ks, just outside off, Prabhsimran backed away and was crouching (prolly in reflex) but swung through anyway. The top edge off the cut went high, fielder ran to the right but couldn't keep it in

wkt_text: Prabhsimran Singh c Naveen-ul-Haq b Yadav 19 (7b 1x4 2x6) SR: 271.42
text: Ballooned pull to mid-on, 147ks. Short and over midde, rose around rib-height, Prabhsimran cleared the front leg and tried forcing it but clothed it straight to Naveen. Pace doing pace things. Good cameo from the batter though
Sniff-the-leather stuff. 145ks, shortish and goes right past him. Let go
postText: Ajey: "Given the PBKS batting line up, I think Prabhsimran did his job alright. "

text: Let go. Early 140ks, shortish over off, Jitesh shapes ever so slightly for the ramp but has no intention of playing it
Mayank knows the instruction and follows it to the T again. 143ks shortish and over off, guided to deep third.
postText: Brian Lara talks about the prospect of Mayank and Shamar bowling in tandem. Salivating, innit?

text: Makes room and thumps it down the ground. It's fullish, Jitesh turned it into a half-volley and clobbered it straight of long-on. Kings have been proactive

shortText: Mohsin Khan to Sharma, no run
text: Wide yorker, around sixth stump, 140ks, Jitesh tries walking into a cover drive. Beaten
Wide on a length, Jitesh goes across and guides it to deep third
preText: 56, 61 and 68 metre boundary from fine leg to midwicket on the legside for Jitesh. That's why LSG are keeping it wide of off
postText: SKP: "Is Livingstone injured ? Will he come to bat ? Any news ?" None yet. Matthew Hayden says he'd have to even if he has to stay on one leg.

text: Wide and fullish, angle takes it past the bat swing. Wide given. 139ks. Jitesh tried slapping it over cover

shortText: Mohsin Khan to Dhawan, no run
text: First review of the match is for a wide that's been given. Dhawan goes across, back leg is on fourth stump and he tries to heave the back-of-length ball over fine leg. He's inside the line of the ball, it's a tad down leg but not enough to be an extra
Slow and into the pitch, shortish, pulled to deep-backward square

shortText: Mohsin Khan to Sharma, no run
text: Slower one goes under bat. Length on fifth, 115ks, Jitesh swipes across the line before collapsing
postText: Rozal: "Super over today . U heard it here first."

text: Dhawan goes across and a low full toss is further from him, guided to deep point
preText: Karthik: "Mayank Yadav might be the find of reason for India. Tremendous pace, may be the fastest in the international cricket now, good short ball, if he has control over line n length. We will see him play for India in a year" How will he close his quota. He's the main reason for the asking rate rising to 12.8 for the last five

text: Stays in the crease while shuffling across, gets followed by a very full ball at 153ks. Must've been an inside edge as he tried whipping it, deflects away off the pad
Another cut beaten, 148ks. Shortish just outside off, Jitesh tries cutting behind square

wkt_text: JM Sharma c Naveen-ul-Haq b Yadav 6 (9b 1x4 0x6) SR: 66.66
text: 141ks, Another pull us ballooned, Naveen takes another catch. Short into the pitch, rises around rib-height, Jitesh looked to go over midwicket but like a few other team-mates, got hurried. Naveen went from mid-on towards short midwicket to catch the top edged ball
postText: Ahmed: "Mayank Yadav at bouncy Perth pitch for the first test against Australia in November anyone? "

text: Ooh, misses a slot ball! 151ks though, three-quarter length but that's slot in T20ks, especially for guys like Liam. He's across on off and tries slugging over midwicket
preText: Premal: "Is Livingstone gonna be able to bat today? Think he hurt himself while fielding. " He has come out. Matt Roller was talking a few days about how he used to clobber raw pace but isn't doing it as well anymore. How will he go tonight? Livingstone that is. I'm sure Roller would smack high pace

text: Goes back to a 148ks length ball on off, cloths a slog. Gets it to deep midwicket.
postText:
Raj: "Don't you guys think Mayank Yadav might fall down breaking his back after first spell at tests?? Shoaib Akhtar, Brett Lee, Shaun Tait, none of them were exemplary in tests. Might've had a moment here and there." Might but why jump the gun, better off enjoying it for now

End of Mayank's spell, that was some adrenaline rush

text: Deep point runs to the left but can't get there. Bishnoi it is, does well to get body behind the ball and get it on the bounce. Was a shortish ball that was slashed

wkt_text: S Dhawan c †de Kock b Mohsin Khan 70 (50b 7x4 3x6) SR: 140.00
text: Bumper is tickled to the keeper. Dhawan can't close out the chase. This landed around fourth, Dhawan swung his head outside off and tried to hook it almost, feathered it to QDK, who wasn't fazed by the dipping ball and took a good catch to the left. Dhawan ends with a SR of 140 but I'd say it's hard to blame him for not going harder during the Mayank's whirlwind spell
preText: Livingstone in pain but will continue

wkt_text: SM Curran c Pooran b Mohsin Khan 0 (1b 0x4 0x6) SR: 0.00
text: Pull skied, catch taken at mid-on, Mohsin has two in two. Another slower bumper, just under shoulder-height just outside off, Curran tried leathering the pull but got a top edge. No sighters and no second chances - death overs doing its thing

shortText: Mohsin Khan to Shashank Singh, 1 run
text: Hat-trick ball is into the pitch, just outside off, tapped to the offside with a fully open face
postText: Arpit : "Pbks doing KXIP! "

text: Bumper on fifth, pulled to deep midwicket. Limited timing, not sure how freely Livingstone's feet are moving

shortText: Mohsin Khan to Shashank Singh, 1 run
text: Run-out chance missed, no direct hit from point. But Livingstone hobbling is the bigger story. He'd given up too but Stoinis can't get it. Was a length ball outside off that was pushed gently
postText: Bharat: "Mohsin reaping the rewards for tight Mayank spell."

text: Bishnoi runs swiftly to the right but can't stop it. Charged from deep midwicket but the ball kept going away and landed a foot or two behind as he slid into the grass. Was a slow short ball that was pulled
preText: Naveen comes in with 56 needed off 18

text: Pacy bouncer around off, doesn't get the pull this time. Goes off the body to the offside
Slow on a slot length but it's on fifth stump. Livingstone has to reach out with upper body only, which is not enough, for the slog over midwicket. Inside edges it to the leg side
preText: Mohsin hobbling, hand on the right hamstring. He's in pain and lies down beyond the boundary

shortText: Naveen-ul-Haq to Shashank Singh, 1 leg bye
text: Fullish and slow, attempted slog plinked again. Leg-side single again

Slower one goes under the bat swing. Smart from LSG to keep it outside Livingstone's arc, something Afghanistan didn't do against Maxwell in the WC. Length ball on sixth, Livingstone tried to go over midwicket
Clips the length ball to the legside
postText: Shaik: "Looks like Ekanth is so awestruck by Pace of Mayank that he is typing 'pace' for 'pain' of Mohsin. Jk!!" Lol sorry, and thanks. Fixed

text: Wide on a length, just inside the tramline. Let go, wide rightly not called. 102ks
preText: avikrams: "last 2 overs simple mantra to LSG bowlers: Keep it simple, straight with good line and length and match is in your bag now" It'll be Krunal for the 19th. Siddharth's not an option, Bishnoi was the other guy

text: Goes across and gets followed by a length ball. Lap-swept onto the body and then to short fine leg
Wide yorker, squeezed to deep backward point
Bumper outside off, beats Livingstone's cut but QDK's reflexes are tested. He manages to take it and then has a word with the bowler
Wide on a length, Liam goes across and slaps it down the ground. Mid-off was very straight and in but was cleared, long-off was too wide
Wide yorker, slapped to deep cover. 41 needed off 6, so the game's done
preText: Long-off is now straighter
postText: Kevin: "An opening partnership of 102 off 70 balls when you chasing 200 is where PBKS lost it. They didn't anticipate a debutant bowling 150 in middle overs "

text: Length on middle and off, back is bent across in advance. He swings across the line and gets six over square leg
Another bumper but it's slower and bounces over head. Beats the pull
preText: Spidercam hit, so it's a dead ball as the ballgirl outside the boundary suggests. Lol the one time Livingstone does middle it... Was a short ball at the body that was pulled to midwicket. Shot off the spidercam is great, shows scratchy rainbowy distorted lines

text: Not fun being an Afghanistan bowler against a batter who can't walk. He goes wide and full, it's not in his reach as such, but he's able to reach out and flay it over extra
Very wide but flat-batted down the ground. Released from very wide of the crease, shortish too, not sure how Livingstone middled that. Magical almost
Back of length over fifth, Livingstone has a swipe across. Misses
Clothed, lands safely and goes to Bishnoi at deep-mid. Livingstone yelps in pain, hobbles the run, lunges and collects a breath. Was a wide length ball that was heaved across
Makes room and slaps the slow length ball on fourth, to deep point
postText:
It's a new pacer, a new performer, a new story. What's better than that, eh? Mayank's spell was an experience in itself, how cool was it to be a part of it?! Hope this is one of many coming in the league. Thanks for joining in tonight. Take care.

Mayank Yadav, POTM I've always heard from others there's nervousness in debuts but that goes away after the first ball. Plan was to not be under too much pressure and to bowl at the stumps and use the pace as much as possible. There was the thought to mix up the pace initially but the wicket helped and the skipper told me to bowl gas. The debut wicket was the favourite. Coming off the injury last season was tough, I'd set my goal to debut at a young age but injuries were a setback.

Nicholas Pooran, LSG captain: Wonderful start in front a home crowd. (On the batting order) We had a start at the chat of the tournament. Use the left-right combo as needed. It's a big ground, one side big. It's tough as you have to go big while going at tens. Shikhar and YJB played well, but they didn't take the game away from us. Mayank's was the story of the night. It was an inspiring performance. Every person in the team is happy he got a chance and performed tonight. Was wonderful watching him from mid-off. It's a young bowling attack. The IPL has given local players opportunities to grow. We have youngsters, experienced players and coaching staff as well. Expect guys to get better. Groundsmen, everyone who contributed was amazing.

Jasdev: "Glad any LSG batsman didn't score big. Now the MoM can deservedly go to Mayank Yadav !!"

Farid: "So Delhi and Mumbai are the only winless teams after two rounds of matches."

Morne Morkel, LSG bowling coach: Happy with the win. Bowlers stuck to it. In the first timeout told the bowlers to stay in the game. Then young Mayank bowled serious heat and got the wickets. It was tough last year as he got injured after the first warm-up game. We're managing him better. He ran in and that was the pleasing thing. We asked the guys to do the basics well on a good wicket. Told him to stick to his lengths and use bouncers. Proud he ran in and bowled gas despite the humidity. How the wicket would play was an unknown, we had to sum up conditions and use them. We had five-six days after the first game, that could've worked against us too. It's harder sitting in the dugout than on comms. (laughs)

Shikhar Dhawan They played well, Livi got injured that impacted us. He'd have come in at 4. Mayank bowled really well. His pace outsmarted us. It was nice facing him, surprised me with that pace. Knew as an experienced player I'd use it. But he figured it out and bowled yorkers to keep me down to a dot and a single. I was mindful and told my partners to use the short side. He bowled at Prabh's body and got him out. Told Jitesh to leave Mayank and take on the other bowlers but they bowled well too and then used the pressure against us. We're gonna analyse the game. We gotta take catches, that takes the momentum away and gets the energy down. To come up with better plans and more importantly implement them is what we need to do. We're close but need to do 10% more.

11:20pm It's another home-team win on Mayank Yadav day. It was an innings of two halves. Bairstow and Dhawan owned the first and Mayank the next. It was singlehanded and shows that the beauty of pace extends beyond optics if accurate. Just for reference, Kings needed 102 off 60 with ten wickets in hand. By the time Mayank was done, they needed 60 off 24 with seven wickets in hand. It was oh so effective, he's all smiles while hugging his opponents. Doubt he'll be tired of the compliments. His fellow debutant, Siddharth, started well bowling like Akeal Hosein in the first over of the innings but was found out. The duo stayed deep in the crease, literally, and found the boundaries often. They nailed the chase for a while but Mayank's entry hurried batters, created dots. It led to Bairstow falling. The new guys tried working against it, unlike Dhawan and also fell. Mohsin was excellent on the other end too. It slowed Shikhar before dismissing him. Krunal bowled tight enough for the game to not drift. Naveen got some tap in the end but had more than enough to defend.

shortText: Azmatullah Omarzai to Agarwal, no run
text: full ball, a hint of shape away after pitching on off stump, Mayank punches confidently off the front foot but can only find mid-off
preText:
Unsurprisingly, no changes to the SRH opening combination. Travis Head is back at Motera for the first time since the greatest cricketing night of his life. He'll partner Mayank Agarwal. No change to the GT plan for now either. Azmatullah Omarzai will get first use of the new ball. Mayank will take strike.

Aashique : "I think GT have one of the best squad but they are not being able to figure out best 12." --- One feature of Nehra's GT has been their brave calls coming off, like Vijay Shankar in the middle order last season. They certainly haven't yet put a finger no their balance without Hardik Pandya, though.

I've got plenty of you asking me about Natarajan's fitness status. He missed the last game with an unspecified niggle, so we're assuming him missing out today is only a continuation of that.

Abhishek Shah: "GT make changes in bowling and not batting?? Baffling.. " --- That's one way to describe it. Sai Kishore certainly will consider himself unlucky to miss out.

Pat Cummins has won the toss, and SRH will bat first. He says it's a good wicket and it's pretty hot, so they want to put some runs on the board. Got some wonderful memories at this stadium, he says. He says the last game was a measure of how good they are. No changes for SRH.

Gill says they would've bowled first, with the thinking being that they would like to know what the target is in front of them. Noor Ahmad and Darshan Nalkande come into the Gujarat side today, Spencer Johnson and Sai Kishore make way

Playing XIs:

Sunrisers Hyderabad: 1. Travis Head 2. Mayank Agarwal 3. Abhishek Sharma 4. Aiden Markram 5. Heinrich Klaasen (wk) 6. Abdul Samad 7. Shahbaz Ahmed 8. Pat Cummins (capt) 9. Bhuvneshwar Kumar 10. Mayank Markande 11. Jaydev Unadkat

Impact Player options: Nitish Kumar Reddy, Washington Sundar, Umran Malik, Upendra Yadav, Glenn Phillips

Gujarat Titans: 1. Shubman Gill (capt) 2. Wriddhiman Saha (wk) 3. Vijay Shankar 4. David Miller 5. Azmatullah Omarzai 6. Rahul Tewatia 7. Rashid Khan 8. Darshan Nalkande 9. Noor Ahmad 10. Umesh Yadav 11. Mohit Sharma

Impact Player options: Sai Sudharsan, Sai Kishore, BR Sharath, Abhinav Manohar, Manav Suthar

Suman: "How can Shahrukh not play after all the investment and effort to bring him in? " --- A certain Ben Stokes was the most expensive player for last year's champions and played only a couple of games, so the auction value certainly isn't the be all and end all.

Pitch Report: 66m and 63m square boundaries. 73m straight boundaries, pockets at extra cover and midwicket a bit longer. It's an absolute road, says Kevin Pietersen, who thinks it looks like a tremendous wicket. He says there's a breeze which will help the players as temperatures are expected to reach 38-40 degrees celsius. Sunrisers will come here, look at that wicket, and say maybe they can make 270 again, chuckles Pietersen, as he tells Ravi Shastri they are going to be calling sixes and fours galore. It's a black soil wicket, adds Shastri, so that is similar to the November 19, 2023. That wasn't as high-scoring, so a nice bit of intrigue surrounds that. .

Ashish: "Is robin minz available for selection?" BR Sharath has replaced him. I didn't know but Aaditya was onto it in a flash. Here he is for more insights.

2:40pm As for Sunrisers, they're 1-1 but were four runs away from making it 2-0. Their pacers need some oomph. Cummins was excellent during MI's 278-run chase but still isn't a T20 whiz. Very different from Tests. His inclusion comes at a cost of other players - like Glenn Phillips and Marco Jansen - missing out. Wanindu Hasaranga's still not in India but he's not too far from making it either. But Cummins is cricketing chess grandmaster and alpha at the same time. He, along with Travis Head, has what it takes to silence the crowd at the Narendra Modi Stadium. Their batting's crazy strong with six-machine Klaasen and in-form Abhishek Sharma.

Aditya: "Hey there Ekanth! I'm going to oppose you here. Though high scoring games do give you entertainment, it is crucial to have games where bowlers dominate once in a while. Too many high scoring games get really boring after a while and hey, bowlers need some of the limelight too come on!" I do agree. Bowlers should dominate once in a while. The point is so should batters. That's what creates balance. My point is for being wholehearted with compliments rather than noting the exception which arguably undermines. Be it with batting or bowling.

CricDude: "GT have an issue with both their middle order. And Umesh failing is an added concern. They have to bring Abhinav at any cost. Either Nalkande or Sushant has to be tried for Umesh, or go for 2 overseas pacers. Gill, Saha, Sai, Abhinav, Miller, Tewatia, Rashid, Kishore, Mohit, Little, Spencer - this would be my XI. Add an extra batter or bowler as the game goes - Shahrukh, Vijay Shankar, Nalkande, Sushant are my impact players."

Match Preview by Sreshth Shah Vulnerable Titans face Sunrisers acid test. Sreshth will also be on the live blog for snappy summaries and analysis during the game.

2:30pm Here's a hot-take to start double-header Sunday - batters bashing it everywhere in T20s is a good thing. Like when Sunrisers Hyderabad got 277 on a flatty, along with basking in power-hitting excellence there was an undertone of 'what about the bowlers'... there was contrarianism in the concern. But you know what, bowlers will win tournaments, they will play a key part especially as the tournament goes on. So even if they don't get the social cache, they'd get many a chance to line up wins for their teams. That's actually what Gujarat Titans would want in the absence of Mohammed Shami. Rashid Khan has blown hot and cold, so they'll want him to turn up. Lest we forget, he's coming back from a surgery and has played just five T20 games since returning, including two IPL games. It's a day game, whoever bowls first will have their task cut out.

text: similar line and length again, some away shape again, Mayank gives himself a touch of room and drives wide of mid-off, where Gill moves to his left and makes a diving stop to keep it down to one
short and wide, a nice gift to welcome Head back to Ahmedabad! Rocks back and punches it through the gap between cover point and extra cover
Omarzai overcorrects, this is a leg-stump half volley, Head clips it away in the air past square leg and he's off like a train again
Omarzai goes around the wicket and angles it too far down leg, Head doesn't get a proper connection on the flick this time, but gets it wide enough of fine leg for them to go through for a couple

shortText: Azmatullah Omarzai to Head, no run
text: length ball on off stump, Head stays leg side of it and drives to mid-off
back of a length ball, on middle and leg, sticks in the wicket a little as Mayank is too early into the flick and lobs it over Nalkande at fielder
preText: Typically Travis, that start. Over to Umesh now.

text: length ball on leg stump, flicked to midwicket, Mayank will be annoyed to have missed out on that one

This time he doesn't miss out, another ball drifting into the pads from Umesh, Mayank is nicely balanced in flicking it past midwicket, Nalkande gives it a good chase and makes a diving stop to save a run
Take that, says Head! Length ball on off stump, no movement, Head gets the front foot out of the way and bludgeons it through the line and past Umesh for his third boundary
length ball pitching on off and angling across Head, he looks to smash it through the line and down the ground again, hits the bottom of the bat and goes through on the bounce to mid-off
goes shorter this time, Head stays legside and looks to unfurl the ramp but misses it
postText: Minimal movement, consistent bounce, so far this seems like a track where the batters can put their head down and swing through the line.

text: length ball drifting into the pads, Mayank misses the flick and it dribbles through to short fine off the thigh pad and they run through for a leg bye to put Head back on strike
back of a length angling across from off stump, Head looks to flay it square on the offside but gets an inside edge through to short fine

shortText: Azmatullah Omarzai to Agarwal, no run
text: length ball on middle and off stump, Mayank goes back and across and pushes it to midwicket

shortText: Azmatullah Omarzai to Agarwal, no run

Poor misfield from Mohit at mid-off. Length ball just outside off, Mayank pushes it wide of mid-off, but Mohit overruns to his left and lets it go through his right hand to give Mayank a release after some pressure might have been building

shortText: Azmatullah Omarzai to Agarwal, 1 leg bye
text: back of a length on middle stump, Mayank looks to flick, misses it and it lobs through to backward point off the front pad
Shot! Innocuous delivery, right in the slot for Mayank to hit through the line, he needs no second invitation as he clears the left foot and lofts this over mid-on
length ball on off stump, seemed to come back in off the seam a touch, Mayank adjusts nicely in dabbing it towards short third, but there's no run there
length ball on off stump, Mayank looks to pull, probably wasn't short enough to play that shot so it hits the pad and dribbles through to short third and they sprint across for a leg bye
slower ball, just back of a length, on middle and off stump, Head hacks it down to long-on

short ball outside off stump, Mayank gives himself room and misses the upper cut, it's called a wide much to Umesh's surprise. He's persuaded Gill to go for the review as well, and it's just as well he did that. It's a fair delivery
short ball on middle and leg, Mayank tucks it behind square but doesn't get enough timing on it, so it's just dribbled through to the left of short fine as they get a single

shortText: Azmatullah Omarzai to Agarwal, no run
text: fuller length ball on leg stump, Mayank misses the flick and gets hit on the front pad. Stifled appeal from Omarzai which is denied
preText: Omarzai will continue

wkt_text: MA Agarwal c Nalkande b Azmatullah Omarzai 16 (29m 17b 2x4 0x6) SR: 94.11
text: The pressure has told on Mayank! Shorter length ball, 137ks, tucking up Mayank, who goes for the swivel pull but the line had tucked him up so he couldn't get a free swing going, Nalkande pockets a simple catch at deep square leg
preText: Mayank's striking at 100 in the powerplay here, and taking up a lot of strike too, surely something has to give soon?

shortText: Azmatullah Omarzai to Abhishek Sharma, no run

preText: Abhishek Sharma now, what a game he had in Hyderabad the other night

shortText: Rashid Khan to Abhishek Sharma, SIX

preText: Rashid goes around the wicket now
postText:
Mustafa Moudi: "With Head, Markram Klaasen and Cummins, I think this is the best Overseas 4 among all the 10 current sides. All other sides are either not sure about their perfect combination or have a weak link in their settled 4 overseas players !!" --- Not sure I agree, CSK with Ravindra, Mitchell, Pathirana and Mustafizur do look a settled unit

Time for a bit of a break, with the day's first strategic timeout

text: Bursts right through his fingers! This one's tossed up around off stump, Head belted it straight back to Noor's right, but he gets only fingertips on it, and it then goes through to long-off

preText: A super period of play for GT after the powerplay. Noor has been excellent and Mohit has started off well. Now, though, it's time for arguably the best T20 batter on the planet. Heinrich Klaasen has arrived.

Secondly, even if they were allowed to do it, why would they sub their captain off? Thirdly, why would they starve themselves off the option of Cummins's off cutter banging into this slow track?

text: takes pace off, pitches on a good length well outside off stump, Samad walks across and looks to mow it across the line, but doesn't time it at all. Eventually, that helps him out as they run through for a couple of runs by the time deep midwicket came in to pick that one up

text: slower short ball again, Cummins again doesn't time the pull shot well enough, and can only find square leg. They keep running off that last ball, and Samad ends up being run out
postText:
5:08pm: SRH were 58/1 at the end of the powerplay, with Travis Head going great guns. But he fell trying to attack Noor, then Mohit picked up Abhishek just when he looked set to go big, then Rashid removed the dangerous Klaasen. The Titans were very effective taking the pace off the ball towards the back end of that innings. Have SRH learned from that? Their captain specialises in that kind of bowling in white ball cricket, to be fair, so he'll certainly be encouraged by what he's seen from the wicket. They've got the extra spin option into their side, in the form of Washington, can he make use of the spin available on this track? 162 is not a huge total, but certainly is defendable.

Abdul Samad: This is a decent score. It's a day game, there's some help for the spinners as well, so this is a decent score. I was striking the ball well, so I thought I should've got more strike in the last over. Looking at our start, we thought we could get around 180, but around 160 is a decent score as well.

text: Guided past backward point, stopped at deep third. Was a length ball in the channel
preText: 5:20pm That's an early start into the second dig. Kudos to the Titans' over rate. Half the ground covered in shade. Saha and Gill to open. Bhuvi, with a slip, to start. He's wicketless so far in the comp, can he change that today?

postText:
That's the 11th win for the home team in 12 games. Will that trend continue in Delhi or can super-strong CSK change that? Find out Live here. Thanks for tuning in to this match. I'm Ekanth, signing off on behalf of my co-commentator Aaditya Narayan, and our scorers, Thilak Rama and M Venkat Raghav.

Mohit Sharma, POTM: Thanks for telling me I'm aging. I practice what I do generally. What's important is knowing when to use them and being ahead of the batter. Everyone has them on slow wickets but knowing how to use it against whom is key. (Importance of tweaking the field when bowling slow) If you and the batter knows what you'll deliver, then you need to play with one fielder's position to deceive the batter. If he's ready for a slower bouncer but I go slow and wide, he won't be ready. (Bowling slow balls in night games) We practice with a wet ball to contend with dew. But it's an uncontrollable, mindset matters more there. (On his role) As long as I do well I enjoy. When you don't it hurts a bit but you have to go back and review things after the game. But it's better if the mistakes are due to failing in execution rather than not following the plan. Spinners were excellent after SRH started well. It helped us chase a smaller target.

Shubman Gill, GT captain: Winning two matches at home is great, two more to go and then we go on the road. Hope to bring the momentum back. Our bowlers, esp Noor, Rashid bhai is world-class. But Noor and Darshan bowled excellently. Mohit is such an experienced bowler, esp on wickets like this. Not easy to bowl three or four overs back to back. He mixes up yorkers, slower ones so well. In this heat, it's easier to bat early in day games. So we wanted to make them hit to the bigger boundary off slower balls. Ball hit the bottom of my bat on my wicket ball. In T20s if you see the ball in your slot you have to go for it. We thought 160-170 would be a good score. Credit to the bowlers to restrict them. Everyone knows their roles in terms of batting or bowling. Sai has played well, Wriddhi bhai does what he does well. Miller's gotten in form too. He has just a cramp I think.

Shadow-Shell: "Wow! Highest impact is Mohit with 58.38. Shows how no one dominated the game more than other"

Ananthanarayana: "Men in blue beat pat Cummins led side in Ahmedabad ! "

Sai Sudharsan: Happy with my contribution as it helped the team to win. On this wicket it was tough to play pacers bowling slower ones. So we thought of targeting spinners and maximising there. Great contribution from Mohit and Rashid, they saved 10-15 runs which was key. To be playing in front of home crowd is a plus point which is playing in our favour. [Being out in the 40s] Everyone wants to score more every game, I'm just thinking of contributing and helping the team win. Milestones will come.

Pat Cummins, SRH captain: Good match but we got 10-15 less. They bowled well. Losing a couple of wickets meant we couldn't get a batter not making fifty plus. It happens, it was probably the difference. [Him coming in late to bowl] Today it was a case because we thought the wicket would slow up a little bit and offcutters would become more effective, which they were. [Would he have changed the toss decision] No, I thought the wicket played the same in both innings. It's T20 cricket, batters have had fantastic couple of games. The boys looked good but were stifled by the wickets.

6:54pm It was a clean finish. Titans took it deep, had wickets in hand and the experienced Miller took them over the line. SRH were probably unders after being stifled in the powerplay. Four batters made 20s and three between 15 and 20. In contrast, all four of Titans' top order got more than 25. Saha attacked Shahbaz, got boundaries off Unadkat and Bhuvi too. Gill carried on with Sai Sudharsan with the asking rate not mounting. SRH were trying to get a good chunk of their spinners' overs out but it led to only two wickets in the first ten. Gill's wicket didn't open up the game as Miller joined Sudharsan. Cummins' entry slowed the rate, Miller was hobbling at times but the 24-run 16th over off Markande meant there were no death-overs worries. Vijay Shankar too chipped in with a cameo in the end.

nickH: "GT's 20th over and SRH's 16th over decided the game."

text: length ball on the stumps. Shaw flicks it straight towards short midwicket
preText:
7.30pm Here we go. Shaw to face, Chahar has got the ball. A first slip and a third slip in place.

Azweer : "Moeen Ali deserves a chance in Playing XI." -- The question is in place of whom.

Shaw's inclusion means he will be facing Chahar, a match-up the seamer has enjoyed: 6 dismissals in 68 balls for 85 runs in the IPL.

Here are the XIs:

Delhi Capitals: 1 Shaw, 2 Warner, 3 Marsh, 4 Pant (capt, wk), 5 Stubbs, 6 Porel, 7 Axar, 8 Nortje, 9 Mukesh, 10 Ishant, 11 Khaleel
Impact Players Sumit, Kushagra, Salam, Dubey, Jake Fraser-McGurk

Chennai Super Kings: 1 Gaikwad (capt), 2 Ravindra, 3 Rahane, 4 Mitchell, 5 Jadeja, 6 Rizvi, 7 Dhoni (wk), 8 Chahar, 9 Pathirana, 10 Deshpande, 11 Mustafizur
Impact Players: Dube, Shardul, Rasheed, Moeen, Santner

"We were looking to field first," Ruturaj Gaikwad says, "as it is a fresh wicket and the first game here and there's not much information about the pitch. Definitely a home game today [lots of yellow shirts in the stands]. We are going with an unchanged side."

7pm Delhi Capitals have won the toss and opted to bat. "The wicket looks good," says Pant. "We came early here and have practised a lot, which gives us a pretty good idea." Kuldeep Yadav has a niggle and Ricky Bhui has been left out. Prithvi Shaw and Ishant Sharma come in.

6.50pmWhile we wait to see if Shaw gets a game, Varun Aaron has a suggestion for Capitals: Play Kumar Kushagra at No. 3.

Sukrit: "Why is the game not being held in Delhi?" --- They wanted to allow the Delhi pitches some time to recover after the WPL games, so shifted the first two matches to Vizag.

6.40pm More from Deiva: There's a tinge of grass on the pitch, which suggests CSK will play both Pathirana and Mustafizur. Prithvi Shaw batted at the nets for about 20 minutes on Saturday, but wasn't at his fluent best. Capitals coach Ponting has acknowledged the work he's put in behind the scenes, but it remains to be seen whether he's done enough to break into the team.

Mustafa Moudi: "I know CSK is already a settled side and needs no changes, I feel they must give Shardul Thakur chance. Not only a wicket taking bowler but he is a great batsman too. Moreover, he is in great form as he played an important role in Mumbai's recent Victory in the Ranji Trophy !!"

6.35pm Here's Deivarayan Muthu from the ground: Whose home game is this, really? This is supposed to be DC's adopted home - they even had their pre-season camp in Vizag - but now there are yellow jerseys all around the city. At my hotel, which is about 15 kms away from the ACA-VDCA ground. At Novotel along the Varun beach, where the teams are staying. At lassi and samosa stalls near the venue. Even around the threates, which are screening the brand-new Telugu movie Tillu Square. Hundreds had turned up outside the gate of the ACA-VDCA ground on the eve of the match to catch a glimpse of Dhoni, but he didn't train on Saturday. Vizag has turned up in huge numbers once again on Sunday as Dhoni returns to the scene of his first big innings.

6.30pm Hello and welcome to match 13 of IPL 2024. It's Chennai Super Kings taking on Delhi Capitals in the second game of the day. If you go by the points table, this match is a mismatch. CSK have won their both games and Capitals have lost their both.

Not just that, Capitals have a few injury concerns as well. Ishant Sharma got injured during their opening game. Shai Hope missed the second with back spasm. Anrich Nortje and Jhye Richardson, meanwhile, are on a comeback trail. While Capitals are playing at home, it's not Delhi but Visakhapatnam. They have lost three of the five IPL games they've played here. I am Hemant Brar and will soon be joined by Alan Gardner as we bring you all the action. While we wait for the toss, have a look at Deivarayan Muthu's match preview.

preText:
7:28pm The crowd have come out in good numbers. Rohit and Kishan are welcomed with a cheer. Trent Boult will have the new ball. Two slips.

Bandit: "Yeah, I was looking at MI's lineup and their impact subs too and thought it was strange. I'm guessing once Dhir gets out, they sub in Brevis? Or maybe Shepherd?" Yeah, Sampath and I were discussing the same. Shepherd if they falter a bit. Thushara could come if they bat well.

Rajat: "MI 11 looks wrong. They should have extra batter in playing 11. "

Here's a recap from about Akash Madhwal, who's in for MI today - How Akash Madhwal engineered his way into IPL record books

MI Impact subs - Nehal Wadhera, Shams Mulani, Romario Shepherd, Nuwan Thushara, Dewald Brevis

Mumbai Indians: 1 Rohit Sharma, 2 Ishan Kishan (wk), 3 Naman Dhir, 4 Tilak Varma, 5 Hardik Pandya (capt), 6 Tim David, 7 Gerald Coetzee 8 Piyush Chawla, 9 Akash Madhwal, 10 Jasprit Bumrah, 11 Kwena Maphaka

RR Impact Subs - Kuldeep Sen, Shubham Dubey, Tanush Kotian, Rovman Powell, Abid Mushtaq

Rajasthan Royals: 1 Yashasvi Jaiswal, 2 Jos Buttler, 3 Sanju Samson (capt & wk), 4 Riyan Parag, 5 Shimron Hetmyer, 6 Dhruv Jurel, 7 R Ashwin, 8 Trent Boult, 9 Avesh Khan, 10 Nandre Burger, 11 Yuzvendra Chahal.

Hardik Pandya does get booed for the length of his first sentence. Says he was wanted to bowl. Good toss to lose, we'll see what we can put up. (Mumbai's 250th game) This franchise holds a lot of value and a lot of love from the fans (boos go up again but he keeps loud and firm), exciting to be very honest. (It gets quieter again) We are quite lucky to be part of the 250th game. Slow start doesn't bother us. We hope to have clarity, keep the mood happy and light. This group is all about that. Looking forward to play a brand of cricket everyone enjoys and gets that two points.

Sanju Samson: Bowling first (gets a small cheer after that) says they are confident. This is the first game here, hope the seamers will use the conditions upfront. Confident from the wins but the tournament has not yet started so we need to keep going. Sandeep misses out, he's not 100% fit. Burger in the XI.

7pm Sanjay Manjrekar is out for the toss with Hardik Pandya and Sanju Samson. Sanjay asks for a big round of applause for Hardik but there is a boo. "Behave," he says. RR have won the toss and will bowl. Small cheer from the crowd

Pitch report: Pitch No. 7 being used. Not used in IPL 2023. Brian Lara says the red-soil surface looks great. It has a generous covering of grass and the team that's bowling first has to get new-ball wickets. We're gonna see a lot of runs. Not sure spinners are gonna come into the game because of the grass. What the team does on winning the toss will be crucial - RR have won batting first. MI have chased, they came short (although they made 246 in 278-run chase). The team batting first will have the advantage.

Sujatha : "Looking Hardik as a villain is totally uncalled for. It is sport , professional sport , a Franchise driven league. Employers need results and emotions need to be set aside. With Hardik and backing him" Think (and hope) his employers are supporting him. It's massive as Tom Moody said. The chat among the public and how things are from a cultural pov is fascinating. Agree that villanising him is uncalled for. R Ashwin's comments on it were interesting too.

Match Preview by Karthik Krishnaswany Can slow starters MI kick into gear on a batting paradise?

6:40pm RR have shown glimpses of being the shrewd franchise that they are by showing flexibility with their Impact Player choices and bowling selections. Sandeep Sharma has been amaze at the death, Avesh Khan can offer him support. Nandre Burger can chomp into top orders with the new ball. R Ashwin and Yuzi Chahal are skilful spinners but won't have helpful conditions. That's a challenge, as is Jos Buttler's poor form. But he'll have a local batter in Yashasvi Jaiswal familiar with the conditions. Their middle order was taken down in the last game but Ashwin came in and gave them an escape. They'll look to bounce back in that department.

Abhi: "@Ekanth, Rajath didn't mean that when he said toss!" Ah, if it's the Pandya reception, yeah, that too, as highlighted in the opening para.

Rajath : "I think i am not the only one who is more excited for toss more than the match." A belter is expected and these two teams have a pattern, so the toss could be crucial.

Mustafa Moudi : "With DC's win last match, Mumbai Indians remains the only winless side now. Hardik's captaincy hasnt changed MI's old habit of starting slow in the tournament. Hope the y get their first win tonight !!"

Comment by Sidharth Monga The People vs Hardik Pandya - why, what, and the way out

6:30pm MI are back at the Wankhede for the first time in IPL 2024 and Hardik Pandya will lead them for the first time, at home, as permanent captain. He's back to his roots as MI was the franchise that gave him his big break back in 2015. But coming back after leading Gujarat Titans to a title win and a final hasn't been seamless. Their season opener, in Gujarat, saw him get booed. But that continuing in Hyderabad was what's surprising. How the home crowd receives him will be a point of intrigue but his team needs to win. That's the bigger picture and might silence the criticism too.

Yuzvendra Chahal: It's a good wicket. I was trying to vary pace and lengths, and bowl good balls. (On Hardik wicket ball) Before that, I saw a couple of balls turn. Thought this was the time to take a chance, so said let's try this ball (in the slot). I always back my self-belief and skills. In this format I know we can go for hits and wickets in others but our team wanted wickets at that stage and I went for it. There was a bit of dew after 16th over but we need to have a good first six.

9:20pm RR well set to get the second win for a travelling team in this IPL. The pitch was said to be a good one to bat on but Boult and Burger ensured that wasn't the case. The former got two in the first over. He didn't try to swing it as Rohit expected, to nick him off. Then did swing it to Naman to have him lbw. Brevis as impact sub didn't work. Kishan was positive but was done in by a Test-like beauty that seamed away a bit. Nicked him off. Hardik tried turning the tide with a counterattack but perished for 34. Chahal got him by flighting the ball. He was among the wickets, Ashwin bowled tight. The back half of the innings was a slow fizzle. MI batted out their overs but seem unders.

text: Starts off with a back of length delivery wide of off. Jaiswal wafts at it but is late into the shot. Quiet appeal from the slip cordon
preText: 9.31pm Thanks Ekanth. Let's see if Mumbai Indians can make a fight out of it. Who takes the new ball will be interesting to see. Hardik looks at ease as he leads the team out. Jaiswal and Buttler are out there. Jaiswal will be on strike first up. And it's... Kwena Maphaka who will bowl the first over! MI think the left-arm quick formula will continue to work in the powerplay? It's a different ball game in the second innings though. Let's find out how he goes!

Top edge as he tries to pull a short ball goes over the keeper and earns Royals the win!
postText:
11.25pm So, that's three wins in three for Rajasthan Royals. But even a return to their home ground could not help Mumbai Indians avoid defeat for the third consecutive game. There were some boos for Hardik, several cheers for Rohit, but it was the Royals bowlers who stole the show. Trent Boult was sublime with the new ball, with two wickets in the first over. Mumbai lost three players for golden ducks thanks to the left-arm quick. Nandre Burger was also great with the new ball as Royals dominated the powerplay. Chahal helped take out the middle order and that left Royals chasing 126. Maphaka started with Jaiswal's wicket in the first over and Bumrah bowled a probing spell without luck, but Akash Madhwal's two strikes just around the end of the powerplay gave Mumbai Indians a sniff at an upset. But with Ashwin pushed up the order to arrest a potential collapse, Parag continued to impress as he played a calm, nerveless knock to eventually make sure Royals won without much fuss. Akash Madhwal's performance will be a rare positive for Mumbai Indians, but they know they have a lot of work to do. For Royals, they would want Buttler and Jaiswal - their gun openers - to start firing soon. While those teams ponder about what's next for them, we are going to wind down here. You can read Sreshth's report, meanwhile, for a recap of the game. Thank you for joining us. On behalf of Ekanth, Chandan and everyone else at ESPNcricinfo, this is Abhimanyu signing off. Goodnight!

11.12pm Time for the presentation ceremony, then.

The player of the match is, as expected, Trent Boult: "[First over wickets] Never say it's a certainty in the format, but it was nice to get the wickets. We created early pressure, nice to take some wickets and glad the result went our way. [On the Rohit wicket] I've played against Rohit a lot over the years and it was just about trying to do something different. It rarely comes off, you try something different and it works, but great when it does. [On Burger] He has been a great find. Bowls with great skill and plays with his heart on his sleeves. Sandeep obviously missed out but he'll play a big role in the season. Excited to be part of this bowling attack."

Rajasthan Royals captain, Sanju Samson: "[The toss] I think that was the gamechanger. The toss was very crucial. I felt it was too sticky to start off and we had the experience of Trent Boult and Nandre Burger's speed. [Boult] has been playing international cricket for so long and we expected him to deliver. I didn't expect four or five wickets down, but it was great. We all do our roles and move on. Someone like R Ashwin knew we had a good powerplay so he didn't go for wickets, just kept it tight. So it's about teamwork."

10.56pm Riyan Parag's assured innings, along with handy contributions from R Ashwin and Shubham Dubey have helped Royals seal this chase with ease. A fired up early spell from Bumrah and Madhwal saw Royals lose three wickets early-ish, but Parag marshalled the chase expertly. Of course, it was Trent Boult and Nandre Burger and the rest of their bowlers who set up the win.

Riyan Parag: "Actually, I've simplified everything instead of trying to do a lot of things. Earlier when I wasn't getting runs I would try a lot of different things. This year, it's just seeing the ball and hitting the ball. When I play domestically this is the exact kind of situations I go into bat. When Jos bhai and Ash bhai got out, I thought to myself this is what I do in domestic cricket. So that's what I calculated/ [On difference between domestic level and IPL level] I have had three-four years of not performing at all. And you really go back to the hotel room and think when you know you can do it and the results are not coming, you go back to the drawing room. I realised I wasn't practicing at this kind of level so I went and did that. I practiced these kind of quick balls and these kind of scenarios a lot and hence the performances."

Hardik Pandya: "We didn't start the way we wanted to, tough night tonight. [On his innings] I think we were in a decent position to give us a chance to get to 150 or 160 but I think my wicket changed the game and brought them more in the game and I think I could have done better. [The pitch] It's good to have something for the bowlers as well. The game is quite cruel to the bowlers. But it was unexpected. It's all about doing the right things. Results, sometimes it happens sometimes it doesn't. I don't think much surprises me anymore. But as a group we believe we can pull off a lot of better things going forward and we just need to be more disciplined and show more courage."

Gaurav: "Does Parag get the Orange Cap, or it remains with Kohli?" Parag has it now, thanks to a better strike rate than Virat Kohli.

Mohan: "MI need to replace Maphaka and Coetzee with Nuvan Thusara and Nabi as their overseas players to make squad stronger."

Arjun: "Two things happened in the last ball of the innings. Coetzee bowled the fastest ball of this IPL at 157 kph and Riyan Parag got 4 runs to get the Orange Cap. " The latter is correct. The former was a glitch! That was at around 141kph, not 157, even though the TV did show it at 157!

text: on the fuller side of a length just outside off, with the ball angled in from over the wicket. Tapped towards cover-point
preText:
One wide slip for Topley, as the action begins.

The umpires walk out, followed by Rahul and Quinton de Kock. Topley will open the bowling for RCB. De Kock on strike.

7.25pm The ground looks jampacked - as is always the case in Bangalore - with the pitch wearing a greenish look. There are a fair bit of cracks on it, with 61m square boundaries in play today. It is unusually hot in Bangalore, with no sign of rain at least until the IPL ends.

"First four players in LSG lineup once played for RCB" --- As Sid Monga reminded us the other day, loyalties don't last in franchise cricket, Nikhil Sai Paru

LSG: 1 Quinton de Kock (wk), 2 KL Rahul (capt), 3 Devdutt Padikkal 4 Marcus Stoinis, 5 Nicholas Pooran, 6 Ayush Badoni, 7 Krunal Pandya, 8 Ravi Bishnoi, 9 Yash Thakur, 10 Mayank Yadav, 11 Naveen-ul-Haq. Impact Subs: Siddharth, Joseph, Hooda, Mishra and Gowtham

RCB: 1 Faf du Plessis (capt), 2 Virat Kohli, 3 Rajat Patidar, 4 Glenn Maxwell, 5 Cameron Green, 6 Dinesh Karthik, 7 Anuj Rawat (wk), 8 Reece Topley, 9 Mayank Dagar, 10 Mohammed Siraj, 11 Yash Dayal. Impact Subs: Prabhudesai, Lomror, Karn, Vyshak and Swapnil

7pm KL Rahul is out for the toss... but RCB win the toss and bowl first. Faf du Plessis calls the Chinnaswamy pitch "patchy". He says his side needs to "find answers" to tighten things up. Du Plessis says Topley replaces Alzarri Joseph. Rahul, playing on his home ground for Karnataka, asks his side to "relax" and put up some big runs on the board tonight. He plays Yash Thakur for Mohsin Khan.

Nisha: "Watch out for Nic Pooran: the ever dangerous, clean striker" --- As they say, he isn't fazed by captaincy either

"Rahul was used as Impact Sub by LSG in their last game, which makes our experts wonder how they will use him today. As for RCB, Mitchell McClenaghan feels they should slot in both Reece Topley and Lockie Ferguson into the playing XI.

6.45pm RCB's batting hasn't quite fired, and they will hope it finally does today. That is what Shashank Kishore's preview states. After all, the likes of du Plessis and Maxwell are yet to kick into gear for the hosts. LSG, meanwhile, have concerns around their captain KL Rahul, who they are looking to only ease back into action. Rahul didn't keep wicket for much of training on the eve of the game, and stand-in captain Nicholas Pooran only said "we'll see how he goes".

6.30pm Hello and welcome to the Chinnaswamy. Not quite a fortress yet for Royal Challengers Bengaluru, who sit at No. 9 in the points table. They have a tight win squeezed in between two losses where they fought before losing their way. That said, Lucknow Super Giants haven't started too well either. They won their second match by nearly the same margin as they lost the first. This is Himanshu saying hello, and I'll be with you or the first innings.

postText:
Elsewhere, FIVE Indians are aiming to be world champions in Chess. Their journey begins at the FIDE Candidates tournament tomorrow, which decides who can challenge the reigning champion - here's all you need to know.

Time-out

text: short of a length on leg and moving away, and clipped to deep square leg
preText: Siraj will continue

shortText: Mohammed Siraj to de Kock, no run

shortText: Mohammed Siraj to de Kock, SIX
text: clubbed over long-on! On a length on middle, and this one moves away again, but de Kock is deep in the crease, with his front leg out of the way. Big six for him

shortText: Mohammed Siraj to de Kock, 1 run
text: low full angling across, and finishing around sixth stump. He goes low to slice it to deep third

wkt_text: D Padikkal c †Anuj Rawat b Mohammed Siraj 6 (14m 11b 0x4 0x6) SR: 54.54
text: taken by Rawat running back! He turned around and started chasing the ball, going down on his haunches to take the ball which was dropping over his head, taking it just over his face. Rawat didn't get distracted by deep third running forward either. Siraj went for a back-of-a-length ball this time, landing it on leg. Padikkal cleared his front leg, and went for the pull, but only managed to get a top edge
the third wide of the over. Siraj went for a bouncer on leg, with the ball moving away sharply to finish outside off. Padikkal let it go, with the ball dying on to the batter
a full toss dipping and landing outside leg, as he looked to clip but missed. Another wide
ahh, this is too high, and hence called wide! The keeper had to leap full stretch to take that, with Padikkal swaying away at this bouncer on middle

shortText: Mohammed Siraj to Stoinis, no run
text: short of a length again. This is outside off and coming on top of the stumps. Blocked back by Stoinis
preText: Stoinis

text: on a length just outside off, and slapped to deep point
starts with five wides! Full ball another set of stumps outside leg, with de Kock going to sweep but missing. Even the keeper beaten while moving to his right
preText: Dagar replaces Maxwell. From around to de Kock.

text: full and dipping on off. Driven wide of long-off
postText: Sowmya: "DDP never looked at any ease during his stay. Being a Bengaluru boy, he must have known the pitch better and batted with ease"

text: ahh, well stopped by Karthik at point! He dived to his left to keep it to one, with de Kock slashing at this length ball wide of off
full and flat on off, and driven off the inside half of the bat to long-on
length ball on the stumps, and clipped to deep square leg
full ball on middle and off, and driven to long-off
preText: Chuvi: "8.5 Just not an easy catch at all. With the cap on, it is even tougher. Very good catch"

text: angles this in, and bowls a low full toss on leg. Flicked to fine leg, as Stoinis sits deep in the crease to whip it away wide of the fielder
preText: Green into the attack

text: good bounce from a length just outside off, with the ball finishing on top of middle. Pushed towards cover
gets across, and flicked to fine leg! He exposed all his stumps to this full ball just outside off, and clipped it with his front leg in the air to Siraj's right

shortText: Green to de Kock, no run
text: gets across, and looks to slash this fullish ball wide of off, which is angled across. But he's beaten again, as de Kock loses his momentum after a rapid start

shortText: Green to de Kock, no run
text: another one that goes past his bat! This time he went swinging at this length ball angling away and landing a bit wide of off, but didn't connect
drills this full ball angling away towards off, and gets a single wide of mid-off
on the bounce to long-off running forward! De Kock made room and went lofting this fullish ball angling across and finishing outside off
length ball on the stumps, and pushed back
preText: Sindh: "Is it me or does every one feel Stoinis looks always angry? He always looks like he is in for gladiator fight" --- I agree, kind of!

text: ahh, slows it down to bowl full on his pads. Tickled to short fine, as de Kock calls for the single
belted back down the ground! That is also de Kock's fifty. He hangs deep in the crease at this length ball, which is flat and just outside off, before ramming it back between long-off and long-on

shortText: Dagar to de Kock, no run
text: full and wide of off, and left alone. Wide not called
six just over the rope! Again de Kock goes over the bowler's head, with Dagar bowling full and just outside off, and de Kock allowing himself to get on top of the ball by hanging back
full toss swinging into off, and driven wide of mid-off
preText: Junaid Anwar: "Quin half-a-ton"

text: the ball flies over the deep-point boundary! He lets this low full toss arrive outside off - the ball was dipping - as he sliced this from deep in the crease. Looked very good
quite full and just outside off, and driven to long-on
hammered over deep square leg! Another full toss from Green, as this one lands just below his waist on the stumps. Swung away for six more, this time by Stoinis
on a length just outside off, and coming into the stumps. Pushed towards cover for a quick single
lofted wide of long-off! De Kock in punishing mood now. He squats a little, and reaches out at this length ball which is wide of off. Presents the full face of the bat to lift it over mid-off
heaved over deep midwicket! That is massive hit! The full ball on the stumps dips on to the batter, with Stoinis heaving it powerfully for a huge hit
preText: Maxwell will bowl out

text: quicker, and on a length on off. Turns in, and is punched to long-off

shortText: Maxwell to de Kock, no run
text: slower, and fuller on middle and leg. Defended back to the bowler
shorter in length, and outside off. Swiped behind square for a single

wkt_text: MP Stoinis c Dagar b Maxwell 24 (20m 15b 1x4 2x6) SR: 160.00
text: taken by Dagar! He was placed at point, and saw the ball come on to his right, as he moved a few steps and grabbed with both hands. Maxwell strikes again, as he bowls short and wide of off. Stoinis had backed away early, so the line of the ball meant that it was quite wide of him. He eventually reached out for it, and ended up swatting to the fielder
full ball dipping on off, and blocked towards cover
preText: Pooran in, with Maxwell from around

shortText: Yash Dayal to de Kock, no run

preText: Dayal back

shortText: Yash Dayal to de Kock, no run

shortText: Yash Dayal to de Kock, 1 run

preText: Pandey Dai: "More sixes than fours are normal now. How the game has changed!"

shortText: Yash Dayal to de Kock, no run
text: a half-hearted shout for caught behind by Rawat, but it is instead called wide. They have a chat... and du Plessis reviews. Bouncer on off, with the ball seaming back in to finish on leg. There is good bounce, with de Kock looking to pull and the ball going over his bat. Multiple replays are checked, and the third umpire confirms it is not a wide. The ball went just over the gloves there, with the not-out decision standing

shortText: Yash Dayal to de Kock, no run
text: superb bowling! He follows a bouncer with a yorker, swinging it away and going wide of off. De Kock went reaching for it, but missed
a bouncer on middle, with the ball finishing around fifth stump. Dabbed to short third, as he rides the bounce
preText: Siraj returns

shortText: Mohammed Siraj to de Kock, no run

preText: Karthik: "That's a match-winning over if there ever was one"

shortText: Mohammed Siraj to de Kock, FOUR
text: this time he beats mid-off! Du Plessis dives to his left, but is beaten. De Kock is again deep in the crease, and drills this full ball wide-ish of off

shortText: Mohammed Siraj to de Kock, no run
text: again Siraj goes for the short ball on middle, getting it to angle away towards off. De Kock went to pull but was beaten

shortText: Mohammed Siraj to de Kock, FOUR

shortText: Mohammed Siraj to de Kock, 1 run
text: gets his front leg out of the way at this full toss on middle and leg, and whips it to deep square
postText:
Upendra: "Here is my prediction: De Kock to hit 100 and Pooran to hit 50 by the end of LSG innings" --- LSG fans would want nothing else!

Time-out

preText: Four overs to go. De Kock on 80. LSG eyeing around 200, probably.

wkt_text: Q de Kock c Dagar b Topley 81 (76m 56b 8x4 5x6) SR: 144.64

slower ball, and full on off. Clipped to midwicket
preText: Badoni

text: full and quicker on middle and off, and hoicked off the inside half of the bat to midwicket

preText: Dayal into his final over

shortText: Yash Dayal to Pooran, no run

shortText: Yash Dayal to Pooran, no run

clubbed on the bounce to long-off, as he gets another slower ball, which is on the fullish side around off

wkt_text: A Badoni c du Plessis b Yash Dayal 0 (5m 3b 0x4 0x6) SR: 0.00

Dayal went for a bouncer, angling it across, while also changing the pace. The ball rose rather sharply, and was very wide of off. Badoni still went swatting, but ended up getting it off the outside half of the bat

this is a wide, though. He goes full and pretty wide outside off, with Pooran leaving it alone

ahh, Topley goes back to his yorker-length ball which is wide of off. Pitches it around sixth stump, with Pooran attempting to loft but missing. Wide not called, but LSG review. It stays the same, though
this is another full toss, but this is low and dipping around sixth stump. Dragged to long-on, as he plays away from his body

shortText: Mohammed Siraj to Pooran, no run
text: starts with a wide yorker, which he angles across and bowls in the channel. Pooran went swinging, but missed
preText: Siraj back
postText: "After Topley's previous over, I was about to type that Topley is such an upgrade over Joseph. Little did I know that you can jinx by even thinking about it" --- The Gods know it all, Anshul!

Pooran reviews for a potential wide again, but the third umpire observes that there is movement across by Pooran, and that the ball is close to the bat. So it remains

now over deep midwicket! He pulls hard at this short-of-a-length ball on middle, getting his front leg out of the way to hammer this for six more
Starts with a length ball outside off that spins away, Kohli plays it late, pushing it towards point
preText: 9.20pm Kohli and Faf are raring to go. 182 is the target, and on this ground, that should be gettable. But LSG's bowlers are no pushovers. Rahul is set to keep, he is leading the LSG huddle. M Siddharth is on as LSG's impact player and he is in action straight away

text: A bit of a drag down, Kohli muscles a pull wide of mid-on to get RCB away

shortText: Siddharth to du Plessis, no run
text: Length ball angling in on off, du Plessis parries to the off side
Length ball punched down the ground to long-off
Darts in a length ball that angles in from outside off, Kohli wants to whip it leg side but ends up blocking it back to the bowler
Driven out to long-off for a single
Full on middle, quick and darted into his pads. Kohli clips it away to deep midwicket
preText: More SLA! Krunal Pandya from the other end!

text: Lofted down the ground and Kohli has his first boundary. On a full length around off, Kohli makes room and swings through the line. Falls just short of the boundary
Steers a length ball towards short third
Darts in a quick ball at 112kph around middle, Faf gets an inside edge through to fine leg and they scramble for a single

Length ball around middle, whipped to mid-on for a quick single

text: Pushes it through quick on a length on off, du Plessis backs away and punches it out to long-off
