text: Slower through the air, on a length around off, Kohli cuts it hard, but straight to the cover fielder
Tucked through midwicket for an easy single as Siddharth gives chase
Just short of cover! This ball drifts away as du Plessis looks to come down the ground. Ends up miscuing a drive towards Bishnoi at cover who dives to his left, but the ball just dips on him
Hammered down the ground for four! It's a length ball outside off, du Plessis backs away and flat-bats it to the bowler's right
Shot! Short-ish and du Plessis slaps it away through cover. The fielder put in a dive but that was hit too hard for him!
Full outside off and angling in, Kohli steps ahead and across and whips it to mid-on
preText: Change of bowling. Naveen-ul-Haq into the attack. Kohli on strike

text: Pitched up outside off at 133kph, Kohli spanks a drive on the off side but hits it straight to mid-off now
preText: "Kohli, Kohli" chants get louder!

text: Lofted straight into the sightscreen! Length ball at 139kph angles in from outside off, Kohli just takes a step forward and drives it straigh back down the ground. Pure class
preText: shashank: "We are moving into an era where slow bowlers are trying to bowl fast while fast bowlers bowl slow cutters!"

text: Low full toss outside off but Kohli misses out! Can only whip it to midwicket
preText: There's a short mid-off for Kohli now

shortText: Naveen-ul-Haq to du Plessis, no run

Chipped over mid-on! In the slot around off and du Plessis just stands and lofts it down the ground
Dropped short around off and Kohli cracks a cut in front of point. Picks the gap expertly and the ball races away
preText: Siddharth to bowl his third on the trot

wkt_text: V Kohli c Padikkal b Siddharth 22 (16m 16b 2x4 1x6) SR: 137.50

Length ball outside off, Patidar punches it to cover point
preText: Rajat Patidar out at No. 3 today

text: Full on leg, tucked through midwicket and he gets off the mark
preText: Sukanta: "Oh! Will miss Kohli vs Mayank" I was kind of looking forward to that contest as well!

shortText: Siddharth to du Plessis, no run
text: On a length on middle, du Plessis parries towards cover
Length ball outside off, du Plessis slaps it straight of cover on the bounce and finishes the over with a single
preText: Srini: "Giving a 3rd over on the trot to Siddharth kills the suprise factor and can be counter productive." Well, it worked for them today!
postText: Mujahid : "Good bowling by Sidharth."

preText: And here's Mayank Yadav

text: Length ball at 144.2kph outside off, steers it past backward point for a single
preText: Maxwell will have to start off at the non-striker's end

Very full just outside off, Green jams his bat down to steer it past the slip fielder
preText: Cam Green now

text: Clipped away through midwicket! This was very full and very straight, Patidar nudges it past the diving fielder for his first boundary. This one was at 153kph!
Tossed up full around off, Green leans ahead and chips it past the non-striker for a couple

Drags a length ball down leg side

Length ball clipped through midwicket for a single

shortText: Ravi Bishnoi to Green, no run

text: Full on off, flicked out to deep midwicket
Mayank Yadav angles in a length ball from outside off, steered to backward point

First ball of Mayank's last ball, 7.1 that is, was recorded at 156.7kph, making it the fastest ball this season!

Time for the timeout

shortText: Yadav to Anuj Rawat, no run

Swung over deep backward square! This is a length ball on middle and he flicks it off his hips, using the pace of the ball and helping it on fine on the leg side
Length ball around off, punched out to sweeper cover

text: Full outside off, Rawat steers to backward point and takes off for a quick single but is turned back.The fielder has a shy at the stumps, but misses and the overthrow lets RCB get the run

text: Full on middle and leg, swept to deep square leg

text: Krunal drops a sitter at deep midwicket! This is a bit short and Rawat rocks back and pulls it flat, but the ball bobbles out of Krunal's hands!
Patidar taking us back to that knock against LSG with this shot! In the arc and he swings it high over cow corner

preText: Stoinis into the attack

Now Stoinis fires a bouncer over Rawat, and KL Rahul, as it goes for five wides
Stoinis angles a back of length delivery from outside off, Lomror is beaten on the cut
Full around off, miscued through midwicket

Slapped away behind point! Short outside off, enough width for him to free his arms and hit it flat. They have to check if it's a boundary or a six. Did it hit the boundary rope on the full? Nope, four given
Full around off and going across him, 139.1kph, Lomror guides it to deep third

shortText: Yash Thakur to Lomror, 1 leg bye
text: All sorts of confusion there! This is full around leg and Lomror misses his flick. Thakur goes up in appeal for lbw as the ball pops towards backward point. Hooda, the fielder, runs in and misses his throw as Lomror had taken off for a single and was being sent off. The over throw lets them get a run
Full around off,flicked away through midwicket
Length ball outside off, 144.3kph, punched to backward point
preText: Mayank Yadav's final over

wkt_text: RM Patidar c Padikkal b Yadav 29 (50m 21b 2x4 2x6) SR: 138.09
text: Top edge goes high in the air. Devdutt Padikkal makes no mistake at deep square leg! It's banged in short, Patidar goes for the pull and skies it. Devdutt Padikkal had to move around to settle under it, but never took his eyes off it and ends up grabbing it to send Patidar back in the hut. Mayank has his third!
Length ball outside off at 149.3kph, Karthik leaves it well alone
preText: Dinesh Karthik, possibly RCB's last hope today

text: Back of length delivery angling down leg, Karthik nudges it down square on the leg side. This one was at 147kph

Mayank Yadav has his fourth! He traps Karthik! But DK reviews. It angles in from outside off to rap him on the front pad. Could this be going high? This was bowled at around 147kph, btw. Okay, no wicket no. 4 for Mayank yet. That's shown to be going above the stumps so Karthik survives

Back of length outside off, Karthik punches it out to deep point for a single. An electric, exhilerating spell from Mayank Yadav comes to an end. Four wickets fell off his four overs, including a run out which was more thanks to Padikkal than anything else, and only 14 runs conceded
Length ball around off, Karthik drops it square on the leg side

<s>dropped by Pant!</s> It is called byes, with the umpire saying no bat involved. It wasn't easy to take for Pant either, as he leapt up full stretch, with the ball flying off the top edge. The ball took the gloves and went off, as Salt went slashing at this back-of-a-length ball outside off, which was angling across
preText:
Khaleel to Salt, with a slip and gully. Ready to start., but... Salt does some digging first.

Salt and Narine walk out to open for KKR. Khaleel has the new ball for DC.

7.25pm Just about five minutes for the first ball. The stadium in Visakhapatnam is mostly painted blue, although there are shades of purple sprinkled around too. The umpires shake hands on their way out, before Warner chirps in the DC huddle.

Afeef: "Keep in mind that fielding substitutes also have to be among the list of Impact Players, that's usually why overseas players are named even though there are four in the starting XI"

Drew: "Why is Fraser-McGurk a sub? I didn't think an overseas player could be an impact sub if the team already has four overseas named?" --- An overseas player can be part of the Impact Sub list for cases like one of the starting overseas players getting ruled out by concussion

Kolkata Knight Riders: 1 Phil Salt (wk), 2 Sunil Narine, 3 Venkatesh Iyer, 4 Shreyas Iyer (capt), 5 Angkrish Raghuvanshi, 6 Rinku Singh, 7 Andre Russell, 8 Ramandeep Singh, 9 Mitchell Starc, 10 Harshit Rana, 11 Varun Chakravarthy. Impact Subs: Suyash, Anukul, Pandey, Arora and Gurbaz

Delhi Capitals: 1 Prithvi Shaw, 2 David Warner, 3 Rishabh Pant (capt, wk), 4 Mitchell Marsh, 5 Tristan Stubbs, 6 Axar Patel, 7 Sumit Kumar, 8 Rasikh Salam, 9 Anrich Nortje, 10 Ishant Sharma, 11 Khaleel Ahmed. Impact Subs: Porel, Kushagra, Dubey, Lalit and Fraser-McGurk

"To bat first is a brave call. Is dew not expected tonight? " --- Neither captain mentioned about it, Shrikant. Maybe it isn't expected, after all.

7pm We are set for the swing of the coin. KKR win the toss and bat. Iyer says the pitch looks like a "belter to bat on". He says it might not make a lot of difference even as he played for DC until a few seasons back. Raghuvanshi is back for KKR. Pant, meanwhile, would have batted first too, given he expects the pitch to slow down. He hit his first fifty last game after his comeback, and is happy to take it day by day. DC have one change: Sumit replaces an injured Mukesh.

Ishant Sharma leads the DC huddle, with all eyes on ears intently on him. We are less than five minutes away from the toss, so hang around while sipping some hot cold coffee.

6.45pm Both DC and KKR have some thinking to do ahead of today's contest. The hosts have still not had their opening batter Prithvi Shaw at his best. He has had a bit of a rollercoaster ride, as Deiva Muthu writes. Their other concern is about the fast bowler Anrich Nortje, who has returned from a long injury lay-off. Tom Moody, our expert, thinks "Nortje isn't quite back at his full pace" yet. As for KKR, they spent INR 24 crore on Mitchell Starc alone, but... is he running out of time already? Moody and Varun Aaron ponder.

In a quick recap of the points table, DC are at No. 7 at the moment, with KKR pretty high up at No. 2. A hat-trick of wins for KKR would mean they draw level on points with Rajasthan Royals, who are also unbeaten. That reminder, and much more in Ashish Pant's preview for today.

6.30pm A former DC captain comes back home, but instead as the leader of the opposition. Meanwhile, his replacement at DC has returned to full flow after missing out on plenty of cricket. KKR, the side Shreyas Iyer brings to Visakhapatnam tonight, face Rishabh Pant's team, who got off the mark three days back at the same ground. We are into Match No. 16 of Season 17 of the IPL, as this is Himanshu saying hello.

wkt_text: SS Iyer c Stubbs b Ahmed 18 (23m 11b 0x4 2x6) SR: 163.63
text: taken at mid-off! Shreyas falls to the short ball. Khaleel bowled outside off, as the ball almost seemed to have rushed through to Shreyas, who went pulling but got it off the top edge. Stubbs kept his eyes on the skied ball, and took it reverse cupped
on a few bounces to deep point, who fumbles and allows the second. Russell went lofting at this length ball outside off, using all the force in his body
preText: Free hit
postText: Dharmesh: "You must be kidding… to remain in the air for 19 seconds, the ball would have had to travel 1763m upwards" --- I wouldn't have been a commentator had I been that good at math!

text: a high full toss almost in front of his face outside off, and slashed to deep point. No-ball called for height
ahh, another wide, but this seemed harsh. Yorker length and wide of off, while swinging away. Left alone by Rinku
preText: Rinku joins Russell

text: sharp pace at 136kph, and on a bouncer-length on sixth stump. He goes slashing, but is beaten
now to deep third on two bounces, as the ball flies off his outside edge after he looks to swing at this length ball outside off
full and a bit wide of off, as it is dragged to mid-off
preText: The crowd chanting "Rinku, Rinku"...

text: ohh, barely six! The man at wide-ish deep third chases to his right, and the ball just about beats him, with Rinku slicing at this full and wide ball outside off, even as he loses his bottom hand
preText:
DC use the Impact Sub: Porel replaces Khaleel. Nortje from around to Rinku.

KKR need another 39 to eclipse SRH's 277... and here comes Nortje to bowl some thunderbolts. And, and... DC are penalised for slow over rate, so only four fielders allowed on the boundary

text: unbelievable! Don't ask me how that went for six! He simply swatted at this full ball dipping around sixth stump, and casually bagged six wide of long-off
on the bounce to deep point's left. Nortje goes short and around sixth stump, as Rinku went hammering at it
wide ball. Goes for the yorker around ninth stump, and is left alone
short ball just outside off. Warner jumps and guides a shot to deep third, one of two outfielders on the boundary line
preText:
Starc to start. KKR have conceded 60+ in their powerplay in both games. Starc, btw, has conceded 100 in eight overs. Capitals to win with two balls to spare? Here we go.

Raghuvanshi is replaced out for fast bowler Vaibhav Arora - impact player activated by KKR.

9.38pm "Knight Riders 15 short?" Surely that's what Ricky Ponting and Sourav Ganguly must be saying in the DC dugout after that sort of battering. The messaging will surely be pretty clear - Warner, Shaw, Marsh, Pant and the rest have to be at their best.

Also keen to see how the KKR spinners do on this small ground. Capitals didn't use a lot of spin, and this is KKR's trump card too.

Lokesh Kumar: "At 19.1 Ishant bowled one of the best ball of his entire career "
postText: shairya: "@Lokesh: completely agree with you. This is ball of the tournament so far. Best bowler vs Best T20 Batter, even Russell appreciated that delivery." -- Take my vote too. Like Rabada's to Russell from the same fixture some seasons ago

text: length ball around off and he plays a tentative cut to the off side
fullish ball just outside off. Prods forward and fends it to the off side. Don't see swing so far
full ball on middle, and a bit of swing into his pads but Shaw uses his wrists to flick it strongly through midwicket. Timing not perfect, but atleast it is in the gap
smartly played over the cordon! Beats deep third too. Starc bends his back and goes short. Shaw lets the ball get across before playing a slash with the bat's face open. Races to the fence
put away, over cover point! Starc errs by giving Shaw width in a length ball. Shaw pummels a smart short, almost lifting it over the infield for four
postText: Anshul: "Shaw is one of those batters who can put a match winning performance against such a huge target, if on song."

text: wrong line, and Warner punishes Vaibhav. Short ball, landing outside leg, and Warner swivels before swinging the bat and putting the loose ball away to fine leg for four
preText: Vaibhav Arora. He has two slips.

text: hurried onto Warner but Warner will get four nonetheless. Short ball, aimed at Warner's body. He tries to pull but ends up top-edging it over Narine at short fine leg. One-bounce four
full ball originating on a leg-stump line but swinging in and landing on middle. Gently tucked off his pads to the on side for a single
preText: Rakesh: "The short ball 95/100 finds the ropes or goes over it, 4 times it results in a dot ball and once it gets a wicket, it is a high run yield = low wicket taking ball, but yet for some strange reason it is over indulged by both the pacers and spinners alike... Silly cricket when you overdo the short ball while defending huge totals."

text: full ball outside off. Warner backs away, and ends up backing away too much. Can't meet the ball after reaching out
postText: Harshad: "More memorable than this single ball was how Ishant tortured Ricky Ponting at WACA."

text: appeal for lbw! Only Vaibhav is interested. Not given Are KKR reviewing? Yes. Height could be a factor here. This was a length ball that moved in sharply after pitching, and hit Shaw after he fended down the wrong line. Too high. Review lost by KKR.

wkt_text: PP Shaw c Varun b Arora 10 (12m 7b 2x4 0x6) SR: 142.85
text: can mid-on get there - yes! Varun Chakravarthy, not particularly known for his fielding, has taken a sensational low catch diving forward. Vaibhav bowls a fullish ball outside off, and the ball swings into Shaw. He tries mow it over mid-on, but mis-hits. The ball doesn't gather a lot of air, so Varun has to take the tough route of diving forward. Mission possible! They go to the TV umpire who confirms it is a clean catch.
back of a length ball outside off. Gets somewhat big on Marsh but he manages to play a cut towards point
full ball around leg. Warner tries to flick but it tickles his pad, and Salt can't stop it on the dive either! Races down to fine leg for four
full ball outside off. Bit of movement away and Warner gets low to clatter a cover drive. Misses, and through to Salt
full ball around off stump. Warner taps it from inside his crease to cover's left
full ball around off stump and Warner offers the full face of the bat to push it back past the bowler

wkt_text: MR Marsh c Ramandeep Singh b Starc 0 (4m 2b 0x4 0x6) SR: 0.00
text: Mitchell gets Mitchell! And that is Starc's first IPL 2024 wicket. Marsh looks to drive this full ball from his body and generates a lot of power on that shot, but not the height, and Ramandeep at cover point intuitively sticks both hands out at the right time. Marsh's poor form continues
preText: Yogesh: "Mitchell to Mitchell."

shortText: Starc to Abishek Porel, no run
text: good length ball just outside off. Porel pokes at it, but the ball moves away after pitching, and whizzes past his outside edge
good length ball originates on leg stump but swings across the left-hander with the seam that's directed towards first slip. To the keeper
fullish ball around off. Warner backs away before stretching out, getting some bat on that to send it to deep third

shortText: Arora to Abishek Porel, no run
text: full ball just outside leg. Flicked off his shin, but straight to midwicket. Fielder throws the stumps down but the batter was inside his crease

shortText: Arora to Abishek Porel, no run
text: full ball around leg and middle stump. Porel assumes the ball with angle across so offers the full face of the bat to drive. Hit to mid off

shortText: Arora to Abishek Porel, no run
text: full ball on off and Porel tries to hammer it back past the bowler but Vaibhav gets low to scoop the ball up on the followthrough!

wkt_text: Abishek Porel c Narine b Arora 0 (5m 5b 0x4 0x6) SR: 0.00
text: short ball too good for Porel! Simple catch for short fine leg. Arora aims for a short ball at Porel's head, and he tries the pull while taking his eyes of the ball. Knocks the youngster over with a classic tall fast bowler's dismissal
short of good length around off stump. Warner taps it towards point after riding the bounce
clubbed away! Home run from Warner. Full ball on off. Warner clears the front leg and clobbers Starc over cow corner.

wkt_text: DA Warner  b Starc 18 (27m 13b 2x4 1x6) SR: 138.46
text: chopped on! Starc gets the second Aussie too. Good length ball on a fifth-stump line. Warner doesn't have the width to cut but goes for it anyway. Under-edge onto the deck and into the stumps. Replay shows Starc changed his pace on the wicket ball
postText: Shrikant : "Pant should have come before Porel and Iyer should have come after Rinku. These are captain's perils "

text: short of good length ball on leg stump. Right-hander Stubbs knocks it off his body to the  leg side
preText: Stubbs.

text: full ball just outside off. Gets low and plays a straight drive, but mistimed. Past the non-striker to mid off
beautiful from Pant! Full ball swinging in but landing outside leg. Pant uses his wrists to flick it languidly off his heel and sends it behind square leg
postText: Gaurav: "If the first innings power play didn't end the game, the second innings one definitely has. "

text: short ball just outside off. Stubbs pull from almost head high. Mistimed to mid on

punchy shot off the back foot and he gets it past point to the backward point four! Excellent shot, waiting on that length ball outside off, and he also had to counter a bit of swing in while playing the shot
lucky for Stubbs that beats short fine leg. Vaibhav digs it in, and Stubbs comes down the ground before bringing out the pull. Absolutely mistimed but fortune favours him there
yorker attempted, very nearly successful. Dug out by Stubbs
short ball just outside off. Mows a mistimed pull to the right of midwicket for a single
full ball on middle, and Pant flicks to deep square leg. Powerplay done there with KKR using only two bowlers in the first six
short ball around leg and Pant doesn't even bother ducking because it's bouncing so much. Wide given. Team fifty
full ball outside off and he clatters a drive to deep cover
preText: Harshit Rana to bowl. RRR is 15.86. And there's a delay because Rana has suddenly left the field. Andre Russell will bowl instead. Manish Pandey as a sub fielder.

text: good length ball on a fourth-stump line. Carefully blocked towards point, off the back foot
good length ball around off again. Pace off delivery this time and Stubbs guides it towards deep third for one

Pant looking in exquisite touch - his second six in four balls! Full ball on middle and leg. Pant doesn't use his feet much, and relies on his hand-eye co-ordination to swipe a six over deep square leg

third six in five balls! Russell tries to deliver a short ball to counter the previous six but Pant was almost expecting it. Pulls, and it is not perfect, but enough on this small ground to beat deep square leg again
preText: Pant might have a niggle.

text: short ball again. Around middle and off. Pant sways away from the ball's line and lets this one go
full ball on middle. Defended with the full face of the bat
preText: Will we see spin now? Yes, Narine.

text: good length ball on off. Narine stays on the back foot and works it with the turn to the leg side
preText: Stat alert: Narine got his highest T20 score earlier today. It was also his 100th batting innings representing KKR

text: full ball outside off. Pant goes across and drags a sweep to deep backward square leg
postText: Varunnath: "All ok with Harshit?" -- No official or unofficial details yet

text: fullish ball on middle and leg. Stubbs gets low to play the reverse sweep. Misses the connection but it hits his body before rolling away behind the keeper
good length ball on leg. Turning towards middle. Pant stays on the back foot and drags a grounded pull to cow corner
terrific ball. Fullish on middle and off but gets some extra bounce. Pant tries to cut but he's surprised by extra spice off the pitch. Inside edged onto his body, and very nearly onto the stumps
postText: AJ: "Loving Rishabh Pant's inning here. That augurs well for India in WC. Jitesh Sharma has not done much with the bat so if Pant can maintain his form and fitness, I would pick him over Jitesh."

text: Chakravarthy gets a rude welcome! Full ball on middle. Turning into leg. Stubbs stays leg side of the ball, clears the front leg and hammers a shot over deep midwicket
preText: Varun.

text: fullish ball on middle, and turning into leg again. This time cramps Stubbs up as he backs away too. Punched to the bowler
high and clears long on! Good length ball around off. Stubbs stays in his crease and flat-bats a shot over the bowler

Chakravarthy can have the last laugh, but dropped by Shreyas at deep midwicket! Stubbs tries to stay aggressive again, and pulls this cramping delivery too square. Shreyas got his body behind that, but the ball popped out!
around the stumps to Pant. Fullish ball on off. Comes down the track and blocked to the off side
full ball outside off. Pant gets in position to play a reverse swipe, but the ball hits his arm and goes to the leg side
postText: Rajkumar Lingav: "Great comeback after those 2 sixes conceded by Varun!!!" -- just needed his captain to back him up

text: full ball just outside off. Bit of turn in. Driven confidently to mid off
good length ball on middle and off. Too close to his body for the cut but he attempts anyway. Gloved past the keeper

full ball on off. Gets low for the sweep. Misses it, and it hits his helmet before going to short third. No LBW appeal because the turn would've taken the ball past off stump anyway. The team doctor runs out to check for concussion
full ball just outside off. Pant mistimes a cut with the ball turning away. Stopped at point
preText: short break

text: Pant uses his feet but Narine bowls a short-ish ball outside leg. Pant ends up in an awkward position  and ends up bunting a shot to the leg side for one
full ball just outside off. Stubbs goes deep in his crease before flat-batting a dragged shot to wide long on. Venkatesh Iyer with some work on the boundary line to stop that strong shot
good length ball from around the stumps. Pant flicks it off the back foot to deep midwicket
good length ball on middle. Hurries onto Stubbs while also getting big on him. Flat-bats a ball uncomfortably to Russell at long on
full ball, quite wider outside off stump. Slapped past Varun after reaching out, and sent to long off
overpitched ball around leg and Stubbs toe-ends a shot to long on for a single
misses his line there. Half-tracker of sorts, landing outside the wide line outside off. Salt does well to move swiftly and stop that
full ball on his toes and Pant clips it away to deep backward square leg, where there is protection

full ball landing just outside leg. Stubbs makes room by backing away and then absolutely hammers a shot straight past the non-striker. Russell runs around from long on and gets there in time, or so it appears. When the camera pans to him, we see Russell picking himself up and the ball resting on the boundary skirting
just clears short fine leg! Short of length ball angling into his body. Pant plays his trademark hook over short fine leg while his head falls over. Not the best execution, but enough!
preText: Venkatesh Iyer, around the wicket to Pant. First time in IPL 2024

text: up and over cover! Good length ball around off and Pant uses the bottom hand to not only drive but drive it in such a way that the shot is lofted over wide long off

gem of an innings! Venkatesh comes over the wicket now, but the result is the same. Rishabh goes very low and then plays a shot with the bat-speed of a flick but the gentleness of a scoop. Dropkicked over fine leg!
around the stumps, and that does not change the result much. Low full toss outside off stump and Pant slices a shot away from his body, sending it behind point. Pant on 47*

a 23-ball fifty for Rishabh Pant! That would make fans of Indian cricket so happy! Fullish ball just outside off. Pant gets low before swinging across the line, and sends it behind square leg for four. Terrific innings
A 28-run over! Another low full toss outside off, near the tram-lines. Pant reaches out and swings the bat in a such a way that it flies off the face of the blade to race away to point for four more
around the stumps to Stubbs. Full ball outside leg stump and Stubbs slog sweeps to the fielder at deep midwicket
preText: So Harshit Rana's unavailability has forced Shreyas to look at his reserve bowlers.

wkt_text: RR Pant c SS Iyer b Varun 55 (39m 25b 4x4 5x6) SR: 220.00
text: this time Shreyas holds onto a catch off Varun's bowling! Tossed up ball, a bit wider outside off. Turning away and Pant also tries to go inside out over cover. Throws all his energy behind it but the shot is sliced and Shreyas at cover calls for that nice and early
preText: Pant is definitely limping. Knee issue maybe
postText: Shameer: "If selectors ever needed a justification to pick Pant for T20 world cup, he just provided one."

wkt_text: AR Patel c sub (MK Pandey) b Varun 0 (1m 1b 0x4 0x6) SR: 0.00
text: Manish Pandey joins the action now! Runs in from long on and takes a catch inside the circle that was swirling by diving forward. Varun enticed Axar with a tossed up ball just outside off and he went for the glory shot. Mistimed, very high in the air, and there was little doubt on Pandey's catching technique

shortText: Varun to Sumit Kumar, no run
text: loud appeal for lbw, but not given. Shreyas chats with Varun before reviewing. 50-50 shout from KKR's reactions. This was a full ball landing around middle and hitting his pad with the batter pressing forward. Turning way down leg, another review wasted.
comes over the wicket to the right-hander. Good length ball on middle, but turns down the leg side
preText: Varun on a hat-trick.

text: full ball just outside off. Sumit's eyes light up and he clatters a shot very hard, back past Varun to long off. Flew off the bat
half-tracker wider outside off but he can't put it away. Cut square to Rinku on the boundary line
full ball just outside off. Stubbs clears the front leg and wants to hit it over cow corner. But loses his shape, and hits the toe of the bat.
good length ball outside off. Stubbs stands tall, shuffles backwards, and then pummels a shot away from his body, and gets it over cover!
another one! Full ball on middle and leg. Turning into Stubbs, and he launches one over deep midwicket! That has gone 70m
Narine bowls flat and full, in fact it is a yorker. Stubbs does well to bring the bat down and dig it out

shortText: Narine to Sumit Kumar, no run
text: full ball, drifting and landing just outside off. Sharp turn into Sumit as he mistimes a defensive shot to the leg side

Narine gets hit for his third six of the over! Narine errs by bowling a half-tracker on off, which is also turning in, and Sumit needs no second invitation. Hangs back and muscles a strong pull over deep square leg
overpitched ball around off and he toe-ends a shot to long on for a single. Gets to fifty in 28 balls

shortText: Varun to Sumit Kumar, 1 leg bye
text: length ball angling into leg stump. Sumit tries to flick it off his hips but misses. Leg bye towards short fine leg
a quick ball darted into his toes, and Stubbs can't put the free-hit away
wild ball! Varun comes around the stumps and bowls an overpitched ball that angles across the right-hander and lands outside the pitch. Salt tries to dive to his right and stop it, but futile
full ball outside off and Stubbs plants his front leg right in front before swatting a drive over cover. Super followthrough on that shot, finishing with the bat behind his head

wkt_text: T Stubbs c Starc b Varun 54 (49m 32b 4x4 4x6) SR: 168.75
text: Stubbs' innings is over as he can't clear Starc at deep backward square leg. Varun bowls a quicker one that lands outside leg, and Stubbs doesn't get enough room for his hands to go through the bat swing. Taken well inside the boundary line

shortText: Varun to Rasikh Salam, no run
text: length ball around off and goes straight through. Salam misses the defense and the LBW appeal is turned down. KKR do not have a review

wkt_text: Sumit Kumar c sub (MK Pandey) b Narine 7 (12m 6b 0x4 1x6) SR: 116.66
text: To deep midwicket! Full ball on off and middle. Turning into Sumit. With only tailenders remaining, he goes for a big shot over the leg side, but does not have the distance on this occasion either. Time out
full ball on middle. Turning in and hits his front leg and he misses the straight drive. Turn meant it would miss leg stump so no appeal for lbw
full ball just outside off. Driven square to deep point for a single

shortText: Narine to Rasikh Salam, no run
text: full on middle and he gets low to sweep. Gloved onto his pad, before dribbling away to the leg side

shortText: Narine to Rasikh Salam, no run
text: full ball outside off and driven to cover
good length ball on middle, and hit straight for a single

wkt_text: Rasikh Salam c †Salt b Arora 1 (5m 5b 0x4 0x6) SR: 20.00
text: And Vaibhav gets a third! Goes for the tried-and-tested method of bouncer to a lower-order batter. Gets a shoulder-high ball to Rasikh outside off and he slices the pull to the wicketkeeper
preText: Vaibhav is back.

text: back of a length ball around off stump. Backs away to play it to the off side but can't get bat on ball
yorker length ball on off. Gets his toes out of the way before slapping a shot to the off side
short ball angling into his body, and hits Ishant's on the handle of the bat as he tries to take evasive action
short and wide. Nortje cuts it over short third. Narine runs around the boundary line from deep backward point, and manages to stop a four
short ball around off. Tries to pull but only finds air this time
slower ball bouncer on off. Nortje hangs back before hitting a tennis-style smash over his head. Mistimed but gets it over Vaibhav
fullish ball on off. Cutter from Russell. Nortje tries to hit it over midwicket but misses. Ball hoops over the stumps

wkt_text: A Nortje c SS Iyer b Russell 4 (9m 6b 0x4 0x6) SR: 66.66
text: length ball around off. Pulled but without much power, and taken by Shreyas on the leg side inside the circle! KKR win by 106 runs
postText:
That's time for us to say goodbye. Congratulations to KKR fans, commiserations for our friends rooting for Delhi Capitals, and if you're a fan of Indian cricket, there were plenty of positives to take home irrespective of which side you support. See you tomorrow for more IPL action. This is Sreshth saying bye on behalf of Sudeep, Chandan and Himanshu.

Sunil Narine, the Player of the Match, for his highest T20 score (85 in 39) and a wicket: "(Happier with batting or bowling?) Cricket is all about batting so looking to contribute more as a batter. That said, I still enjoy by bowling. (On the team joke that he does not attend batting meetings) I have one role and the less I know the better it is for me. (Batting lower down in Abu Dhabi Knight Riders) We had sufficient batters there so I wasn't needed. At the end of the day it is what the team needs. If they need me to bat, i will bat. (Plan with Salt) He is aggressive and gets the scoring going so all the pressure isn't on me. (As well as you've bowled?) On a wicket like that we wanted to win by a bigger margin so it helps later on in the tournament."

Winning captain Shreyas Iyer: "(Did you think about crossing 277?) No no, the way we started we thought 210-220, but 270 was icing on the cake. (Going hard in the powerplay - pre-planned?) As I said in the toss interview, Sunny is there to take on the bowlers, and if he cannot the rest of us should. That's the plan. (Raghuvanshi) He was fearless from ball one. His work ethic is phenomenal. He analyses situations well. He is a smart batter, shots were pleasing to the eye. (Bowling - Starc, Varun with wickets) Good to see bowlers stepping up and taking responsibility. They supported each other in their successes. We've been observing that last few games. (Harshit Rana OK?) Don't know. He was holding the shoulder. I know how he is feeling with shoulders. Will find out. (Vaibhav) The way he came back after conceding two overs early to take wickets. That is the character we need. (Three wins in three) You always have to be down to earth, especially in the IPL."

NEW: All the stats highlights from the KKR batting innings

Mitchell Starc, two wickets tonight: (What worked tonight?) Not changing too much. In T20s, you get some dropped chances and some edges and they don't go your way. But we are 3-0 and that's what it is all about. (Biggest price tag. Struggled with wickets early on) Nothing really as I said before. Games come thick and fast. It is T20 cricket, it can get brutal. You take a bit of luck here and there. We are 3-0, been clinical with the bat, so personal things aside, the team is going fantastic. Nice to have Marsh and Warner in the pocket. Another way win. (Vaibhav Arora and the short ball) That is all him. He was fantastic, using the short ball really well. We talk more in training and in bowling meetings. Just talking about that side of things. They may have questions, we have little conversations, certainly not me telling them what to do."

Mustafa Moudi : "85 with the Bat, A Wicket and excellent Economy Rate with the ball and a Catch as a Fielder. Narine has contributed in every department tonight !!"

Rishabh Pant, losing captain: Our bowlers were all over the place. We just didn't turn up on the day. Today was one of those days. As a batting unit, we only wanted to keep going hard as a team. I would rather get all out as a team than not go for the target. (Some reviews not taken) I think it was quite loud here. At the same time, couldn't see the timer on the screen. There was some problem on the screen. But there are some things you can control, some things you can't. (Use of Axar, only one over) See the thought process was that we didn't want to use spinners but our fast bowlers were going through the motions. I think it is time for reflections as an individual. We need to learn from these mistakes and come positive in the next match. (Pant's own body) Doing fine. Getting out there. Enjoying every day but cricket has its own ups and downs."

11.18pm So KKR win their first three games, of which two have been away from home! This 106-run win now also sends them to No. 1 on the points table.

There wasn't much pressure for their bowlers after the batters posted 272, and the seamers Starc and Arora very nearly ended the chase in the powerplay. From there on, the Capitals saved some blushes with Pant and Stubbs hitting two attractive half-centuries, but Varun and Narine closed the deal swiftly thereafter. KKR win comfortably after posing the second-highest score in IPL history, stopped from breaking the record only courtesy a terrific Ishant Sharma 20th over in the first innings.

shortText: Harpreet Brar to Saha, no run
text: Stops a bit in the pitch. Might be a good call to start with spin. Tad short of length, given some air, Saha checked the back-foot punch to the bowler
preText:
7:27pm Umpires Vineet Kulkarni and Nitin menon walk out. Gill and Saha are the regulars who will open. Surprise first up from Kings - Harpreet Brar will open the bowling. Not Arshdeep. Around the wicket

Arun: "IPL should think of providing a bonus point for teams who doesnt use impact-sub :) What do you think ?" Not sure how popular it'd be given the rule came in just last year. Plus bonus points aren't a thing. Maybe if the league needs a shake-up at some point they might do it. Guessing not soon though

Usayd: "longtime suffering supporter of Punjab *cries in my pillowsGoing by recent form - the last few seasons - Punjab is scheduled to win today's match - they normally win and lose in equal amounts...now if I was a betting man - I would be a millionaire.... "

Ashish: "I don't think this is a chasing IPL. Teams should bat first after winning toss and put a score to defend."

Jayant Isswani: "The team batting first always has an option to include only 3 overseas players. The fourth one can come based on conditions. For eg here GT should have included Mohit instead of Noor and then included either Noor or Spencer or Little based on conditions!"

Murtuza: "Why are overseas players listed as possible impact players when a team picks 4 overseas at the start of the match? Surely that means only indian players can be used as impact players, isnt it?" They can field though

Bill: "If Prabh and Arsh are both playing, who will Punjab sub in? I'm hoping for Harpreet Bhatia or maybe Rishi Dhawan if Arsh bowls his 4 early on. Also, playing without Chahar is a 1st for Punjab" Harpreet and Rishi aren't on the subs list. Ashutosh Sharma might come in. But yeah, as Cricfan mentions it seems like a batting XI

GT Impact Players list: BR Sharath, Mohit Sharma, Sandeep Warrier, Abhinav Manohar, Manav Suthar

Gujarat Titans: 1 Shubman Gill (capt), 2 Wriddhiman Saha (wk), 3 Sai Sudharsan, 4 Kane Williamson, 5 Vijay Shankar, 6 Azmatullah Omarzai, 7 Rahul Tewatia, 8 Rashid Khan, 9 Noor Ahmad, 10 Umesh Yadav, 11 Darshan Nalkande

PBKS Impact Players list: Tanay Thyagarajan, Nathan Ellis, Asutosh Sharma, Rahul Chahar, Vidwath Kaverappa

Punjab Kings: 1 Shikhar Dhawan (capt), 2 Jonny Bairstow (wk), 3 Prabhsimran Singh, 4 Sam Curran, 5 Jitesh Sharma (wk),, 6 Shashank Singh, 7 Sikandar Raza, 8 Harpreet Brar, 9 Harshal Patel, 10 Kagiso Rabada, 11 Arshdeep Singh

Gill: Would've bowled, it's a good wicket. Hopefully it's going to be an exciting contest. We've started pretty well. Got couple games on the road after this. Last year we did well. Miller misses out due to a niggle, Kane comes in

Dhawan: It's a good wicket, think it'll stay the same. Hence the call. Few games, the score has gone up but doesn't mean it will be like that every game given all teams are very good. We're playing decent cricket, need ten percent improvement. It's early, got lots of learnings, need to implement them. Livi goes out due to injury, Raza comes in.

7pm Shubman Gill and Shikhar Dhawan are out, both in good spirits too. Gill has the coin, tails is the call. It's tails, Punjab will bowl first

Pitch: Square boundaries are 63 metres each. Fine ones are shorter - 55 and 56 metres. Long ones are on the other side - 68 to 70 metres. Simon Katich says it's pitch 6, was used four times last game including the final. Three were won by the chasing team. It has a mix of black and red soil, so it's rock hard. Got 3 millimetres of grass on it, so there'll be a bit of pace and bounce but also runs for batters. GT have won 8 out of 12 games, so Kings will have a tough challenge. From the sounds of it, my guess is that chasing would be the better. Let's see what the captains think at the toss. Scheduled for 7pm local as always.

dsk: "One of the battles to watch out for is the GT's packed Middle order with left handers v Brar and ChaharWoudnlt be easy task for Dhawan this!"

Mustafa Moudi : "Exactly around this time last year, Shikhar Dhawan said if he would be the selector, he would choose Gill over himself as the Indian Opener for the World Cup. And within a year Gill has an Orange Cap and now also became the Captain. Really Excited for the battle between the Former Indian Opener vs the Current Indian Opener !!"

6:40pm The sky's blue in Ahmedabad but probably not for long. People are peppering in across the stands. The ring-lights on top are on. Practice is going in full flow. The pitch, as the preview mentioned, might be one of red soil. We'll know more about that and the teams soon. If it does have some zip, GT might think of bringing in Spencer Johnson, who looked like a million bucks in the BBL but didn't start as well here. Of course after Mayank Yadav's bursts, raw pace might be worth a try. Kings' spin, actually the home bowlers in general, need to step up. Jitesh Sharma, in his pre-match interview on the IPL website, has in fact all but confirmed Liam Livingstone won't play due to an injury tonight. Shoutout to Matt Roller for digging it out.

Cricfan: "Punjab has options, and they should definitely get Rilee Rossouw in. Of all the teams that are not performing well currently, only RCB seems to not have too many options. An RCB fan here !! "

Deivarayan Muthu's Match Preview - Gill's Titans look to make it three in three at home

6:30pm: Isn't it nice to be in a routine? It's what the IPL, along many T20 leagues offer. Something to comfort-watch on a weekday that's beyond what an algorithm recommends. (Recommended reading on the topic from three years ago). And today can be about breaking free from set formats for Punjab Kings, who might bring in Sikandar Raza in place of Liam Livingstone if he is unfit. They might, as Mitch McClenaghan mentioned, go with Rile Rossouw to strengthen their batting. For the hosts Gujarat Titans, it's mostly go-with-the-flow stuff. They're in a groove, have a balanced side, may want Rashid to get more consistent but he's easing back in to top-level cricket. So no alarm bells for now.

Amit: "Out of 120 balls, your opening batsman and also the best batter in the team only faces 40 percent of deliveries. It's criminal by GT." Wouldn't go that far given there was assistance for the bowlers early on. But he did make the most of what was available.

Kane Williamson: Nice to be out there after long. Shame to lose Davey (Miller) for a week or two. Reasonably competitive total. Hope to do well in the second half. There was a bit there with the new ball, had to wait for the sideways movement to come off and make use of the good wicket, which it was. Great start to captaincy from Gill. Led from the front, will keep growing as time goes on. There's isn't any dew at the moment which is good. We are playing two spinners. A bit of bounce and hold, so hope they'll be effective. Should be good if bowlers hit the right areas.

9:14pm Gill, Titans' captain, bats through and has given his side a great chance. It was a buffet, nay, a Thali of strokeplay, powerhitting, placement, everything you want. That down-the-ground six to a Rabada length ball is a highlight. He got going in the powerplay. Saha tried too but couldn't. Arshdeep, Rabada got great bounce and a bit of sideways which Williamson tried to negate. It slowed them down a bit. He fell to Brar while trying to up the ante. Sudharsan joined Gill and did that though, in a 53-run stand. Kings tried to hold their own but conceded big overs every now and again. Vijay Shankar coming above Tewatia gave them some wiggleroom but Gill was still doing his Superman thing. Tewatia did eventually come in and bash a few.

postText:
Shashank's heroics made sure that our heart rates went up towards the end. And so the points table wears an exciting look with both Titans and Kings in the middle. That's all from us for tonight. Do join us tomorrow as well, when CSK take on SRH. Till then, take care! Ciao!

11:30pm Time for the presentation

Shikhar Dhawan Kings captain: "It was an amazing game. Very, very close. Boys did the job. Plan was to give a good start, but I got out early. We lost a few wickets early and Shashank came and played a tremendous knock. When you are chasing a big total, you have to keep the momentum going. Shashank showed his class. Magnificent knock. He timed the ball so nicely, it looked effortless. He kept his cool and finished the game. He started from No. 7 and is now showing his positive mindset. Ashutosh also came in and took the game well. The two young boys were keeping their calm and soaking the pressure."

Shashank Singh, Player of the Match: "Still trying to sink in. Visualised all these things, but when it turned into reality, proud of the effort. Coach told me to react to the ball. The wicket is very good, the bounce was good. 200 scored by both teams, so the wicket was fantastic. They are the legends of the game, but when I go to bat I think I am the best. You get experience, couldn't get a lot of matches before. Here the owners and coaching staff backed me. I was very confident."

11:14pm What drama! Kings finally stall their losing run, and it is the second-highest successful chase against Titans in the IPL. Kings steadily lost wickets at the start but what they did not fail to do was keep up with the asking rate. Prabhsimran and Bairstow first, Jitesh a bit, and then Shashank and Ashutosh at the end kept the hits coming and helped the side hunt down the 200-run target. What a platform the IPL is for these unheralded players. Two of them shine and take their team across the line. Did Titans miss a trick but not bringing in the sixth bowler earlier? Should they have promoted Omarzai with the bat, perhaps ahead of Vijay? Lots to dissect for them.

Shubman Gill, Titans captain, gives Mohit Sharma the Purple Cap: "Couple of catches went down. Never easy on a wicket like this when you drop catches. Difficult to defend runs in these conditions. The new ball was doing something. There are always areas to improve. I think 200 was good enough. We were in the game till the 15th over. When you drop catches, you will be in trouble. The way Nalkande bowled in the last match, we went to him for the last over. This is IPL for you - people who you have not seen will come and win games."

Ashutosh Sharma: "I would like to thank Punjab Kings for believing in me. Happy that our team has won. Personal performance happens, but main thing is for the team to win. [Mindset] Shikhar [Dhawan] has told me a lot of things mentally. I was like 'I will do it'. I have won games for my team, so I had the belief. Sanjay Bangar also believed in me, he spoke to me a lot during camps, and that helped. Back home, I had worked with Amay Khurasiya, my coach. He said you will do well when you get the chance."

preText:
7.29pm Righto, here we go. Out come the two CSK openers, Ruturaj Gaikwad and Rachin Ravindra. And, oh hello, it will be the left-arm spin of Abhishek Sharma with the new ball. Long-on and deep midwicket is out. A slip in place too.

7.25pm Not long before the start of the game. In the mean time, how about some light reading. Here's Sidharth Monga on how CSK put opposites together to become an IPL batting behemoth. Hemant Brar meanwhile writes about the Impact Player and and which team has made the best use.

Naren: "It might be a stretch but SRH is playing with 6 all rounders(Nitish, Abhishek, Markram, Klaasen, Shahbaz, Pat) and possibly 7 with head. Options gallore"

Aditya: "Ardent CSK supporter here. 2 of our best death bowlers are gone and we're defending on this belter. Seems like the game is over before it even started!"

Kumar : "Excited to see a local player finally playing for SRH. Go Nitish "

7.20pm So, Travis Head is likely to come in for Unadkat in the second innings and CSK are likely to bring in Mukesh Choudhary for one their batters. Mitchell? Possibly. Must admit CSK's bowling looks weak without Pathirana and Mustafizur, especially their fast bowling stocks. Jadeja, Moeen and Theekshana might have to do a lot of the heavy lifting.

Kawal: "Who is Mukesh in CSK? is that a typo?" Mukesh Choudhary, forgotten about him? Cleaned up Ishan Kishan with a jaffa of an inswinger in one of the previous IPL seasons.

Playing XIs

SRH: 1 Nitish Kumar Reddy, 2 Abhishek Sharma, 3 Aiden Markram, 4 Heinrich Klaasen (wk), 5 Abdul Samad, 6 Shahbaz Ahmed, 7 Pat Cummins (capt), 8 Bhuvneshwar Kumar, 9 Jaydev Unadkat, 10 Mayank Markande, 11 T Natarajan

Subs: Umran Malik, Washington Sundar, Travis Head, Glenn Phillips, Rahul Tripathi

Chennai Super Kings: 1 Ruturaj Gaikwad (capt), 2 Rachin Ravindra, 3 Ajinkya Rahane, 4 Moeen Ali, 5 Daryl Mitchell, 6 Shivam Dube, 7 Ravindra Jadeja, 8 MS Dhoni (wk), 9 Deepak Chahar, 10 Tushar Deshpande, 11 Maheesh Theekshana

Subs: Mukesh Choudhary, Shardul Thakur, Shaik Rasheed, Mitchell Santner, Sameer Rizvi

Toss: Pat Cummins has won the toss and SRH will bowl. Two changes for them. Mayank Agarwal is not feeling well says Cummins so Nitish will play. Natarajan is also back from injury. For CSK, there are three changes. Mustafizur is not around, and Pathirana also has a niggle says Gaikwad. Moeen Ali, Maheesh Theekshana and Mukesh Choudhary come into the side.

Pat Cummins: Few games, still trying to get my head around the impact player. Consistency is the key. Mayank is feeling unwell and Nitish is in. Nattu is back from injury. It looks like a good wicket.

Huge cheers for Ruturaj Gaikwad. Home crowd anyone? "So far so good, last game we were close," he says. "Everyone is in good head space. For me, I have done captaincy, nothing new for me. I just want to be myself and just take thing forward. Fizz is absent, Pathirana has slight niggle as well. Mo comes in Theekshana comes in and Mukesh comes in. Big miss for us [Fizz]. The bowlers are rearing to go regardless.

Not long before the toss

Pitch report: One side is slightly bigger than the other - both square boundaries are 70m and the straight boundary is longer, says Samuel Badree. It's a different surface to the 277 game, says Lara. "More visible cracks but that won't make a difference," he says. "The captain should bat first and put a big total. If you get 200 here, you should think you have done well. Pace on the ball will help earlier but it is a flat track and batters should do well."

Vineeth Nalluri: "Since Fizz isn't available, I would bring Santner in his place and replace Rizvi with Shardul."

Mustafa Moudi : "Unpopular Opinion: Reaching 270s twice within a week is too boring. T20 is slowly turning into a Baseball, i.e. Six Hitting Competition. This is just increasing Batsman personal records and Bowlers Economy with their fault. We need a proper contest between the bat and the ball !!"

6.50pm Dhoni has just walked out on to the park and Uppal has gone berserk. Absolute bedlam in the stands. Just what the sighting of one man can do. He's warming up with some light football. while Cummins is doing some batting practice. He'll hope he is not needed today. For all the euphoria, this game is crucial for both sides, who are coming off a loss. SRH went down to Gujarat Titans by seven wickets, and have won just one game out of three. CSK after winning their first two games, lost to Capitals by 20 runs despite Dhoni's whirlwind knock. They will want to get back to winning ways. As far as the head to head is concerned, CSK are firm favourites having won 14 out of 19 games played between the two sides. They, however, will be without their spearhead Mustafizur Rahman for this game.

Here's Travis Head talking to Harsha Bhogle on air: [Any orange around?] Scattered a little bit. I have heard things about Chennai. If Dhoni walks down now, I might lose you. [277 surface] The wicket was nice, we are making sure we start well ,give ourselves the best chance. Hopefully we can get off to a good start. [Going after his shots] It is situational. I am always giving myself a chance. My technique is of a three-format player. I try to use my experience. [Coming to Hyderabad] Have been here a couple of times in the last 12 months, and have done well, so hope to do better. [Surface] I had a look at the surface a couple of days out it looks quite good. Try to come in with plans, assess the conditions, is it swinging, is it not. We tried to do that a couple of days ago and will try to make the right decisions. [Score 277 again?] Tough game to follow. We need to have the same intent, and give ourselves the best chance.

6.40pm Sixes flew, records broke, the balls went out shape the last time an IPL game took place in Hyderabad. SRH amassed 277, the highest-ever score in the history of IPL, while Mumbai Indians were not far off in their chase reaching 246. So, what's in store today? More of the same according to Shashank Kishore in his preview. For SRH, Abhishek Sharma has set the tempo at the top and Travis Head has already shown how dangerous he can be in that game against Mumbai . Then there's Aiden Markram and Heinrich Klaasen in unbelievable six-hitting form. CSK too have a prolific six-hitter in Shivam Dube, who has struck at 177.09 against spin since last year's IPL while they also see Daryl Mitchell warming up to a similar role. And then, of course, there is Thala, who blazed away to an unbeaten 16-ball 37 in his last game against DC. We might be in for an epic clash tonight.

6.30pm IPL S17E18. Hello, and welcome to the ball-by-ball commentary of match no. 18 between Sunrisers Hyderabad and Chennai Super Kings in Hyderabad. It is a home game for SRH, but does that really matter when CSK are in town. There is a sea of yellow at the stadium in Uppal, 80% yellow, and let's give a generous 20% to orange. I am Ashish Pant and will soon be joined by S Sudarshanan as we bring to all the updates from the all important SRH-CSK clash.

9.12pm At a venue where more than 500 runs were scored, records broken for run, CSK have huffed and puffed to 165 for 5. But, mind you this is a very different surface to the one that was laid out in the earlier game. Barring Shivam Dube, who hammered 45 off 24, no batter really got going. The SRH bowlers were meticulous with their strategies. They took the pace off and didn't give CSK anything to work with. Can SRH batters chase this down? Join Sudarshanan in a bit to find out.

Mujahid : "Fantastic bowling performance by SRH,now to show up some good baiting skills."

Here's Jaydev Unadkat: Not a lot of difference from the surface last time. But we kept hitting the lengths. Having a fast bowing captain helps. That is a strong point. It was one of those days where we kept hitting the lengths. [Chase] It is about getting the momentum in the beginning. If we get the powerplay right, we will be able to get that score.

text: Swings it in from outside off, from a fuller length, Chahar. Head gets nicely forward and drives it to cover
preText:

Mukesh Choudhary is the Impact Sub for CSK, coming in for Dube. Travis Head, Impact Sub for Natarajan, has walked out to open with Abhishek Sharma.

9:22pm Welcome back! We have an interesting chase in our hands. Sunrisers bowled only four overs of spin in their innings, and they went at close to ten an over. Yet, the off pace deliveries from the fast bowlers were hard to hit. What route will CSK take? Dhoni was a master at operating with spinners. CSK have at least 12 overs of spin to turn to, if needed.

text: Edged and gone down! How many times has Head been dropped early in his innings! Chahar is not happy. A perfect plan, outswinger following one that moved in previous ball. shortText: Mukesh Choudhary to Abhishek Sharma, SIX
text: Poor ball, superb shot. Choudhary digs it short but angles it down leg. Abhishek swivels and deposits it wayyyy over fine leg

text: Gift, gleefully accepted! Full toss just outside off, Abhishek gets under it and tonks it over long-off. Free hit? What's that?

shortText: Mukesh Choudhary to Abhishek Sharma, (no ball) SIX
text: Whipped away in some style. Flair, elegance and timing all aplenty. Choudhary bowls it full on the pads, 139.2kph, Abhishek flicks it well over deep midwicket. And the bowler has overstepped, to make matters worse for CSK

text: Twenty seven of the over! Proper slot ball, outside off. Allows the width for Abhishek to free his arms. He does with a forward-stride and hits it over extra cover

Jadeja runs to his right from backward point takes it reverse-cupped with a dive. Chahar exults

SRH have scored 73 between the 7th and the 17th over. CSK managed 81 in the same period, George Binoy tells me. So SRH have been slower in the period but they were top notch in the powerplay, which puts them ahead in the game right now. Here's Deshpande

preText: Chahar
postText:
CSK still manage to stay on third, while SRH rise to fifth. As many as five teams are in the middle with four points. Who will break out of the mid-table logjam first? Tomorrow, RCB have a chance to join the middle with four points, while RR have a chance to go clear on the top. Do join us tomorrow for an exciting clash. Till the next time, take care, aficionados! Ciao.

11:05pm Time for the presentation

Pat Cummins, SRH captain: "Different soil, slowed up as the game went on. Stil a fantastic game. We have got plenty of fast bowlers. Shivam was hitting the spinners. So we took a chance with the fast bowlers bowling cutters. [Abhishek Sharma] I would not be wanting to be bowling to him. The crowd is crazy tonight, especially when MS walked out. We love playing here, home conditions."

Abhishek Sharma, Player of the Match: "In the bowling we felt it was a slow wicket. So we wanted to take the powerplay on. We had a chance to prepare well before the IPL. We knew it will be slow but not if we take on the bowler. Because it would be difficult for the bowler as well. Big scores matter, but I went with the flow today. Hopefully I will get out last next time. It is all the hardwork i have put before this. Special thanks to my dad, Yuvi paaji and Brian Lara."

10:49pm One-way traffic in Hyderabad tonight. But CSK did not leave it without a fight. Given the start SRH had, they could have well romped home earlier. Head and Abhishek are turning out to be some pairing. They never let the opposition in, unless they commit a mistake. Tonight was also something similar. Head was offered a life in the first over and then CSK were senton a leather hunt. SRH romped to 78 for 1 in the powerplay in the chase. And you almost knew that was the game.

Ruturaj Gaikwad, CSK captain: "It was a slow pitch. At the back end they bowled well. We couldn't capitalise in the last five overs. We were in a good situation halfway but they bowled well at the back. Black soil pitch, so we expected the slowness. As the ball got older, it got slower. They used the conditions well - big boundary one end. We did not bowl well in the powerplay but did well to drag the game. 170-175 is par, if we would have had a good powerplay with the ball, we could have had the game. There was slight dew at the later stage. Moeen was spinning the ball in the 15th-16th over, so not much of a difference."

Aiden Markram: "Not too bad, but not like it was against Mumbai. When we bowled, the first ten overs or so, it was coming on alright but got tougher. So we took on in the first ten and were in a good position later. I don't want to think too much, probably see-ball, hit-ball. That is encouraged by the team management and Patty [Pat Cummins]. When you get in, the batter that is in needs to value the position. The Impact Player has freed batters."

Rajkumar Lingav: "Klassen finishes without hitting a Six!!! "

Nishant: "SRH wasted a great opportunity to improve their NRR. The middle period they went into a shell unnecessarily! No RR pressure, no wickets pressure " Wasn't a very easy surface to hit through and through, and that reflected.

7:26pm Kohli and du Plessis are ready. They await the umpires - Alex Wharf and Tapan Sharma - to walk out. RR's players get into a huddle and then make their way out. Their darkish pink kit looks great.

Virat: "Strange tactics from RCB. They could have selected in form Lomor in the the playing XI and later replace him with Vyshak.. Not sure what is the thinking.."

Shrikant : "What is Pink Promise?" A social initiative by RR. There are details about it on their website

RCB Impact Subs: Suyash Prabhudessai, Mahipal Lomror, Himanshu Sharma, Vijaykumar Vyshak, Swapnil Singh

RCB:1 Virat Kohli, 2 Faf du Plessis (capt), 3 Rajat Patidar, 4 Glenn Maxwell, 5 Cameron Green, 6 Dinesh Karthik (wk), 7 Saurav Chauhan, 8 Reece Topley, 9 Mayank Dagar, 10 Mohammed Siraj, 11 Yash Dayal.

RR Impact Subs: Rovman Powell, Tanush Kotian, Kuldeep Sen, Shubham Dube, Abid Mushtaq

RR 1 Yashasvi Jaiswal, 2 Jos Buttler, 3 Sanju Samson (capt & wk), 4 Riyan Parag, 5 Dhruv Jurel, 6 Shimron Hetmyer, 7 R Ashwin, 8 Trent Boult, 9 Avesh Khan, 10 Nandre Burger, 11 Yuzvendra Chahal

Faf was thinking he'd have bowled but not fully sure. We've got one change to give some impetus to our batting. I feel we haven't played at our best. It's a case of trusting guys and it's a matter of time before things click. We've been inconsistent and hope to improve tonight. It's important for guys to give roles they feel is their strongest entry point. It's not worked out yet but it's not due to positions. Saurav Chauhan is coming in, exciting talent. Looking at him play he's got serious hitting ability, beautiful bat swing and astonishing power.

Samson says it's to do with current conditions. It's a fresh wicket and there could be dew. Expecting help for our seamers at the start. Happy people are taking responsibility. We have a lot of match-winners but not all are going to come off everyday. But when time comes try to make sure it does happen. No changes in our team, Sandeep continues to be unavailable

7pm It's an all-pink day for RR, it's part of a campaign named Pink Promise. Sanju Samson has the coin, Faf du Plessis calls heads. It's tails, RR win the toss and will bowl

Pitch: The ground has a few big boundaries - 73 to 76 metres from long-on to long-off on side. 57-to-60-metre ones on the other side are short. Square ones are 63 and 69 metres far. WV Raman says it's a hard pitch, has grass, is well prepared. Batters will make runs. It offers more turn for spinners than other grounds. There is a bit of patchy grass which will help them along with the big boundaries. It's an open ground, so dew might not be a big issue.

Match Preview: RCB searching for answers against in-form hosts

Murtuza : "Good evening Eknath, looking forward to your commentary. The impact player rule is not giving enough practice to all rounders, especially in case of finding more of them for the Indian team. For eg. If Shivam Dube is selected and expected to bowl, it will be harsh on him as he has not been given a chance to do that in this tournament. I would like to know your thoughts on it. " Hey, I do agree, but I don't think it's been a net negative to the quality of play overall.

6:40pm The floodlights are on and RR's huddle was full of energy. Unlike RCB they are getting things to click together, be it by promoting R Ashwin or Boulting out MI ,in an away game, which has been next to impossible or with Riyan Parag firing. Talk about trusting a player to the hilt. They're great while batting first and it'd be fun to see how they'll chase when it goes tight. Let's see if that happens tonight.

CricDude: "If Will Jacks is in, him and Maxwell can cover spin. They are more than capable. Somehow getting the right 4 overseas combination is tough with some of them not in form. My RCB XII: Jacks*, Virat, Faf*, Lomror, Maxi*, Green*, Manoj, DK, Vyshak, Siraj, Yash. IP - Patidar/Akashdeep. Lots of allrounders and bowling options plus this bats deep."

6:30pm: It's time for RCB to go pink. Home hasn't been kind to them and Rajasthan Royals are trying to re-establish Jaipur as their fortress but going back on the road could be the welcome change the visitors need, especially their big-name batters Faf du Plessis, Glenn Maxwell, and Cameron Green. They have Karn Sharma and Maxwell in the ranks but aren't strong in the spin department. Alzarri Joseph, their fast-bowling big buy, got pumped. But Reece Topley brings height and the left-armer's angle with him. Can things click together, which seems to be the only mode in which RCB can thrive this season?

George: "For all the selective comments being published with regards to Kohli's striking and Faf's slowdown, to put it into perspective, both are scoring at nearly the same rate. Pls be fair in your assessment of both the openers." Fair point. Faf's tried going big and failed. Kohli's slowdown seemed intentional. It opens that anchor debate again

Datta: "Is the pitch not very conducive to scoring? I can't think of any other reason why they have two anchors now" Spinners are getting turn and variable bounce. Won't be easy to put away cutters from the quicks either. Not a pitch for new batters to get going right away. Having said all that, Faf has struggled and Kohli had a slow phase late in and just after the powerplay

Maxwell, Green come out with Neil McKenzie

His off-day might be a big issue for the day but might be a bigger worry big-picture wise

Kohli on 98*

shortText: Avesh Khan to Kohli, no run

Wide low full toss, slapped to long-off

postText:
9:11pm 183 - It's roughly around par but are they short though? Okay, three minutes and the Kohli chat later, one thing's clear - conditions can't not be factored in. As he said, they had to hit straight and couldn't get under balls. Faf tried pretty much everything but couldn't shake it off. Kohli had a great start to the powerplay. Ashwin coming in slowed things down. He and Chahal were excellent. They used the lack of bounce well and the pace, which wasn't true all the time. The openers then consolidated for a while, put on 125. RCB promoted Maxwell and Chauhan but couldn't get much. Kohli though, was like a motivated bike rider in Bangalore traffic. Knew which gullies to go through and where to accelerate. It might not be enough but he's given them a chance.

Virat Kohli: The wicket looks different from up there when you're not playing the ball yourself. It seems flat. But when you see the ball holding up in the pitch, especially against the spinners you see pace is changing quickly. Big dimensions come into play. Our initial target was 195 but then we decided if one of me or Faf got out one had to bat till the end. We got a boost and got 185, which I feel this is an effective total. If we get the change of pace and lengths right, it will be a tough chase. I'm not coming in with premeditation. I was 12 off 10, I don't want to be over-aggressive, want to keep the bowler guessing. They want me to go hard and get me out. It's just experience and maturity. I play the conditions and have the game ready. Doesn't seem there's dew hope it's the same. Balls didn't come on to bad, felt you couldn't get under bat.

Durvank: "In days of 200s, 183 seems little short..."

text: length ball, straightens a touch towards off stump, defended back to the bowler
preText: 9.22pm Here we go then. Royals need 184 to make it four out of four for the season. Out walk Yashasvi Jaiswal and Jos Buttler. Would be the perfect time for either or both to get back among the runs. RCB have brought in the legspinner Himanshu Sharma as their Impact substitute. He comes in for Saurav Chauhan. Reece Topley has the new ball. Left-arm over with a slip in place for Jaiswal.

wkt_text: YBK Jaiswal c Maxwell b Topley 0 (1m 2b 0x4 0x6) SR: 0.00

Gets it to bounce awkwardly as Jaiswal looks to drag a pull from well outside his body, and ends up skewing a top-edge high in the air for Glenn Maxwell to get under at mid-off. Just the start RCB wanted
back of a length, slanting across and straightening slightly to tuck Samson up as he looks to punch into the covers. Thick inside edge past his leg stump

preText: Left-armers from both ends. Here's Yash Dayal. Over the wicket, slip in place.

shortText: Yash Dayal to Samson, no run

shortText: Yash Dayal to Samson, no run

full, swinging into Buttler's feet, clipped to deep square leg

fullish, a hint of swing in towards middle and off, and Samson meets it with the perfect straight drive. Small stride to the ball, gets his head over it, and presents the full face to punch it between the non-striker and the stumps

text: length ball on off stump, defended into the covers

a touch short again, and Buttler picks up four more. These errors in length get hidden sometimes when they happen outside the powerplay, but with cover point inside the circle rather than sweeping on the boundary, there's no margin for error
20 off the over. Buttler ends the powerplay with a double, a full ball driven to the left of long-off

Four more, and Royals are heaping the pressure on Dagar. Century partnership comes up now. Drops short, and Samson swivels fiercely into a pull to beat deep backward square leg to his left
and he sends down a half-volley that Buttler dispatches ruthlessly. Gets his left foot out of the way and launches it straight back over the bowler's head
