preText: Two to get. Single and six to get the century?

text: and he ends it with a six!!!! Shortish, into the body, and it wasn't his most sweetly hit pull, but it was sweet enough, landing just outside the boundary to the left of the man at deep square leg. Utter delight for Butter, who David-Warneresque bat-stabbing leap after yanking his helmet off. Hetmyer celebrated just as hard too. Royals have begun the season with four wins in a row.
preText: Buttler is on strike as Green comes on to bowl the last over. One to win, six to bring up the hundred.
postText:
11.32pm Superb performance from Royals who've begun this season with an absolute bang. Four games, four wins, but they know from recent memory that a good beginning is no guarantee of going deep into the IPL. As for RCB, well, lots of problems to dwell on and sort out. Before that, though, we have a tasty double-header coming up tomorrow: MI vs DC first up, and then LSG vs GT. Two potential crackers, so do be there to follow all the action on your favourite website. Until then, good night!

Jos Buttler, Player of the Match: "A little bit of luck to get it over the rope in the end, didn't time it that well, but delighted to get the win. However long you've played the game, you still have those anxieties and stresses. Sometimes you just have to tell yourself it'll be okay. Just keep digging in, working hard, at some point we will be okay. I actually did feel really good in the last game, even though I only scored 13 or something. We've started this season really well. We've been together for three seasons, everyone's comfortable with each other, we just need to keep this momentum going."

Sanju Samson: "I think anything below 190, with a little bit of dew coming in, with the batting order we have, I felt it was a good total to chase. Touchwood, few more games to go, we are bowling well. And we have got a break, which is helping us charge up and come in fresh. [Are RR a batting or bowling side?] I think bowling is 9, and batting is 8.7. It was just a matter of time with Jos. He just needed to get through the powerplay and middle a few balls."

Kumar Sangakkara: "I thought it was a good toss to win, we were pretty decisive in wanting to chase. RCB started well, but Nandre Burger brought us back with the spinners, and Jos and Sanju were clinical. Everyone requires a chat, but the chat doesn't have to be about cricket or technique or anything like that. Jos is the best white-ball opener in the world, and all he needed to do was sit back and ignore some of the noise. [On Jaiswal:] We know the quality that Jaiswal brings to the side, we just want him to relax and bat, and bat long. He just needs to calm down a little bit, rest up."

Faf du Plessis: "I think batting out there with Virat, we found the wicket really tricky and low. We did feel 190 would be a good score. I did feel we could have maximised 10 or 15 more towards the end. It was a good toss to win, you did see that it played much nicer with the dew. Virat was playing really well at the back end. Whether it was Virat or a Greeny or a DK coming in, we could have scored a few more. We tried, but it was quite tricky to hit. With the spinners, a lot of balls were hitting the bottom of the bat. I think the pitch definitely got better. That's what dew does, that's the nature of the wicket. I thought it was a good toss for them to win. We started well in the first four overs, then the one over from our spinners, 20 runs, it shifted the pressure back onto us. Maxwell, all the right-handers batting in the middle, that's why I went to the left-arm spinner, Mayank, who's been bowling well for us this season. And the legspinner [Himanshu], you want to use the attacking option. When we got the wicket of Jaiswal, with the two right-handers in the middle, it didn't feel like the right time to use the offspinner."

11.08pm Terrific win for the Royals. It seems like a long time ago, but RCB began brilliantly with the bat before the Royals spinners began turning things around to restrict them to 183. It didn't feel like enough then, despite what Virat Kohli said about the conditions, particularly with all the doubts over RCB's bowling quality. Royals did it easily in the end, with a brilliant century from a back-among-the-runs Jos Buttler, and a superb 69 from Sanju Samson.

text: On a length on off stump with a hint of nibble in, Rohit defends
preText:
Khaleel Ahmed with the new ball. He is over the wicket, two slips in place

Piyush Chawla: Whenever you go or a match, there is a positive mind frame especially in Wankhede where there are so many fans. We have lost the first three games, but we have to forget that. There are 11 matches left. Our team has what it takes to get back. Today's match is very important and we need to get two points on the board. [Bowling at Wankhede a problem?] Don't think so. As a bowler, you need to know your strengths and I back that.

Vinod Rajpal: "I am now at Wankhede, every time I watch live at the venue, Mumbai Indians lose the match....hope today it is reversed !"

Pitch report from Simon Katich and Pommie Mbangwa: The outfield is brilliant in terms of being manicured. Not too difficult to get to the boundary. The square boundaries are 62 and 63 m. Straight boundary is 74m. Pitch is rock hard, same pitch as was used against Rajasthan. Today is red hot, feels very warm. Little bit of grass, but expect runs. The numbers indicate that spin has gone for less runs. However, it is a small ground so it will be risky to bowl a lot of spinners.

3.20pm The big news from the toss is that Suryakumar Yadav is back and he will hope his return helps Mumbai get back to winning ways too. No Nuwan Thushara as yet, but Nabi is back, and so is Romario Shepherd. For Delhi, Richardson is back but without Marsh, the top order might have to do the heavy lifting once more.

Meanwhile, there's a big hockey match going on between India and Australia right now. After India's loss yesterday, they seem to have bounced back with more aggression and intent today, leading at the break. Follow the second half live.

Afeef: "Jhye Richardson was bought by MI last season but he missed the entire season. Now he's gonna play against MI at their home ground."

Ashutosh Malasi: "Where is Kuldeep yadav ? Why he is not playing ? " He has a groin injury.

Playing XIs

Delhi Capitals: 1 Prithvi Shaw, 2 David Warner, 3 Abhishek Porel, 4 Rishabh Pant (wk and capt), 5 Tristan Stubbs, 6 Axar Patel, 7 Lalit Yadav, 8 Jhye Richardson, 9 Anrich Nortje, 10 Ishant Sharma 11 Khaleel Ahmed

Subs: Kumar Kushagra, Yash Dhull, Jake Fraser-McGurk, Sumit Kumar, Pravin Dubey

Mumbai Indians: 1 Rohit Sharma, 2 Ishan Kishan, 3 Suryakumar Yadav, 4 Tilak Varma, 5 Hardik Pandya (capt), 6 Tim David, 7 Mohammad Nabi, 8 Romario Shepherd, 9 Piyush Chawla, 10 Gerald Coetzee, 11 Jasprit Bumrah

Subs: Akash Madhwal, Kwena Maphaka, Naman Dhir, Nehal Wadhera, Shams Mulani

3.00pm Toss: Heads is the call from Pant and Delhi Capitals are bowling first. Changes across both teams.

Rishabh Pant: Here you can chase any target and we would like to see that. We have to stick together as a team, and if we can do that we can come out winners. Happy to be back. Every match gives me immsense confidence and as a cricketer, I am improving. In cricket, it is hard for the bowlers, but this is the job they chose. Marsh is injured, Richardson is in and Lalit comes in for Rasikh.

Hardik Pandya: This looks much more drier and it will be good to bat. The track looks fantastic and properly rolled. The moisture will be less and it will be good to bat. Not getting a win has put pressure on us. One win will bring in more. Good to see almost 18000 young hearts. This game is special for us. Surya comes back in place of Naman, Romario comes in for Maphaka and Nabi comes in place of Brevis

2.50pm There is a chance Mitchell Marsh might miss out today due to an injury. Jhye Richardson is getting his cap in the Delhi Capitals huddle, and so is Kumar Kushagra. For their first two games, Mumbai Indians opted for the extra spin option in Shams Mulani, but brought in Akash Madhwal for their first home game of the season and he has done well. It will be interesting to see how Mumbai go about with their Impact Player sub.

Here's S Sudarshanan from the venue. Good afternoon from the Wankhede! It is quite hot but not unbearable. It's Mumbai Indians' annual ESA Day. And so there are queues of kids outside every gate, waiting to get in. Some of those are inside the premises in a queue, waiting for goodie bags before heading up to the stands. The enthusiasm among them all is unmissable with chants in support of MI and Rohit Sharma keeping them company in their wait.

Ishan: "Nuwan Thushara got a Hat-trick on his last T20I against Bangladesh. Worth a try for Mumbai? "

2.40pm Mumbai fans, some good news first up. Looks like Suryakumar Yadav is fit and ready tp play. He is doing some batting drills, speaking with coach Mark Boucher. Hardik Pandya is also close to the boundary lines, taking throwdowns. Ishant Sharma meanwhile is having a chat with Jasprit Bumrah. On the subject of Suryakumar, S Sudarshanan did some SKY watching on the eve of the game. Here's what he found out.

Hari : "As a MI fan, we are in for a fight today. Get the history erased, score 300 and instill fear."

Aprameya: "Looking forward to see Sky bat today"

2.30pm Happy IPL double-header day. Can Mumbai Indians finally get on board? Is Suryakumar Yadav match fit? Can Delhi Capitals score a second win of the season? Will Hardik Pandya get some Mumbai love? Hello and welcome to the ball-by-ball commentary of match number 20 between Mumbai and Capitals. I am Ashish Pant and will soon be joined by Shashank Kishore as we look to answer all the questions. Hang in there, it should be a fun ride.

postText:
Thanks so much for joining us. Look forward to your company for LSG v Titans that has already begun in Lucknow. For now, this is Shashank Kishore signing off on behalf of Ashish Pant, Thilak Gowda and the rest of our crew.

Time for the presentations

Romario Shepherd is the PoM for 39 off 10 balls along with the wicket of David Warner. "Yeah, it made me proud, my hard work has paid off. Hardik told me to express myself on his way out. In these situations, got to just keep eyes on the ball. Don't need to be tentative. Keep a clear mind."

Hardik Pandya: "I would like to have this feeling [of being winning captain[] more often than not. Lot of hard work, hard to clear our minds, and everything clicked. We will be making some tactical changes here and there but more often than not this will be our XII. Settling of the team is important. There was a lot of love and care going around, everyone knows we lost three games but the belief and backing was there, everyone believes we needed just one win and today was the start. I mean amazing, to start with 77 after six is always wonderful. The way everyone was batting, we needed rhythm to bat, the way everyone is chipping in with the opportunity coming in was fantastic. That was some hitting from Romario, he won us the game. The difference was his innings. I like him, he always has a smile of his face, doesn't run away, very proud of the way he played, proud of the team. All good, will be bowling at the right time. Had it covered, so didn't need to roll my arm over."

Ishan Kishan: "We played to potential, this is what we're known for. Kept the process going, we were in a good headspace and got the result we were looking for. Played enough games here, not easy after six overs, more of a rotation game after that, so power play was important for both of us to take the bowlers on and we executed in a very good way. Romario has been working very hard, wasn't playing but was giving his 100% at the net sessions. That was the kind of over we were looking forward to. We know he's very powerful and it changed the game. I'm feeling very good, lot of meetings going on, talking to the coaches, we knew we had to bowl well."

Hardik Pandya & co doing a lap of honor around the ground to thank the 18,000 kids who turned up to watch them play as part of Reliance's CSR initiatives. All the members of the squad are right there - Hardik., Tendulkar, even the owners.

7.20pm Mumbai Indians were challenged briefly, but the carnage at the end of their batting innings by Romario Shepherd proving to be the difference. Capitals conceded 92 off the last four overs. They'd look back at that as a massive turning point and a momentum changer in the match.

Rishabh Pant: "I feel we didn't have enough runs in the Powerplay. Yes, tried to change it afterwards but when pressure mounts on you with asking rate crossing 15-16, it's very difficult. One over here and there can change the momentum, either we can look to play the blame game or look to improve on that. The wicket was good to bat on, slower ones were sticking on the wicket. Will look to improve power play [batting] and death bowling."

preText:
A false start because Umesh has run in too quickly, The umpire and de Kock did not seem ready. So, we go again...

7:27pm The two umpires make their way out to the middle. GT are in a huddle, and look up for the fight. de Kock and Rahul will open the batting for the hosts, and they would want to get LSG off to a strong start. de Kock on strike, as Umesh prepares for his new-ball gambit - here we go!

Anonymous: "Hopefully LSG can break their losing streak against GT today!"

7:20pm Just about ten minutes to go for the first ball. GT have put all of their eggs into the bowling basket, and are playing three front-line overseas bowlers. LSG not changing what is not broken, and will be defending a total for the third time this season.

NAGARAJAN: "GT could have played Sai Kishore in place of Vijay Shankar as Sai can bat a bit also and contain some runs while bowling." -- They already have six bowling options, plus Rahul Tewatia and Vijay Shankar. Another bowling option might have left their batting a little light.

Gujarat Titans XI: Shubman Gill (c), Sai Sudharsan, Vijay Shankar, BR Sharath (wk), Rahul Tewatia, Rashid Khan, Darshan Nalkande, Noor Ahmad, Umesh Yadav, Spencer Johnson, Mohit Sharma

GT bench: Abhinav Manohar, Matthew Wade, Kane Williamson, Manav Suthar, Jayant Yadav

Lucknow Super Giants XI: Quinton de Kock, KL Rahul (c & wk), Devdutt Padikkal, Marcus Stoinis, Nicholas Pooran, Ayush Badoni, Krunal Pandya, Ravi Bishnoi, Yash Thakur, Naveen-ul-Haq, Mayank Yadav

LSG bench: Arshad Khan, M Siddharth, Deepak Hooda, Amit Mishra, Yudhvir Singh

7pm It's time for the toss. Rahul and Gill are out in the middle. Heads is the call by Gill, and it comes down as tails. LSG will bat first. Rahul says it is a good wicket. Batting first has been working for them, and they are confident about it. Adds this is the first time he has realised they have not won against GT and they are not really thinking about it. Same team for LSG. He also talks about Mayank Yadav, and says he is very professional in the way he goes about his cricket and his routine and that it is important for them to manage him.

Gill says he would have bowled first anyway, so he is happy with the toss. Adds that they were on top for 32-33 overs but that happens in T20 cricket. Couple of injuries. Saha misses out with a back spasm, with BR Sharath making his debut. Spencer Johnson comes back in too. Says everyone drops catches but it is about always looking forward to the next game.

Over in Mumbai, the five-time champions are well in control against the Delhi Capitals, with the latter needing 82 off 24, as things stand. You can follow all the live action here.

Let's see what the conditions have in store for us. We have moved on to pitch no. 5. Equidistant square boundaries - 66m to each side. 75m hit down the ground. The shortest and longest pocket are 60m and 79m, respectively. The pitch looks hard and Matthew Hayden proves that by banging his knuckles into the turf. He reckons it might be an innings of two halves. It will not be easy work but it the batting conditions will be great with the ball coming on. As the ball gets softer, though, it could get tougher.

6:30pm The last time these sides met in Lucknow, the Titans huffed and puffed their way to 135-6, led by Hardik Pandya's 50-ball 66. Mohit Sharma then turned up with the ball to stifle the Super Giants, helping the Titans win by seven runs.

6:25pm The Lucknow Super Giants versus the Gujarat Titans. A side that has fallen short at the Eliminator twice in succession, against an outfit that has reached the final in both years of its existence. A team with lofty ambitions, up against a franchise that has already gotten to where LSG would want to be.

In one corner, a power-packed batting unit, studded with stars throughout; in the other, an ensemble cast that continues to do what is asked of them. On one side, there is a young fast bowler, all of 2 IPL games old, terrorizing batters with his raw pace. And in the opposition, a veteran who keeps unfurling his bag of tricks with guile, poise and precision.

Then, there is a captain who is relatively experienced in the IPL (and has led India), and another who has just started out. A team that could barely win at home, against a side that travelled so well in 2023 (winning six out of their seven away league fixtures).

This might seem a contest of contrasts. But what ties these two franchises together, apart from when they first ventured into the IPL arena, is that they are on four points, and would love two more. Two points that will ensure they end the weekend in the top four, and will allow them to continue dreaming big.

Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of the IPL. This is Match 21, and we are back in Lucknow. LSG have only ever won three matches at this venue, and they have never beaten the Titans in the IPL. An 0-4 record usually hints at a lopsided rivalry, but LSG would be out to prove otherwise tonight. Hop on, this should be plenty of fun!

postText:
9:14pm And so, LSG stutter and stumble their way to 163. They were rocked early, losing de Kock and Padikkal to Umesh. Rahul and Stoinis then resurrected the innings. The former, though, was probably too cautious, scratching his way to 33 off 31 and perishing when he attempted a big stroke.

Stoinis fared better and registered a fifty, but he too could not carry on and give LSG the finishing kick they were after. Pooran did manage a 22-ball 32, while Badoni scored 20 off 11. But LSG, at this stage, will feel they have left a few runs out there.

As for GT, they will be largely pleased with their bowling effort. Umesh set the tone early and the spinners followed suit. Nalkande was a tad expensive but he did account for Stoinis and Rahul, which meant LSG were never able to generate the head of steam they were after. GT will be confident of chasing down 164, but they will also be mindful of the fact that LSG have never lost when defending 160-plus. Join us in a bit for the run-chase!

Umesh Yadav: (On his animated celebrations) The way the games are coming, and how I am bowling with the new ball, this was the first time I got two wickets back-to-back in the powerplay. What I worked on before the match, it worked out, so I was happy. My plan was to swing the ball. I feel that if the ball swings and if you can stick to your lines and lengths, that is the best way to get dismissals. That was what I was trying - to bowl in the right areas and to get it to swing. The wicket is a little spongy and there was a little bit of dew. I feel this (score) should be chaseable.

9:28pm Right. We are back. LSG, remember, have never lost defending a total in excess of 160. GT, though, have never lost to LSG. One of these records will be broken tonight. Which one will it be?

postText:
11:40pm That will be all from us, folks. We will be back again tomorrow as the Chennai Super Kings return to Chepauk, hoping to snap their two-game losing streak, against a Kolkata Knight Riders side that is firing on all cylinders. Until then, this is me (Shashwat) signing off on behalf of Sudeep and everyone else at ESPNcrcinfo. Goodnight and take care!

Yash Thakur, Player of the Match: I am very happy with my first five-wicket haul and my first POTM award. (On bowling to Gill) The plan we had for Gill, we had two fielders on the leg side. So, we sort of knew that he (Gill) would try to make room. Rahul bhaiya told me to stick to my plans and that we will get a wicket that way. Unfortunate for us that Mayank picked up an injury. But Rahul bhaiya told me that this is my day and that I will win the game for LSG. In the last two seasons, we had not won against them. We won today so we are very happy. (On which wicket was his favourite) Shubman's wicket.

KL Rahul, Lucknow Super Giants captain: (On LSG making defending totals an art) We will take the win. Not going to make too much out of it. For the young bowing group we have, helps when we bat first and they can assess the conditions. They have been adapting really well, so credit to them. (On not losing a game when defending 160-plus) It is a good record to have. But it is where we have played. We know how the wickets were, very low-scoring wicket and low-scoring ground. Having the home advantage obviously helps a bit. The same guys were playing last season as well, they have adjusted their roles and they are reading the wicket well. That is something I try to speak to them about in the nets and in practice, to help them make the right choices when the pressure is on. Hopefully we can continue. (Thoughts at the half-way stage) We knew very early that it (the pitch) was not as good as the other day. We were not trying to get to a particular score, and were just trying to bat and see how many we would get. We put up a score and then you expect the bowlers to do their job. All three spinners have been key for us. Sid (Siddharth) has done very well, he bowls a crucial part when he bowls with the new ball. He has shown great temperament and he has given us steady bowling in the first 2-3 overs. He has picked up wickets, but his job is to restrict runs. KP (Krunal Pandya) has played for so many years, and he is smart and knows how to bowl. Have played with Bishnoi also for a lot of years. Feels good to get off the mark (against the Titans).

Shubman Gill, Gujarat Titans captain: (On the conditions) I think it was a good wicket to bat on. just a poor batting performance by us. We got off to a decent start but we lost it in the middle overs and were never able to recover from that. (On the bowling) I think our bowlers were exceptional to restrict them to that score. We were looking at 170-180 but to restrict them, it was a tremendous effort. (On Miller) He is a player who can change the game at any time. We had a couple of injuries but irrespective, this total was gettable. (On his dismissal) It was the last over of the powerplay and I just wanted to capitalise. Everyone was up on the off side, I wanted to give himself room. The ball I got out to, I was trying to play it too square and missed it. (On Umesh Yadav) He is definitely someone who is very experienced. Darshan and everyone in the bowling attack did a good job.

Krunal Pandya: When I went in, I just played a couple of balls. I was having a chat with Pooran and the wicket was very good, and we felt we were 10-15 runs short. At the end of the day, what I do is knowing the batter's strengths and weaknesses and bowling according to that. On some days, it works. On others it does not. One of those days where I was able to execute what I wanted. It feels great the way we have been defending in the entire tournament. It gives that extra confidence. But see, at the end of the day, you have to go there every day and execute your plans and we have done well so far. (On Mayank Yadav's injury) I don't know what is happening. I had a brief chat and he seemed okay, which is a positive. Whatever conversation I have had, whatever we see, he has a good head on his shoulder. Really excited to see how his carer pans out.

11:11pm At the half-way stage, it might have seemed the Super Giants were a little par. As it turned out, they weren't, and much of it was down to how well they bowled. They were put under pressure early, with Gill and Sudharsan getting the Titans off to a decent start. Once the latter fell to Thakur on the final ball of the powerplay, though, things went south for the 2022 champions.

None of their middle-order batters got going, and they kept finding ways to get out. Williamson perished to a sensational catch, while some of the other batters' shot selection left a bit to be desired. Tewatia got a few boundaries away towards the end but that only reduced the margin of defeat, rather than acting as a catalyst for a turnaround.

Coming back to LSG, Thakur picked up his career-best IPL figures, finishing with a five-wicket haul. Krunal was also very impressive, giving away only 11 runs in four overs and accounting for three batters. Bishnoi and Naveen also chipped in, ensuring that LSG, once they got the momentum in their bowling innings, never relented.

wkt_text: PD Salt c Jadeja b Deshpande 0 (1m 1b 0x4 0x6) SR: 0.00
text: straight to point first ball! And Jadeja is not missing that. Perfect start for CSK. Deshpande with a wide ball outside off and he tried to drive, but plays it away from his body. The length wasn't right for the drive either, and CSK strike first ball.
preText:
Deshpande to Salt. One slip, one short fine leg, and mid-on and mid-off inside.

7.25pm The umpires are out. And the camera enters the CSK huddle showing Dhoni quietly observing Gaikwad leading the team talk. Rachin with a "lets go boys" before they break off.

VJ: "CSK should have left out Theekshana and retained Moeen. His off spin would be handy against Narine, V.Iyer and Rinku. Plus CSK has been wasting his hitting prowess by batting him so low." -- I think Theekshana will be an attractive new-ball option too in the powerplay against Salt and Narine. Either way, CSK will need to be proactive with their new-ball plans because KKR's opening combination has scored 236 runs in 137 balls this season!

Andre Russell having a chat: "I plan against specific bowlers. Things become easy when you do your homework. Can pick the right ball. (Against CSK) Will take it ball by ball, whether with ball in hand or bat. That's the mentality of the whole team. The management has been working on giving us confidence. There is no easy team in the IPL and so we can't think too far ahead."

KKR XI: PD Salt†, VR Iyer, SS Iyer*, SP Narine, A Raghuvanshi, AD Russell, RK Singh, Ramandeep Singh, MA Starc, VG Arora, CV Varun
Impact: Sakib Hussain, Suyash, Manish Pandey, Anukul, Gurbaz.

CSK XI: RD Gaikwad*, R Ravindra, AM Rahane, Sameer Rizvi, DJ Mitchell, RA Jadeja, MS Dhoni†, SN Thakur, Mustafizur Rahman, TU Deshpande, M Theekshana.
Impact: Dube, Moeen, Shaik Rasheed, Santner, Sindhu.

7pm, Toss update: CSK win the toss, and Gaikwad's first win. They will bowl. "Good toss to win, looks quite humid," Ruturaj says. "We will bowl first. We have confidence. We have lost by a few runs margin but it hasn't dented our confidence. We have had some forced changes too. Definitely trying to win. (Against KKR) They are playing good brand of cricket but we would like to focus on ourselves, do simple things right. Pathirana is not available, Deepak Chahar has a niggle. So we have Shardul back, Mustafizur back, and Rizvi.

"We would've bowled first too," Shreyas Iyer says. "The approach and attitude has impressed me. The way we have adapted and played fearless cricket...pure bliss. (KKR's poor record at Chepauk) It is history. That was completely different. Team has also changed. Now our character will decide how we play here. If we complicate, we will struggle. Our focus is on being in the present. Same team."

Dev: "The one change I would have made would have been to bring in Anukul Roy for Ramandeep. Anukul's two overs of spin in the first game were valuable, and last IPL he batted at least as well as whatever we have seen of Ramandeep. "

Pitch report: This is the same surface as the CSK vs RCB season opener, where CSK successfully chased down 174. Suggestions are that it is a batting surface with solid bounce for the seam bowlers. Remember, this is a relaid Chepauk surface from a couple of years ago after which spinners' effectiveness has reduced. No CSK spinner has taken a wicket here in IPL 2024.

Kannan: "Today I am expecting Ruturaj will fire, like the 2022 edition he took four matches to warm up and time for the real show"

6.43pm The KKR social media has been abuzz with pictures of Nitish Rana practicing. He missed the start of IPL 2024 due to a niggle, but his smiling face suggests he should get a game soon. But is it possible to keep out Angkrish Raghuvanshi, the talented right-hand batter who dazzled in their last outing? The teenager also has big dreams, and he wants to realise them "like no one has ever done before."

It was only last week that we were talking about how well balanced the CSK batting unit looks, but with a bit more evidence, we ask: is Gaikwad the anchor weighing CSK down?

Mustafa Moudi: "Since Chepauk traditionally supports Spin, its more suited to KKR than the home side because KKR's spin bowling is strong their CSK and Narine, as an opener, Loves to attack spinners too. So hope this surface doesnt support spin to have a neutral contest !!"

6.30pm Welcome to Chennai again as Chennai Super Kings face off against Kolkata Knight Riders. CSK have lost their last two games in IPL 2024 and if they get a hat-trick of defeats tonight, the way up will be challenging.

KKR, on the other hand, have had a rollicking start to the season with a 3-0 beginning, and the way their batters are going, no ground seems big enough to contain them. But the Chepauk is MS Dhoni's den, and with Mustafizur Rahman back with their squad, their bowling will be bolstered, and there are some CSK batters who would be licking their lips to face KKR's revered spinners. This is Sreshth Shah, and joining us soon is Shashank Kishore. Here's the match preview to get you warmed up.

postText:
Thanks for joining us. This is Shashank Kishore saying goodbye on behalf of Ashish Pant and Chandan Duroah. Cheers, take care.

11.01pm CSK have turned a banana peel of a chase into an absolute cruise at dewy Chepauk. Ravindra Jadeja led their turnaround after KKR set themselves up superbly in the Powerplay, and then with the bat, Gaikwad and Mitchell laid the foundation of a chase that they were always in control of. And that means, KKR have been consigned to their first defeat this season.

Ravindra Jadeja is PoM for his 3/18. "My title hasn't yet been verified, hopefully they'll give me one [laughs]. I always enjoy my bowling on this track. I was hoping the ball grips a little, if you bowl in the right areas with helps you. For visiting teams it takes time to settle in and plan, you hardly get 2-3 days, for a visiting team to come here, play and identify the surface is little difficult. We know our conditions better."

Ruturaj Gaikwad: Bit of nostalgia for me. My first IPL fifty, Mahi bhai was with me to finish the match. With Jinx injured, onus was on me to bat through, didn't want to put the youngsters in a difficult situation. Was a 150-160 wicket. Jaddu always comes in after the power play with momentum in the spin department. With this team, I don't really need to tell things to anyone. Everyone's in a great head space, Mahi bhai and Fleming are still around to take those calls. I wouldn't say mine is a slow start, in T20s there are times you nick off one or two balls, sometimes you need a bit of luck to get going, maybe something for experts to talk about, with my strike rate (laughs)."

Daryl Mitchell: "Always nice to play in front of a special crowd, pretty cool. When you know surface is on the slower side, it's about building a partnership and take it as deep as we could. He's world class, for me it's coming up with plans to put pressure on those guys. The way Rutu got the job out there was amazing to see. There was a bit of turn and bounce, for us it was about building partnerships and allow ourselves into a position to finish it off. I don't mind wherever I bat, here to win games of cricket and get the job done.

Shreyas Iyer, tonight's losing captain: It's deafening out here, will try to express how I'm feeling. We fell short in terms of assessing the wicket. Phenomenal start in the power play but we couldn't capitalize. Couldn't assess conditions, pitch completely changed after power play and to score runs, it wasn't easy. They know conditions pretty well, bowled according to their plan. It was tacky, wasn't easy to go big right from first ball. It changed tremendously after power play and the way we were trying to construct our innings, didn't go to plan. We take those learnings and move forward. We were in a comfortable place, thought 160-170 was a great score. That was our plan but when you lose consecutive wickets it's difficult to carry forward momentum. Have to go back to our drawing board and learn, just a matter of one match and one innings, glad it happened at the start of the tournament. When we go back, we know our home conditions pretty well, important to analyze and assess situations and make the best use of it.

text: huge appeal, and not given! This is an absolute peach first up. Threatens to shape in from leg on a length, only to pitch and deck away slightly. Opens up Head completely, and does him all ends up. Might have flicked the back leg on the way hence causing the noise. UltraEdge confirms there was bat involved, and had PBKS reviewed, Head would have been on his way! The keeper went up straightaway but there was not a lot of support from elsewhere.
preText:
7:27pm The umpires make their way out to the middle, and there is a roar from the crowd as the Punjab Kings fielders emerge. Head and Abhishek will open the batting, so no surprises there. Rabada to take the new ball - the first time he is doing so this season. Head on strike - here we go!

7:20pm Just about ten minutes to go for the first ball. SRH have batted first on two occasions; scoring 277 and following it up with a more sedate 162 against the Titans. What kind of batting innings do they have in store for us tonight?

Shrikant : "Why Rahul Tripathi is not in playing 11 this year?" -- SRH's top order seems stacked, with Abhishek, Head and Markram all in good form, with Klaasen to follow. Plus, Tripathi did look scratchy in their opening game against KKR.

Suresh: "Who will be the Impact Sub for SRH? Markande or Umran?" -- No specific news on that at the toss. Cummins did mention they were going in with the same team, which could mean Markande coming in when SRH bowl. That said, if there is pace and bounce in the surface, they could be tempted to bring in Umran.

Punjab Kings XI: Shikhar Dhawan (c), Jonny Bairstow, Jitesh Sharma (wk), Sam Curran, Sikandar Raza, Shashank Singh, Ashutosh Sharma, Harpreet Brar, Harshal Patel, Kagiso Rabada, Arshdeep Singh

PBKS bench: Prabhsimran Singh, Nathan Ellis, Tanay Thyagarajan, Rahul Chahar, Rishi Dhawan

Sunrisers Hyderabad XI: Travis Head, Abhishek Sharma, Aiden Markram, Heinrich Klaasen (wk), Shahbaz Ahmed, Nitish Kumar Reddy, Abdul Samad, Pat Cummins (c), Bhuvneshwar Kumar, T Natarajan, Jaydev Unadkat

SRH bench: Umran Malik, Mayank Markande, Washington Sundar, Glenn Phillips, Rahul Tripathi

7pm Right. It is time for the toss. Cummins and Dhawan are out in the middle. Dhawan gives the coin a flick. Heads is the call, and tails it is. Punjab Kings will bowl first. Dhawan says the pitch is likely to remain the same and they want to know what they are chasing. Adds they were lucky they won the last game and that there is no dependency on certain players, with everyone standing up. They are looking forward to another win today. Livingstone is still recovering, and hopefully he will be back for the next game.

Cummins says he would have bowled first too but on a new venue, he does not mind batting first. They are happy with how they are playing. It has been fun and exciting to be a part of, he says. Says they have lots of options with the new ball and at the death, and that is the reason he is bowling more in the middle overs.

6:50pm The last time these sides met, Shikhar Dhawan produced a magnificent unbeaten 99, putting together a 55-run final-wicket stand in the process. It was in vain, though, with Markram and Rahul Tripathi ensuring SRH cruised to an eight-wicket win.

The previous three games between these franchises have been won by the chasing team, and in the only IPL game at this venue, PBKS won batting second. Win the toss and bat second then? Toss in 10.

Nick: "You feel if Bairstow doesn't score runs today, he might get replaced" -- He has not gone big so far this IPL but he has looked in decent touch in his last two games. Maybe tonight's the night...

Pitch Report: Slightly skewed square boundaries tonight: 63m to one side, 70m to the other. 72m hit straight down the ground, with the shortest and longest pocket being 56m and 75m, respectively. Simon Katich reckons the pitch might play similar to how it did during the Punjab Kings-Delhi Capitals game. He says it is a very good wicket, calling it a 200-run pitch. It is rock hard and there is an even coverage of grass. He reckons SRH will enjoy batting on this, as will the Kings. There has not been a lot of dew in the past couple of days, and it might be the same tonight as well.

6:40pm Shashank Singh helped the Punjab Kings script a remarkable victory away to the Gujarat Titans just days ago. This, thus, is the perfect time to jump into this piece, tracing his journey every step of the way.

6:30pm There will be plenty of familiar faces across both camps. Jonny Bairstow and Shikhar Dhawan, who will likely open for the Punjab Kings tonight, donned the SRH orange once upon a time. Shashank Singh, PBKS' hero against the Gujarat Titans, and who made headlines at the auction (for no fault of his), like Bairstow, also made his IPL debut for SRH.

Flip it around, and Mayank Agarwal was one of two players PBKS retained ahead of the 2022 mega auction, only to be released a year later. Aiden Markram was not retained at all and found his way to SRH, where he has become a vital cog.

6:25pm ICYMI: Wanindu Hasaranga, who was bought by SRH to bolster their spin-bowling stocks, has been ruled out for the season, with Sri Lankan spinner Vijayakanth Viyaskanth replacing him.

6:20pm Four matches, four points. A win in their last game against the 2023 finalists, a 100% record at home, and a chance to get closer to table-toppers Rajasthan Royals: the circumstances that precede this contest and what is at stake, appear uncannily similar.

Both the Punjab Kings and the Sunrisers Hyderabad have points to prove too. Neither made the playoffs last year. In fact, it has been ten years since PBKS (Kings XI Punjab then) did so, whereas SRH last tasted playoff action in 2020.

These teams have traversed different paths up to this point, even winning their respective last encounters in contrasting fashion. But tonight, they are on a collision course, and only one will be able to emerge from this scuffle unscathed, making their fans rejoice tonight, and perhaps proclaiming to the rest of the IPL that they are the real deal in 2024.

Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of the IPL. It is Match 23, and the Punjab Kings are back at home, where they won their opening game and where they will play their next four matches. Up against them are the Sunrisers Hyderabad, who are yet to win on the road this season but have a 14-7 record against the Kings in the IPL. Grab your choice of food and drink, and jump on, this has all the makings of a humdinger!

postText: Lots to ponder for SRH at the time-out. They have played their hand early, with respect to the Impact Player. With this pitch also not looking as conducive to stroke-play as many thought, they might also want to recalibrate. With Klaasen yet to bat, though, they will feel they can get to their desired total. For PBKS, it will be about chipping away and ensuring SRH do not generate any momentum in these middle overs.

Harshal back for his second

Meanwhile in tennis, Sumit Nagal became the first Indian ever to win an ATP Masters 1000 match on clay (singles), and the first in 42 years to reach the Monte-Carlo masters main draw. How has a player ranked 638 in 2022 climbed to 93 (and rising) now? Find out, here.

Curran is very interested and he thinks there is bat involved. The PKS fielders get together, and they go upstairs. There is indeed a nick. A clear spike as the ball is next to the bat and Tripathi, in fact, seemed to walk as soon as PBKS reviewed it. Strange sequence of events, but what matters is that SRH are now four down!

preText: Unadkat is the last batter in
postText:
9:15pm An innings of two halves, really. In the first half, the ball was doing all sorts and PBKS reduced SRH to 66-4. They could not get rid of Nitish, though, and he stood tall, even as those around him perished. He registered his maiden IPL fifty and finished with 64 off 37. Samad, Shahbaz and Head also played cameos, and those knocks have helped SRH to get to 182, which did not seem llikely at the half-way stage.

Arshdeep was the standout bowler for the hosts. His last over went for 15 but with the new ball, he looked unplayable at times. He broke the back of SRH's top order, with a two-wicket over that included the scalps of Head and Markram. Arshdeep then returned later to rip out Samad and Nitish, ensuring that SRH did not threaten a 200-plus score.

Curran and Harshal picked up two wickets apiece, while Rabada accounted for Cummins. PBKS will be relatively happy with the score they have to chase. SRH, though, will also feel they can make a match out of this, especially if they start well. Join us in a bit for the run-chase!

Arshdeep Singh: There was some movement to start off with. It was a little sticky. Then the dew came in and the wicket settled a little bit. I was very happy till the third over. It was a really good day, was trying to stick to my plans and deliver for my team. Hitting boundaries straight is relatively easy than hitting it square, so trying to make the most of it, and tried to use the wicket. Tried to bowl into the wicket and bowl wide yorkers also.

text: length just outside off. A bit of shape away and Dhawan accounts for it, defending into the off side
preText: 9:28pm Right. We are back. Dhawan and Bairstow stride out to the middle. This powerplay could be pivotal, if the ball swings around like it did in the first innings. Bhuvneshwar with the new ball for SRH. Dhawan on strike - here we go!

back of a length on the stumps. Shashank tips it to short mid wicket and sets off for a single. The fielder takes his eyes off it and misfields, conceding the second in the process. Had he gathered cleanly, there might have been a run-out chance at the bowler's end
Raza clears the fence! Off-pace and to be fair, this is a half-tracker outside off. Raza waits for it and then shovels it over deep mid wicket!

shortText: Unadkat to Sikandar Raza, no run
text: slanted in on a length on middle and leg. Raza cuts himself off a little and pokes it towards mid wicket
preText: Around the wicket now

shortText: Unadkat to Sikandar Raza, no run
text: hard length, angling into middle and off. No room to work with for Raza and he prods it towards the bowler
back of a length on off. Raza jabs it towards mid off and hares across to the other end

shortText: Unadkat to Shashank Singh, no run
text: hard length, denying the batter any room on middle and leg. Shashank advances and taps it towards extra cover
banged in shorter on middle stump. Shashank gets into a bit of a tangle and miscues it towards fine leg

shortText: Shahbaz Ahmed to Shashank Singh, 1 run
text: full on the pads. Shashank comes forward and works it away towards deep mid wicket
preText: First look at spin this innings. Shahbaz to bowl the 12th. PBKS need 109 off 54. Required run-rate a tick over 12 runs per over

shortText: Shahbaz Ahmed to Sikandar Raza, 1 run
text: back of a length on leg stump. Raza waits for it and stabs it towards deep mid wicket

shortText: Shahbaz Ahmed to Shashank Singh, 1 run
text: fired into the pads again. Shashank tucks it away towards deep mid wicket

shortText: Shahbaz Ahmed to Sikandar Raza, SIX
text: pick the bones out of this one! Back of a length on leg stump, and Raza tears into it. Gets down on one knee and clatters it over deep square leg!

shortText: Shahbaz Ahmed to Sikandar Raza, no run
text: short and wide outside off. Raza tries to hit it too hard and ends up chopping it off the under-edge towards the keeper

shortText: Shahbaz Ahmed to Sikandar Raza, 1 run
text: fuller on off. Raza comes forward and pushes it towards deep extra cover
back of a length just outside off. Raza hops up onto his toes and runs it down to third man
preText: Cummins returns. He too is sensing the need to break this partnership now

text: shortish outside off. Shashank waits for it and dabs it to third man

shortText: Cummins to Sikandar Raza, no run
text: hard length just outside off. Raza tries to go inside out but is cramped for room. Clinked back to the bowler

shortText: Cummins to Sikandar Raza, no run
text: hard length outside off again. Raza hacks it back to the bowler
short and wide outside off. Raza laces this one but picks out the sweeper at deep cover point
Cummins cannot close out the over well! Back of a length, angling into off stump. Shashank gives himself ample room and knifes it past backward point for four!
preText: Just three runs off the over. Can Cummins close it out?
postText: A seven-run over is still not bad in the grander scheme of things. SRH have pushed the required run-rate to more than 13 per over, and PBKS, at this time-out, will need to figure out a plan to attack. Bhuvneshwar, Cummins and Natarajan will bowl four of the seven overs that remain. Whoever else bowls, might have to be taken down by PBKS

wkt_text: Sikandar Raza c †Klaasen b Unadkat 28 (38m 22b 2x4 2x6) SR: 127.27
text: Raza looks for the boundary, and perishes for the cause! Slower ball on a back of a length on off. Raza has decided a week early he wants to play the lap. Gets into position but the lack of pace meddles with his timing. Can only scoop it straight up, and Klaasen accepts the offering gleefully. Vital wicket for SRH!
preText: Unadkat to bowl. 92 needed off 42. PBKS might look to make this a big over. Around the wicket

text: back of a length on the pads. Jitesh works it into the square leg region and gets off the mark
preText: Jitesh is the new batter. When on song, he can clear the fence with ease. Unadkat stays around the wicket

text: hard length on leg stump. Shashank backs away and drops the ball into the off side for a sharpish single
dug in shorter outside off. Jitesh gets onto the back foot and heaves it over mid wicket for a couple of runs
slower bumper on middle and leg that just does not arrive. Jitesh has to wait an eternity before gloving it down to fine leg
preText: The longer boundary is to the right-hander's leg side this over

shortText: Unadkat to JM Sharma, no run
text: back of a length outside off. Jitesh goes feeling for it away from his body and the ball sneaks past the outside edge
back of a length outside off. Shashank throws his hands at it and toe-ends it down to third man
preText: Natarajan to bowl the 15th. PBKS need 86 off 36

text: shortish on off. Jitesh steps down the track and slaps it towards deep cover point
width outside off again. Shashank stands up tall to this back of a length ball and flays it towards deep cover point
Jitesh breaks free! Too much width outside off. Jitesh waits for the ball to arrive, throws his hands at it and carves it over extra cover!

shortText: Natarajan to JM Sharma, no run
text: banged into the track well outside off. Jitesh lets it go, hoping for the wide but does not get any favours
dug in again, outside off. Jitesh moves across and mows it towards deep mid wicket

shortText: Nitish Kumar Reddy to JM Sharma, 2 runs
text: another miscue, and Natarajan shells it! Back of a length, slanting into leg stump. Jitesh has a swipe at it and the ball goes straight up off the top edge. Natarajan circles under it nervously from third man and over-runs it in the end. Has to snatch at it to his left and he grasses it!
preText: Nitish back for his third. This is a massive over in the context of the game. 78 off 30

shortText: Nitish Kumar Reddy to JM Sharma, SIX
text: fetch that! Hard length outside off. Jitesh skips down the track, stands tall and boshes it over the long off fence!

shortText: Nitish Kumar Reddy to JM Sharma, 1 wide
text: back of a length delivery well down leg. Jitesh swings and misses. Called a wide

shortText: Nitish Kumar Reddy to JM Sharma, OUT
wkt_text: JM Sharma c Abhishek Sharma b Nitish Kumar Reddy 19 (11m 11b 1x4 1x6) SR: 172.72
text: Jitesh holes out, and Nitish rises to the occasion again! Slower bumper on leg stump that is actually begging to be hit. Jitesh tries to smash it into next week and swings too early. Gets it right off the toe-end and rather than flying over fine leg, it spoons up towards deep square leg. Abhishek comes running in off the fence, slides forward and completes the catch! PBKS keep slipping!

shortText: Nitish Kumar Reddy to AR Sharma, 1 run
text: short on leg stump. Ashutosh swivels on this slower bouncer and helps it down to fine leg
preText: Ashutosh and Shashank out in the middle together. Can they recreate their magic tonight?

shortText: Nitish Kumar Reddy to Shashank Singh, 1 run
text: slow, short and following the batter outside leg. Shashank swipes it towards deep square leg

shortText: Nitish Kumar Reddy to AR Sharma, no run
text: slower ball dug into the track just outside off. Ashutosh looks for the upper-cut but has no pace to work with. Fails to make contact
streaky but they all count! Back of a length outside off. Shashank throws the plumbing at it and the ball skews off the outside edge over short third!
preText: 67 needed off 24. PBKS need that 20-run over, right about now. Bhuvneshwar to bowl out

text: back to back boundaries! Goes for the wide yorker but errs on the shorter side. Shashank sits deep in his crease and cracks it past extra cover!
low full toss on the pads. Shashank can only flick it towards deep mid wicket. Just a single
back of a length outside off. Ashutosh hangs back deep and scuffs it down the ground to long off
third four in the over! PBKS are coming after SRH! Short, wide and put away. That much width is always asking for trouble and Shashank smacks it past extra cover!
gets the line right this time. Full enough to prevent Shashank from getting under it and he squeezes it out to deep backward point

full and wide again, beyond the tramlines. More exercise for the umpire. Klaasen is adamant it should not be a wide, and SRH review! Shashank has moved across his stumps, and the ball was only just beyond the tramlines. But the decision has been upheld. Not sure what Bhuvneshwar did wrong there, but the decision goes against SRH!
length delivery bowled a mile outside off, perhaps as a response to Shashank shaping for the scoop. Well beyond the tramlines and called a wide
hard length on off. Comes on quicker and hits the bat hard. Shashank shanks it towards deep mid wicket
preText: 50 off 18. This is still SRH's game to lose, but this pair, just a few days ago, pulled a win out of the fire for PBKS. Cummins to bowl the 18th

text: that has gone to the fence like a tracer bullet! Shortish outside off. Ashutosh picks the length early, backs away, stands tall and blasts it past deep cover point, who barely had to move a couple of yards, but still could not get there!
Ashutosh is toying with Cummins now! Slower short ball outside off. Ashutosh has read this like the morning daily too and ramps it over the keeper's head!
another off-pace ball, dug into the track on leg stump. Ashutosh is cramped for room and slogs it towards mid wicket
safe! Hard length outside off. Shashank tries to muscle it over long on but does not get all of it. On the bounce to long on

shortText: Cummins to AR Sharma, no run
text: full on middle and off. Ashutosh sits deep in his crease and smashes it straight to the fielder at mid off. Dot ball
nails the wide yorker first up. Shashank cannot get under it and digs it out towards deep backward point
preText: 39 off 12. Unadkat and Natarajan will likely bowl these overs. Natarajan it is. Over the wicket to Shashank

text: oh my days, this is a shot and a half! Natarajan bowls it a mile outside off. Ashutosh works it out in time and goes down on one knee. Fetches it from that wide line and clubs it to long on's right!
preText: 38 off 11. PBKS will not mind a four or a six here, just to put pressure on the bowler

shortText: Natarajan to AR Sharma, no run
text: right up in the blockhole on off. Ashutosh can only squeeze it out towards the bowler
another top wide yorker. Ashutosh plays with an open bat face and slices it towards deep backward point
innovation at its best! Low full toss well outside off. Shashank, like his partner, reads that line and shapes for the scoop. Gets enough on it and beats short fine leg!

shortText: Natarajan to Shashank Singh, no run
text: perfect yorker to end the over! Gets the length right, and also the line. Just inside the tramlines and Shashank, despite his best attempts to jam down, cannot do so in time

palmed over the bar! Final-over deja-vu! Half-tracker outside off and Ashutosh smashes the cover off this. Gets it right out of the middle and bludgeons it towards deep mid wicket, where Nitish helps it over the fence!
preText: 29 needed off the last over. Unadkat to bowl. Over the wicket. Surely SRH have enough in the bank?

text: palmed over the bar again, what is happening here in Mullanpur?! Right up in the slot on middle and off. Ashutosh lays back deep in his crease and snaps through the line, banging it towards long off, who pushes it over!
preText: 21 off 5 now
postText: Samad did not time the jump and SRH paid the price

text: slow, short and beyond the tramlines again on the off side. More exercise for the umpire, and Unadkat is feeling the pinch
and now the wide! The pressure is on! Wide yorker goes wrong and Unadkat sprays it way outside off. Called a wide
preText: Around the wicket

text: slower delivery dug into the track outside off. Ashutosh swings himself off his feet and drags it towards deep mid wicket. Scrambles back for two and makes it
another slower bumper outside off. Ashutosh gives it all he has but the lack of pace means he can only pull it on the bounce to deep mid wicket

dropped again, but the important bit is that this has not cleared the fence! Slower ball on a back of a length on off. Ashutosh waits an eternity for it before hoicking it towards deep mid wicket. Tripathi puts down the catch but it is just a brace
preText: 10 off 2 now

text: slow, short and outside the tramlines on the off side. Called a wide again. Oh my, this game is twisting and turning every moment!
preText:
11 off 2. A six and a four, and we go into a Super Over

Mohit: "No way these two are going to do it again, right?"
